<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 0026EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Emmys 6thLd-Writethru 2Takes 09-18 1177</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Emmys, 6th Ld-Writethru, 2 Takes, a0412,1205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to CORRECT typo, recast; breaks copy into two takes;
should stand for AMs.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos LA6,7,9,10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``L.A. Law'' and ``Cheers'' scored the
top series awards at the 41st Emmy awards Sunday night, which
honored series stars who portrayed a Vietnam nurse, a widower, a TV
reporter and a Southern cop.
   The 41st Annual Primetime Emmy Awards divided its honors evenly,
and miraculously ended seven minutes ahead of its three-hour
scheduled closing, the first time that has happened in a decade.
   ``War and Remembrance,'' which critics said took longer to show
than the Second World War it chronicled, won outstanding miniseries
and led a charge that stampeded favorite ``Lonesome Dove'' out of
town.
   The leading winners were ``Murphy Brown,'' CBS' TV newsroom
comedy; ``thirtysomething,'' the ABC yuppie drama series and the Fox
Network comedy-variety presentation ``The Tracey Ullman Show.'' Each
claimed four Emmys.
   Actress Colleen Dewhurst won two awards, both for guest
appearances.
   ``L.A. Law,'' which previously won as best dramatic series in
1987, repeated Sunday night as did ``Cheers,'' which was named best
comedy series previously in 1983 and 1984.
   CBS, third in the Nielsen ratings last season, collected the
honor for total awards with 27, followed by NBC with 25 and ABC with
13. The newcomer Fox Network claimed its first Emmys for a total of
four.
   The predicted sweep for the epic western miniseries ``Lonesome
Dove'' did not materialize. It won only a single Emmy on the
broadcast for director Simon Winser, adding to its six awards during
the technical academy presentation Saturday night. It had 18
nominations.
   ``A major shock,'' exclaimed ``War and Remembrance'' producer Dan
Curtis, whose 12-part miniseries aired over 17 hours and 25 minutes
in November 1988 and 11{ hours in May 1989. Its budget was estimated
at a record $100 million.
   The miniseries continued the saga writer Herman Wouk began in the
novel and miniseries ``The Winds of War,'' beginning one week after
Pearl Harbor. It concerned the wartime lives of the family of naval
Capt. Victor ``Pug'' Henry.
   ``It took longer than World War II, I know,'' Curtis said in his
acceptance. ``I want to thank ABC for having the guts to pony up the
dough for this.''
   James Woods, the founder of Alcoholics Anonymous in ``My Name Is
Bill W.'' and Holly Hunter, who won a pro-choice verdict from the
U.S. Supreme Court in ``Roe Vs. Wade'' were named outstanding stars
of a miniseries or special.
   Woods, who won an Emmy two years ago for ``Promise,'' told the
Pasadena Civic Auditorium and Fox Broadcasting audience that he
considered it ``truly an honor to play the man I consider a saint.''
   In her remarks, Miss Hunter, who was nominated for an Oscar as
the frantic producer in ``Broadcast News,'' thanked the real Jane
Roe, Norma McCorvey, ``for continuing to keep women from being
second-class citizens, and for refusing to give up her right for a
reproductive choice.''
   ``Roe vs. Wade'' also was a co-winner as outstanding drama-comedy
special, sharing the Emmy with ``Day One,'' an account of the
development of the first atomic bomb.
   The award for ``Day One'' was the first one for its co-executive
producer Aaron Spelling, producer of ``Dynasty,'' ``Charlie's
Angeles,'' ``Love Boat'' and other such shows.
   Dana Delany won her Emmy for best actress in a dramatic series
playing the compassionate nurse in the Vietnam war series ``China
Beach,'' and Carroll O'Connor won his for the crusty officer of ``In
The Heat of the Night.''
   Miss Delany appeared stunned by her win over Susan Dey and Jill
Eikenberry of ``L.A. Law,'' Angela Lansbury of ``Murder, She Wrote''
and Linda Hamilton of ``Beauty and the Beast.''
   ``I'd like to thank the women who served in Vietnam. I will never
know what it was like to have been there. I would like to thank you
for sharing your experiences and allowing me to pay you the tribute
you so greatly deserve,'' she said.
   O'Connor was near Covington, Ga., where the third season of ``In
the Heat of the Night'' is being shot. He is executive producer this
year as well as star this year.
   O'Connor was reading a book on Civil War generals Grant and Lee,
and was dozing off when he got word of his Emmy via a telephone call.
   ``That's a surprise. I'm pleased to have won four Emmy awards in
the comedy field (``All In The Family'') , and now to win one in the
dramatic field is a great delight. I am surprised.''
   Candice Bergen, as the hard-driving reporter in ``Murphy Brown''
was a popular winner. She closed her acceptance with a comment,
``Dad, if you're watching, this is for you.'' Her late father,
ventriloquist Edgar Bergen, was the founding president of the
Academy of Television Arts and Sciences.
   Veteran comic actor Richard Mulligan of ``Empty Nest,'' who had
previously won for his zany role in ``Soap'' in 1980, also won
hearty applause from the audience.
   He thanked fellow actors, including Bear the dog and his trainer,
and dedicated his Emmy to the late Cathryn Damon, who won an award
as his wife in ``Soap,'' and later died of cancer.
   An ecstatic Tracey Ullman came on stage with her eight
co-producers to claim the award for outstanding variety, music or
comedy program for ``The Tracey Ullman Show.''
   Miss Dewhurst won her second Emmy in two nights for a supporting
performance and British actor Derek Jacobi was selected outstanding
supporting actor in a miniseries or special.
   Miss Dewhurst, a distinguished Broadway performer, was named
Saturday night for outstanding guest actress in a comedy series as
Miss Bergen's mother in ``Murphy Brown.'' She added another Emmy on
Sunday as supporting actress in a miniseries or special for her role
as Margaret Page in the NBC special ``Those She Left Behind.''
   Jacobi was chosen for playing the impostor G.I. in Hallmark Hall
of Fame's ``The Tenth Man.''
   The television academy governor's special award went to the late
Lucille Ball. Her frequent co-star Bob Hope entered to a standing
ovation and introduced a string of film clips from Miss Ball's
career, which included the television shows ``I Love Lucy,'' ``The
Lucy Show,'' and ``Here's Lucy.''
   ``Lucy loved her work and loved the television industry,'' said
the comedian's widower, Gary Morton, in accepting the award. ``You
made the Lucy I love very happy, and she would have been very
touched by this symbol.''
   ``Cheers'' won best comedy series, and shy bartender Woody
Harrelson and brassy barmaid Rhea Perlman, both laboring at the
television tavern, won best supporting players in a comedy series.
   ``This really puts you in a good mood,'' exclaimed Miss Perlman,
who claimed her fourth Emmy in the supporting category. She thanked
her fellow performers and exited as the camera focused on her
beaming husband, Danny DeVito.
   Harrelson was not present at the awards in the Pasadena Civic
Auditorium, but a clever ``dramatization'' using his still portrait
with the lips electronically manipulated to express his gratitude.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
