<FIRST>r a PM-Emmys-Review     09-18 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Emmys-Review,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Emmy Awards Prove Painless, Contain Miracle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There should be an Emmy for Sunday's prime-time
Emmy awards show. It was workmanlike, had some funny bits, some
surprises, and moved along smartly for the most part. It also
included a miracle.
   It ended five minutes early.
   Never, ever have I seen this happen with an awards show,
particularly the Emmy awards show. It tends to be television's
equivalent of the Long March. Not so Sunday's 41st annual exercise
in tube tribute.
   Broadcast by Fox Broadcasting, the two-hour, 55-minute Emmyganza,
conducted on a set full of stylized, blue and mauve mockups of old
TV sets, was a model of painless awarding.
   Produced by John C. Moffitt and Pat Tourk Lee, and crisply
directed by Walter Miller, Sunday's show could have been a nightmare
in nostalgia, having warned beforehand that it would have a
50th-anniversary-of-TV theme.
   But the clips of TV's past and present were well-chosen. They
were run in various well-edited categories, such as TV wives, where
one could marvel at the contrast between yesteryear's very proper
``The Donna Reed Show'' with today's rowdy ``Married...With
Children.''
   The acceptance speeches, by and large, were over with quickly,
and only one acting winner, Dana Delany of ABC's ``China Beach,''
was heard to say, ``I would first like to thank my agent.''
   And, while ``Lonesome Dove'' star Robert Duvall, an Emmy
presenter, predictably joked about poking along, there was an
amazing development as the night wore on. It had been thought that
CBS' high-rated Old West miniseries would get the major Emmys. It
didn't, save for best-direction honors.
   Early on, the Emmy show took sly digs at such things as the bits
of ``simulation'' and story ``dramatization'' that this year have
slipped into some network news programs.
   Example: Robert Altman wasn't on hand for his Emmy for directing
``Tanner '88.'' However, Duvall told viewers, ``ABC has been kind
enough to furnish us with an exclusive acceptance simulation.''
   There ensued a black-and-white videotaped scene of street corner
late at night. There, a lady in a trench coat furtively slipped the
Emmy to a man in a trench coat. There was no time code running on
the videotape, so I'm inclined to think it was from ABC's
enterainment division or something.
   Not all the joshing of AWOL awardees worked, though. One, for
absent winner Carroll O'Connor, had an actor mumbling from within
his knight's suit of armor. That made no sense, not even for TV.
   But on balance, Emmy night was a pretty good night, as these
things go, with Milton Berle closing it by reminding those who
didn't win to ``just remember, there's always radio.''
   Fox, which filched Emmy night from the CBS, NBC and ABC networks
and now has broadcast it three consecutive years, must decide
whether to re-up for a fourth year or yield this festival of statues
back to the big three.
   No matter what happens, remember one thing: On Sunday night,
Emmys awards in separate categories even went to the Grammy and Tony
award shows of last season.
   If they can give awards to other award shows, maybe next year
they can give an Emmy for Sunday's show. That might sound strange,
an awards show awarding itself for achievement.
   But that is the magic of television.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Jay Sharbutt has been covering television since
1972.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
