<FIRST>r p PM-Wilder-Democrats Bjt   09-18 0791</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wilder-Democrats, Bjt,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wilder Minimizes Race as He Tries to Make History</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Marye in 4th graf cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Virginia Lt. Gov. L. Douglas Wilder, trying to
become the nation's first black elected governor, says his bid for
office should be viewed as an ``arithmetic progression'' rather than
a referendum on his race.
   Sitting in his campaign headquarters in suburban McLean, Va.,
Wilder insisted that his election would send a message ``more
important'' than trumpeting the success of a black man from
Richmond, capital of the old Confederacy.
   At the same time, it was clear during a recent interview that
Wilder is aware of the historical significance of his spot at the
head of the Democratic ticket in a state capital where blacks were
for so long barred from the political and social corridors of power.
   He talked of how a close friend, State Sen. Madison Marye, a
white man with a rich Southern drawl, quipped that ``my grandfather
was a Confederate army captain ... and your granddaddy was a slave.''
   Still, he shies away from emphasizing race.
   ``The important thing is that it sends a message that says you
don't have to be connected politically, you don't have to be born to
money,'' Wilder said.
   And that, he said, is a worthwhile message for young people of
all races.
   ``You see, a lot of times, unfortunately, everyone believes the
other guy's got it made: `I'm the only one that has a hard time
because I'm black, but every white person in the world has got it
made,''' he said. ``And you know, I don't have to tell you, it's
silly.''
   Determined to stake out his own identity _ one not marked by race
_ Wilder said he does not want Jesse Jackson to campaign for him as
he seeks to move from No. 2 to No. 1 in Virginia.
   ``It's not a rejection of Jackson,'' he said. ``I think Jesse is
an activist. ... I have been involved with compromises _ getting
half the loaf when you couldn't get the whole loaf. I don't want to
walk away empty-handed.''
   Wilder said his style of political accommodation with adversaries
``forces you to a broader constituency'' and that while serving as
the only black in the Virginia Senate, he came under pressure
``because people thought I was representing black Virginia.''
   But times have changed in the state, he said, ``so that what you
have now is what I call a new mainstream, and I'm a part of it.''
   ``Most people that I come in contact with are interested in where
we go from here,'' he said. ``(They) don't give a rip about the
past. ... It's rather poetic, and ironic.''
   He does plan to have comedian Bill Cosby appear at a fund-raising
event _ ``because he's an entertainer'' _ but is not having any
political figures from outside.
   Wilder said that attempts by Republican opponent J. Marshall
Coleman to depict him as a Michael Dukakis-type liberal won't work.
   ``I'm not a Mike Dukakis,'' he said. ``I have a record and a
proven record. The American people really never knew Dukakis. And
this has nothing to do with disparaging Michael Dukakis.''
   Wilder supported Dukakis for president last November, but stayed
neutral during the primary season. Jackson won the Virginia
Democratic presidential primary without Wilder's help.
   As he campaigns against Coleman _ a former attorney general with
a youthful, telegenic appearance _ Wilder acknowledged that he is
confronted with whispers that his efforts will be undermined by a
Labor Day weekend disturbance, mostly involving young blacks, in
Virginia Beach, Va.
   Asked whether his campaign would suffer because of the riots and
looting, Wilder replied, ``If I was an unknown quantity, maybe yes.
But people know me. They know that I would not tolerate that
nonsense ... and they don't look at me as a black lieutenant
governor. ... Somebody outside Virginia, who wouldn't know, might
think that.''
   Except for plenty of white hair showing the passage of time,
Wilder at 58 looks much the same as he did 20 years ago when first
elected to the Virginia Senate.
   He complained of news accounts resurfacing about a story that
arose during his 1985 campaign for lieutenant governor _ accounts of
his ownership of an allegedly dilapidated building in Richmond.
Wilder denied anew that the building was a slum, said no one had
been living there, that he had it repaired and transferred the
mortgage to a trust with himself as the beneficiary, to put the
issue behind him.
   He said the building never was cited as a ``public nuisance,''
despite a grand jury investigation, and insisted he had gone
undergone intense press scrutiny on the matter.
</TEXT>
