<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Ethnic Bjt   09-18 1075</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Ethnic, Bjt,1117</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Soviet Ethnic Dilemma: Why the Meskhetians Can't Go Home.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATSKURI, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Where the Kura River broadens from its
forested gorge into Meskhetia's tan fields, eight Soviet Georgians
wielding clubs block any ethnic Turks seeking to return to their
homeland.
   Policemen at a nearby checkpoint are happy for the help, just in
case the next bus is packed with Meskhetian Turks bent on violence
against Meskhetian Georgians.
   ``We don't know how many there will be, and if they'll be armed
or not,'' one officer said on condition of anonymity.
   Three hundred years as a Turkish province split Meskhetia, a
region in southern Georgia, into Georgian-speaking Christians and
Turkish-speaking Moslems.
   Then, in 1944, Josef Stalin had the Turks packed into cattle cars
and deported to Uzbekistan in Central Asia.
   Despite the officer's fears, it is the Turks who have been hacked
to pieces and burned alive in recent months. A pogrom in Uzbekistan
in June claimed 100 lives and sent thousands fleeing.
   But even after being uprooted for the second time in 45 years,
the Turks are barred from returning home. The Georgians and
Armenians living in Meskhetia are worried that an influx of Turks
might stir up centuries of Moslem-Christian feuding.
   Somehow, President Mikhail S. Gorbachev must resolve this
deadlock _ and at least 40 other deep-rooted ethnic conflicts
between the more than 130 nationalities peopling the Soviet Union _
if he hopes to hold the country together.
   On Tuesday, the Communist Party's policy-making Central Committee
opens a meeting devoted to ethnic problems following months of
strikes and ethnic unrest that for some Soviets herald the breakup
of the empire.
   The disputes are territorial, they involve political power, or
are matters of language, independence, religion, culture.
   Gorbachev has promised a special meeting of the party leadership
to solve the ethnic problems that have raged for more than 1{ years
since Azerbaijani-Armenian rioting in February 1988 that claimed 31
lives.
   On Aug. 17, the party issued its proposed solution, which was to
give more power to the republics and regions long dominated by
Moscow. The document also calls for legal guarantees of minority
rights and local self-government for small ethnic groups.
   There was not a word about the specific complaints of the peoples
of many regions in turmoil, including Meskhetia.
   ``We personally saw nothing there for us,'' Ibragim Medzhidoglu,
a Turkish refugee from Uzbekistan, said of the document.
   More power to autonomous republics would be helpful if the Turks
dominated Meskhetia, ``but the territory is closed to us,'' he said
in Moscow.
   While Communist leaders cast about for compromises, hundreds of
Meskhetian Turks are virtually camped in the once-tidy reception
area of the government Presidium in Moscow, where they make daily
appeals for aid. Most are among the 35,000 Meskhetians who fled the
violence in Uzbekistan.
   The petitioners are now adrift in the Soviet system with no jobs
and no homes, but with a fierce desire to return to Meskhetia.
   National authorities moved quickly to protect the Meskhetians
from well-organized attackers in Uzbekistan. Since then, they have
offered the Meskhetians refugee camps in the neighboring republic of
Azerbaijan, or cottages in central Russia and Byelorussia abandoned
by peasants moving to cities, said one man on condition of anonymity.
   ``Our goal is a peaceful route to regaining our homeland,'' he
said.
   The Meskhetians have been pleading to return to Georgia for
decades, signing hundreds of petitions. But returning is not as
simple as rescinding Stalin's order, which shipped more than 150,000
Meskhetian Turks to Central Asia in November 1944. Stalin allegedly
was convinced that Turkey was about to attack.
   Soviet residency permits are still tightly controlled, and tied
to existing jobs and scarce apartments.
   The Meskhetian Georgians _ some of whom moved into the Turks'
former homes _definitely don't want them back. They say their former
neighbors were also old enemies in a Moslem-Christian conflict based
more on rival cultures than on religion, and they recall relatives
killed and terrorized by the Turks.
   ``They killed, they robbed, they raped,'' said Avtandil
Diasamidze, an older man in the village of Vale. ``It was impossible
for a wife to take food to her husband working in the fields,
because the Turks would attack her.''
   Meskhetia was the cradle of Georgian civilization but became a
province of the Ottoman Turkish Empire for 300 years until the
Russian czar took over in the early 19th century.
   The landscape is a constant reminder of the conflict, with its
ruined watchtowers and mountaintops denuded of forests, reportedly
by Turks trying to burn out Georgian partisans hiding in the trees.
   Since the Moslem preference for large families has multiplied the
Meskhetian Turks to 360,000, compared to the 200,000 Christian
residents of Meskhetia, some Turks say their majority gives them the
right to demand the area be separated from Georgia.
   ``If we are allowed back, we will ask for autonomy,'' said Sattar
Iskandarov, a Meskhetian studying in Moscow who is taking part in
the vigil at the Presidium office.
   Some Turkish activists have even called for deporting Georgians
so the Turks can replace them, said Shalva Shanidze, Communist Party
chief in Akhaltsike, the largest city in Meskhetia.
   ``Why solve the first mistake with another?'' he said.
   A pre-pogrom plan to return several hundred Meskhetian Turkish
families to Meskhetia was scrapped after Georgians heard that some
Turks planned to demand autonomy, Shanidze said.
   ``Friction started when the Turks came and saw people had been
living for 45 years in their houses,'' Shanidze said. ``They came
and said, `This is our home. Throw them out.'''
   Besides, Shanidze said, ``we don't have enough land'' to support
hundreds of thousands of new residents, most of them farmers
demanding at least a garden plot if not fields to lease.
   With the way to their homeland blocked, some Meskhetian Turks are
seeking to emigrate to Turkey if the Soviet government will allow it.
   Sevki Mutevellioglu, first secretary of the Turkish Embassy in
Moscow, said 5,000 to 10,000 Meskhetians are seeking Soviet exit
visas to emigrate.
   ``To refuse them is out of the question,'' he said, even though
Turkey is already overwhelmed by refugees as Bulgaria expels tens of
thousands of its own ethnic Turks.
   Iskandarov, who wants to go to Turkey, said the violence in
Uzbekistan has left him with no faith that the Meskhetian Turks will
ever have a safe home among the Soviet people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
