<DOCNO> AP890918-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 0131EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-SovietBanks     09-18 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Soviet Banks,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Embargoed for use 10 a.m. EDT; time set by source</HEAD>
<HEAD>Banks Ask International Bodies to Help Markets in Eastern Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spokesman for major banks around the world is
urging the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund to get
together to aid market forces in the Soviet Union and its east
European allies.
   ``The IMF and the World Bank should make a concerted effort to
promote change,'' said Horst Schulmann, managing director of the
Washington-based Institute of International Finance, which includes
major banks in the United States, Britain and other leading
financial countries.
   The IMF and World Bank are owned by 151 governments, with the
United States taking a major role in both. China and some East
European governments are members, but not the Soviet Union.
   ``These institutions can do more, particularly in advising how to
replace administrative controls with market mechanisms and through
the funding of structural adjustment efforts,'' Schulmann said.
   ``The IFC (International Finance Corp.) can also be helpful by
bringing together foreign investors and local enterprises,'' he said.
   The IFC, a part of the World Bank that lends to private business
rather than governments, already invests in Poland, Hungary and
Yugoslavia as well as in China. It also has a growing interest in
helping privatize industry owned by governments.
   Schulmann's statements were in a letter dated Sept. 12 to leaders
of World Bank and IMF, which also is headquartered in Washington.
Schulmann, a West German, was an adviser to former Chancellor Helmut
Schmidt.
   Schulmann's letter was made public today as representatives of
leading banks and the 151 governments began gathering for annual
meetings that will go on until the end of the month. Treasury
Secretary Nicholas F. Brady will be the chief U.S. representative,
and a speech from President Bush is on the schedule.
   Developments in eastern Europe are expected to be among the
topics. Another will be international debt and Brady's proposal for
reducing its burden on debtor countries. Poland and Yugoslavia are
among the major problem debtors.
   Member countries also will try to make progress on increasing the
fund's $118 billion in assets, which Managing Director Michel
Camdessus wants to see doubled.
   In recent years the fund's money has been used to help debtor
countries improve their financial positions. In a speech on
Thursday, Camdessus spoke of prospects for change in eastern Europe.
   ``This promises to be a major transformation which, if
successful, will bring large benefits, but there are serious
risks,'' he said. ``The challenge to these countries and to those
who should help them are enormous. What is certain, is that here we
must not fail.''
   Helping the Soviet Union and its allies adapt to western ways was
proposed last week as the task for the fund during the 1990s, in a
study by two U.S. experts. They were Catherine Gwin of the
Rockefeller Foundation and Richard E. Feinberg, executive vice
president of the Overseas Development Council, a private research
group. Both are former State Department officials.
   The World Bank's annual report, published Sunday, said a greater
role for markets in eastern Europe would mean a basic change of the
economic system. In many cases privatization would not be needed,
but rather competition where none existed before, it added.
   ``Trade reform and an opening of the economy to foreign
competition is often an important element in this process,'' it
said. ``Systemic reform in the socialist economies of the region
perhaps offers the greatest of challenges, given the major
structural changes required within their economies.''
</TEXT>
