<FIRST>r a PM-ArsenalWhistleblowers     09-18 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arsenal Whistleblowers,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilots Under Fire at Rock Island Arsenal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCK ISLAND, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two pilots who blew the whistle on
safety violations at the Rock Island Arsenal say they've been
grounded, discredited, and assigned to minor jobs in reprisal.
   The Army credits the two civilian pilots, Curt McRae, 40, and
Lloyd Williams, 50, with providing evidence that led to improvements
in safety, but arsenal officials deny any action has been taken to
punish the pilots.
   McRae's supervisors said he was grounded because of mental
instability, a claim McRae denies.
   ``I spent 13{ months in Vietnam with the Marines. That was a
cakewalk compared to what I've gone through at the arsenal,'' McRae
said in a recent interview. ``I put up with safety violations and
broken rules, and even participated myself, for six years because I
was afraid of losing my job.''
   The pilots' jobs involved flying Army brass, equipment and
dangerous chemicals and weapons across the country. The violations
they reported included failure to report minor aircraft accidents,
falsification of documents and unsafe transportation of hazardous
cargo.
   McRae made his first report in September 1987 on violations at
the flight detachment based at Quad City Airport in nearby Moline.
   Gen. Marvin Brailsford credited him with pointing out
``weaknesses in safety, management and operations'' at the flight
division.
   Disciplinary action was taken against supervisors, the flight
detachment was reorganized and new safety checks were added to daily
routine, said Brailsford, commander of the U.S. Army Armament,
Munitions and Chemical Command.
   But in October 1987, McRae was grounded. This past January, he
was told he would be fired. The firing has been suspended while the
Merit Systems Protection Board investigates.
   Since his grounding, McRae has sorted tools in a machine shop
while drawing his $39,100 annual pilot's pay.
   ``They want to make an example out of me,'' he said. ``They are
trying to destroy any chance I have for employability in the airline
industry.''
   Williams became involved in the case when, as an aviation safety
officer, he followed up on some of McRae's allegations.
   Williams grounded himself in June 1988, citing the stress of
standing up for McRae and testifying against his supervisors at Army
inquiries.
   Now Williams wants to fly. Although a flight surgeon and
psychiatrist found him fit to do so, he has not been recertified.
   ``The only reasonable explanation for my situation is reprisal
for whistleblowing,'' said Williams, who is working as a machinery
oiler in a lubrication division.
   Arsenal spokesman Al Schwartz said Williams' flight status is
under review and there is no move to fire him.
   Pilots who flew with McRae and Williams had divided opinions
about the case.
   Chuck Hanna, who recently retired from the arsenal, described the
two as ``a couple of fellows trying to get their boss' job.''
   Hanna said a personality conflict between McRae and Neil Pobanz,
chief of the flight detachment, led to problems.
   Pobanz would say only that he regretted the situation. ``It's not
good for anybody on either side,'' he said. ``That's all I can say.''
   One pilot, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the Army
``abrogated all McRae's civil rights'' after he reported the
violations, attacking his character and stability.
   ``The supervisors at the flight detachment claimed Curt was
suffering from post-Vietnam stress syndrome. If that's true, they
should have treated him and counseled him,'' the pilot said.
   Schwartz said McRae was offered the opportunity to return to his
job in a December 1988 meeting with Brailsford and was told he would
have to work under the supervisors whose violations he reported.
   ``Mr. McRae essentially said, `No,''' according to Schwartz.
   ``I'd go back in an instant,'' McRae responded. ``But I told the
general I won't keep my mouth shut and I won't do wrong again.''
</TEXT>
