<FIRST>r w PM-Obit-Engle     09-18 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Engle,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former AP Reporter, Editor Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jacob B. Engle, an Associated Press reporter
and editor for 41 years, died last week, his wife said. He was 86.
   Engle joined the AP as a reporter in Topeka, Kan., on Jan. 3,
1927, and served there and in Wichita before transferring to
Washington in 1933.
   Before retiring in 1968, he covered 18 Republican and Democratic
national conventions.
   Engle was born in Abilene, Kan., on May 24, 1903, and was
graduated from the University of Kansas in 1925.
   Before joining the AP, he was city editor of the Pratt (Kan.)
Tribune and the Hutchinson Herald.
   After retiring, his chief hobby was gardening. In a letter
written to the AP in 1979, Engle said he grew several hundred
varieties of rhododendron and azaleas around his home in Bethesda,
Md. He was president of the American Rhododendron Society's Potomac
Valley Chapter and vice president of its Middle Atlantic chapter.
   From 1948 to 1959, he was a member of the Bethesda Fire Board.
   Engle died Thursday. He is survived by his widow, Jessie, a
daughter, Mary Louise Engle, and a sister, Viola Nigg, of Los
Angeles.
   A funeral mass was planned for 10 a.m. today at St. Bartholomew's
Catholic Church in Bethesda.
</TEXT>
