<FIRST>r w PM-Arts-Kreeger     09-18 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arts-Kreeger,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arts Benefactor Praised as `Universal Man'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Lloyd Kreeger, a major benefactor of arts
and educational institutions, was toasted by violinist Isaac Stern
and praised by President Bush as representing ``the renaissance
ideal of the universal man.''
   Bush's congratulatory letter was read at a black-tie dinner
Sunday night in a downtown hotel attended by 400 guests to
commemorate Kreeger's 80th birthday, which occurred in January.
   Kreeger, a multimillionaire former insurance executive and
amateur violinist, was entertained by Stern, cellist Mstislav
Rostropovich, the Cleveland Quartet and the Tokyo quartet.
   Kreeger ended the pre-dinner musical program by performing a
Mozart duet with Stern and two Scott Joplin rags with the combined
string quartets.
   Kreeger, who is undergoing radiation therapy for cancer, is
honorary chairman of the GEICO Insurance Co., based in Washington.
For years he has been a major donor to such local institutions as
the Washington Opera, the National Symphony Orchestra, the Corcoran
Gallery of Art, Arena Stage and American University. His northwest
Washington mansion contains a valuable collection of paintings by
Picasso, Renoir, Monet, and other masters.
   Toasts were given by Rostropovich, Supreme Court Justice William
J. Brennan, and British Ambassador Sir Antony Ackland. Stern, an old
friend who often played the violin with Kreeger, told the audience
that ``David was the cultural center of Washington before it ever
became a cultural center.''
</TEXT>
