<FIRST>r p PM-NJGovernor     09-18 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NJ Governor,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>NJ Republican on the Defensive in Fight to Succeed Gov. Kean</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS MARTELLO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A six-term congressman seeking to come from
behind to prevent the governor's mansion from falling into
Democratic hands has found his campaign bogged down on issues such
as homosexual rights and abortion.
   Rep. James Courter, the Republican nominee for governor, has been
trying to close a 17-point lead pollsters said his Democratic
opponent, U.S. Rep. James Florio, held in June.
   But Courter's stands on volatile social issues have kept him on
the defensive in his quest to succeed Gov. Thomas H. Kean, a popular
Republican who is barred by law from running for a third-consecutive
term.
   Courter stormed away from a street-corner news conference last
week when reporters asked him to clarify a statement that the state
should not hire ``avowed homosexuals'' as teachers, camp counselors
or foster parents.
   At the news conference he called to discuss auto insurance,
Courter said he would not change state laws to bar homosexuals, and
bristled at suggestions he was changing his mind.
   Like Kean, Florio has said homosexuality should not be a
consideration in hiring practices.
   Abortion has hounded Courter since July, when the U.S. Supreme
Court allowed states to restrict abortion rights. The decision
focused the national debate on New Jersey and Virginia, the only
states with governor's races this year.
   Florio immediately took a strong stance favoring abortion rights.
Courter, who previously promised to sign a bill outlawing abortions,
later said he would not impose his views on New Jersey. His new
stand angered both sides.
   ``We have had problems,'' said Ken Connolly, Courter's campaign
manager. ``But we are going to show over the next seven weeks and
two days that we are not demoralized and that we are not
disorganized.''
   Both candidates in November's election are proven vote-getters.
   Florio, 52, an eight-term congressman, lost the 1981 race for
governor to Kean by less than 1,800 votes, the smallest margin in
state history. Florio has built his reputation on environmental
affairs and authored the federal Superfund laws to clean up toxic
waste dumps. New Jersey leads the nation in the number of toxic
dumps.
   Courter, 48, who vanquished a large field of candidates in the
Republican primary, gained recognition as a member of the
Iran-Contra committee and is an outspoken proponent of a strong
national defense.
   After June's primary, each campaign answered charges of influence
peddling within federal housing programs.
   Two top Courter aides, including former Reagan administration
political strategist Roger Ailes, resigned from the campaign after
their consulting firms became embroiled in a congressional influence
peddling investigation of the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban
Development.
   One of Florio's aides resigned after being implicated in an
investigation of a Camden County housing authority, located in
Florio's district.
   As the candidates head into the final stage of the race, analysts
predict the campaign will turn dirty.
   ``I think it's going to be nasty,'' said Richard Roper, director
of Princeton University's Council on New Jersey Affairs and a
consultant to Florio's campaign. ``I would be surprised if a lot of
mudslinging does not occur.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
