<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 0310EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Emmys-Analysis     09-18 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Emmys-Analysis,0729</SECOND>
<HEAD>Predictable Emmys Offer Some Unpredictable Surprises</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Emmys, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The usually predictable Emmy awards show
was quite unpredictable this year.
   The winners were picked in such a random fashion it's impossible
to know what the members of the Academy of Television Arts &amp;
Sciences had in mind.
   The hit CBS miniseries ``Lonesome Dove'' won the most awards with
seven, but the only major award went to Simon Wincer for directing.
   ABC's monumental ``War and Remembrance'' was all but ignored,
then won as outstanding miniseries. Producer-director Dan Curtis
expressed it best, calling it ``a major shock.''
   CBS's rookie series ``Murphy Brown'' was the most honored comedy.
It won four awards Sunday night, including those for Candice Bergen
as best lead actress, Colleen Dewhurst as best guest actress, and
Diane English for writing.
   But NBC's ``Cheers,'' still highly popular but looking a little
strained after eight years, won for comedy series.
   How about ``Designing Women'' or ``The Wonder Years?'' Each was
nominated for best comedy series but none of the well-deserving
actresses in either series has ever been nominated.
   Did academy members cast their votes by the ratings? If that were
the case, NBC's ``The Cosby Show'' or ABC's ``Roseanne'' would won.
Neither was nominated. ``Lonesome Dove'' was the year's
highest-rated miniseries, but it lost to ``War and Remembrance,''
which failed to get as large an audience as anticipated.
   Sir John Gielgud gave one of the best performances ever seen on
television, portraying the professor who strayed from his Jewish
faith before finding it again in a Nazi concentration camp in ``War
and Remembrance.'' He lost as best actor in a miniseries or special,
as did Robert Duvall for his multi-layered role as an aging Texas
still determined to sow his wild oats in ``Lonesome Dove.''
   James Woods won for a role as the man who founded Alcoholics
Anonymous in ABC's ``My Name Is Bill W.,'' a considerably less
complex role.
   Holly Hunter won as best actress in a miniseries or special. Her
show, NBC's ``Roe vs. Wade,'' tied for outstanding drama or comedy
special with CBS ``Day One.''
   The story of the case that made abortion the law of the land was
politically popular in Hollywood, but was pedestrian drama.
   The big loser, and the actress who should have won, was Jane
Seymour, for her magnificent role as the American Jewish woman
trapped behind enemy lines in ``War and Remembrance.''
   Dana Delany of ABC's ``China Beach'' was a good choice for best
actress in a drama series. Too bad former co-star Chloe Webb was
overlooked for her absolutely captivating role as Laurette in the
guest actress category.
   Ken Wahl would have been a good choice for best actor in a drama
series for CBS' much under-rated ``Wiseguy.''
   The funny thing about the comedy awards is the way the women from
NBC's ``The Golden Girls'' keep dominating the lead actress
category. They're great, the show's great, but the bittersweet
complaints from Dixie Carter, Annie Potts and Jean Smart of CBS'
``Designing Women'' are on the money. They deserve to be nominated
and the show deserves better treatment than it has gotten from the
academy.
   Rhea Perlman won her fourth Emmy as Carla on ``Cheers.''
Perlman's talent is looking good in a role that has been virtually
milked dry.
   More deserving were Julia Duffy of CBS' ``Newhart'' or Faith Ford
of CBS' ``Murphy Brown.''
   Peter Scolari, also of ``Newhart,'' deserved recognition for
giving new dimension this past season to a heretofore predictable
character.
   ``The Arsenio Hall Show,'' which is rewriting some of the roles
of late-night programming, lost out as best variety, music or comedy
program. Maybe they should let the young viewers vote.
   Among others not nominated:
   Kirstie Alley of ``Cheers,'' the freshest thing on the show.
   CBS' ``Newhart.'' Maybe they just make it look too easy.
   Fox's ``Married...With Children.'' Maybe they make it look too
raunchy.
   Why not NBC's deliciously funny ``Dear John,'' which won for best
guest actor? Or NBC's intriguing drama ``Midnight Caller,'' although
it did win in two guest acting categories?
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Jerry Buck has been covering television since
1967.
</TEXT>
