<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru a0795 09-18 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0795,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Japanese Stocks Both Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with closing Nikkei, dollar. Pickup
4th graf `Traders attributed...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged higher against the Japanese yen
Monday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose
moderately.
   The dollar ended trading at 146.43 yen, up 0.58 yen from
Thursday's 145.85-yen finish. It opened at 145.90 yen and moved
between 145.45 yen and 146.45 yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average added 70.66 points, or 0.21
percent, ending trading at 34,472.54. It gained 114.94 points
Thursday.
   Traders attributed the dollar's higher opening to its upswing on
overseas markets triggered by better-than-expected U.S. trade
figures released Friday.
   The U.S. Commerce Department reported the nation's trade deficit
declined for the second consecutive month in July to $7.58 billion,
the smallest gap in nearly five years.
   The dollar held its ground despite intermittent dollar-selling
operations by the Bank of Japan, said Minori Takeuchi, trader with
Chemical Bank in Tokyo.
   The central bank intervened when the dollar was about to reach
the 146-yen level and again when it passed the 146-yen level, she
said.
   The Bank of Japan does not comment on its monetary actions.
   ``Securities investment and insurance companies were buying the
dollar at its lows, whereas the central bank was trying to halt the
dollar's upward movement whenever it began rising,'' Ms. Takeuchi
said, ``so the dollar wasn't moving that quickly.''
   But the dollar continues to be strong due to its attractiveness
to market players following the improved trade figures, Ms. Takeuchi
said.
   Meanwhile, stock trading was inactive following a three-day
weekend because of a Japanese national holiday Friday, when stock,
foreign exchange and other financial institutions were closed, said
a dealer with New Japan Securities, Co., speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Some dealers said market players were concerned about the yen's
performance against the dollar.
</TEXT>
