<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 0611EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--NursesStrike     09-18 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Nurses Strike,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nurses End Walkout at Oakland Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Children's Hospital nurses approved an
agreement to end a 10-week strike that forced the transfer of
critically ill patients from the area's only children's trauma
center.
   ``The strike is officially over,'' Karen Cooper, spokeswoman for
the California Nurses Association, said Sunday.
   The CNA, which represents 700 nurses at the hospital, declined to
reveal the vote. The pact, reached late Friday, puts unresolved
issues such as sick leave and holiday pay under binding arbitration.
   The two sides earlier agreed to a 20 percent wage increase over
two years.
   The nurses, who went on strike July 11, will start returning to
work Friday, Cooper said.
   ``I think everybody's basic feeling is relief,'' said hospital
spokesman Steve Tiger.
   The hospital, one of 14 children's trauma centers in the nation,
transferred or discharged most of its patients, many of whom were
critically ill, after the strike began. The number of patients fell
from 170 to 38 immediately after the strike started but grew to 112
by Sunday, Tiger said.
   The strike cost the hospital about $4.5 million, Tiger said.
</TEXT>
