<DOCNO> AP890918-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 0432EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Maldives     09-18 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Maldives,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Sentences Commuted to Life Term</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maldivian President Maumoon Abdul Gayoom
has commuted the death sentences of 12 Sri Lankans and four
Maldivians for roles in last year's abortive coup to life
imprisonment, the government said today.
   The clemency came after the condemned men appealed to Gayoom,
said the statement sent by telex to New Delhi from the Maldivian
Department of Information and Broadcasting.
   Another 56 Sri Lankans and three Maldivians were convicted in the
plot and sentenced to prison terms ranging from nine to 38 years by
the high court in Male, the Maldivians capital, in August after a
two-month of trial.
   The Nov. 3 coup attempt was crushed by Indian paratroopers who
landed in Maldives in response to a call for help from Gayoom. At
least 17 people, mostly local residents, were killed in the fighting.
   ``The country had never executed people for political crimes in
its history and that he (Gayoom) did not want this generation to be
the first to shed blood on our soil as punishment for political
crime,'' the statement said.
   The last death sentence for non-political crime was carried out
in Maldives in 1953 by a firing squad.
   The Maldivian government has said the convicted Sri Lankans were
mercenaries who belong to the People's Liberation Organization of
Tamil Eelam, one of the several guerrilla groups that has
participated in the Tamil separatist war against Sri Lanka's
Sinhalese majority.
   The failed coup was led by Abdullah Luthufi, a Sri Lankan-based
Maldivian who was among those who benefitted from the clemency.
   The Maldives are a string of coral islands about 500 miles south
of India and roughly the same distance southwest of Sri Lanka. The
country is made up of about 2,000 islands of which only 200 are
inhabited.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
