<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 0420EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     09-18 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar climbed against the Japanese yen today
despite the Bank of Japan's dollar-selling intervention, while the
Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index rose moderately.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues rose 70.66
points, or 0.21 percent, to 34,472.54. It had gained 114.94 points
on Thursday. The market was closed Friday for a national holiday.
   The dollar closed at 146.43 yen, up 0.58 yen from Thursday's
close of 145.85 yen. It opened at 145.90 yen and ranged between
145.45 yen and 146.45 yen. The dollar had fallen a total of 1.92 yen
in the previous three trading days.
   Traders said the dollar rose despite dollar-selling by the
central bank in efforts to check the U.S. currency's climb.
   The dollar's upswing was attributed largely to a
better-than-expected U.S. trade figure released Friday.
   The U.S. Commerce Department reported that the nation's trade
deficit narrowed for the second consecutive month in July, to $7.58
billion, the smallest gap in almost five years.
   ``Institutional investors, who had strong demand, increasingly
bought the dollar in the afternoon and pushed it further up against
the yen,'' said a trader with the Bank of Tokyo, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   ``Currently, the level around 146.50 yen seems to be an
equilibrium point for the dollar's selling and buying,'' he said.
   Spot trading volume totaled $9.737 billion, down from $9.861
billion on Thursday.
   On the stock exchange, the index rose steadily, despite
uncertainties over the foreign exchange rate, as participants bought
real estate, railway and construction issues in thin trading,
dealers said.
   The market's main barometer rose mainly in the afternoon
following speculative investors' arbitrage deals, a tactic to make
profits out of price gaps between spot and futures issues, said a
dealer with a major Tokyo securities firm, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   First section volume was estimated at 450 million shares, down
from Thursday's 550 million.
</TEXT>
