<FIRST>r a PM-Chamorro-Miami     09-18 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chamorro-Miami,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan Opposition Candidate Visits Miami</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With direct U.S. funding no longer a possibility,
Nicaraguan presidential candidate Violeta Barrios de Chamorro is
lobbying Miami's exile community to raise money for her campaign.
   Mrs. Chamorro, nominated this month to lead the 14-party
anti-government slate, spoke to 2,000 exiles Sunday during her first
visit to this country since becoming a candidate.
   She said the support of Nicaraguans abroad was vital to her
effort to oust the leftist government in the Feb. 25 elections.
   ``You keep alive the dream of a free Nicaragua,'' she said.
   Tonight, a $100-a-plate fund-raising dinner in Miami is planned
for Mrs. Chamorro, head of the La Prensa newspaper and wife of
publisher Pedro Joaquin Chamorro, whose 1978 slaying helped spark
the insurrection that put the Sandinistas in power in July 1979.
   The Bush administration on Friday bowed to congressional pressure
and abandoned a plan to funnel about $2 million in government funds
to her campaign through the U.S.-financed National Endowment for
Democracy.
   But administration officials say they will encourage private and
foreign groups to donate money to Mrs. Chamorro.
   She assailed the Sandinista government for human rights
violations and causing the country's economic problems, and appealed
for Nicaraguans abroad to consider returning to home if her party is
successful.
   ``The hour has sounded for liberty in Nicaragua,'' she said.
``But the liberty is for Nicaraguans and the reconciliation of all
the people.''
   Mrs. Chamorro is the candidate of the National Opposition Union,
known by its Spanish initials UNO. The Sandinistas are expected to
nominate President Daniel Ortega for re-election.
   Mrs. Chamorro, 59, a devout Roman Catholic, pledged religious
freedom and emphasis on a free-market economy in Nicaragua, which
because of war, a U.S. embargo and economic mismanagement during the
last 10 years has become one of the hemisphere's poorest countries.
   She called on the United States to grant work permits to
Nicaraguan refugees.
   Earlier this year, more than 100,000 impoverished Nicaraguans
arrived in Miami.
   A small band of opponents demonstrated outside the amphitheater
where Mrs. Chamorro spoke. Detractors among the anti-Sandinista
forces cite her political inexperience and the brief term she served
in the revolutionary government.
   In campaign appearances, Mrs. Chamorro often evokes the name of
her late husband, who inherited control of the family-run La Prensa
in 1948 and used the newspaper as a forum for attacks on the ruling
Somoza family.
   Mrs. Chamorro joined a five-member junta following Anastasio
Somoza's downfall, but resigned within a year and returned to direct
La Prensa, which repeatedly has been closed by the Sandinistas.
</TEXT>
