<FIRST>r a PM-Emmys-Fox     09-18 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Emmys-Fox,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fledgling Fox Network Wins Top Emmy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Emmys, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The upstart Fox network moved another
rung up the television ladder, winning a top Emmy for ``The Tracey
Ullman Show'' at the 41st annual awards ceremony.
   The program, which won four awards, was the first Fox
Broadcasting Co. show to win television's top prize.
   ``It's a beginning,'' Barry Diller, chairman of Fox Inc. said
backstage during Sunday night's ceremonies. ``The first is always
the best.''
   The network, which has been criticized for its raunchy situation
comedy ``Married... With Children'' and the tabloid news show ``A
Current Affair,'' has defied critics who were convinced the
2{-year-old endeavor would flop.
   ``The award tonight had a special explosion to it,'' Diller said.
``I think it's because everybody involved in this enterprise thinks
of it as an adventure. And it is.
   ``There was not a single person in the entertainment business who
thought that we were anything but a fool's errand, and that we would
dismally fail.
   ``The people who were our friends thought we'd survive the
failure and go on. The people who were our enemies were juicy about
how viciously we'd fail. They're going through the process now of
saying, `Well, I guess it didn't happen.'''
   Although ``The Tracey Ullman Show'' is not Fox's highest rated
series, it is probably its most acclaimed. The variety show, which
made its debut in April 1987, is an unusual, irreverent cornucopia
with Miss Ullman as host.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
