<FIRST>r a PM-PrintShopMassacre     09-18 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Print Shop Massacre,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paramedics Describe Harrowing Scene of Rampage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two paramedics who were among the first to
arrive after a gunman opened fire inside a printing plant were
pinned down with four victims in a reception area while the gunman
roamed the building.
   At a news conference Saturday, paramedic Greg Torpey described
watching helplessly as Sharon Needy died of massive internal
bleeding, while gunman Joseph T. Wesbecker roamed somewhere nearby
in the Standard Gravure Corp. building.
   ``If we could have got her out right away and got her to a trauma
center ... there is a possibility that she could be living now,'' he
said.
   Wesbecker, a Standard Gravure employee on longterm leave because
of mental problems, went from floor to floor shooting people at the
plant Thursday, leaving seven dead and 13 wounded before committing
suicide.
   Torpey and Connie Grace, who were among the first to arrive at
the building after the shooting spree began, described the harrowing
scene along with three other emergency workers at an impromptu news
conference at Louisville Emergency Medical Services' headquarters.
   Torpey said that one of the wounded women he was treating had
expressed something akin to sympathy for Wesbecker when she learned,
by police radio, that he had shot himself.
   ``The victim said, `Well, God rest his soul,''' he said, ``which
for me was a tremendous boost in faith that somebody could say that
after being shot several times ... to still understand that this
wasn't the action really of a criminal, this was the action of a
sick individual, someone who for some reason has gone over the
edge.''
   Torpey and Ms. Grace heard shots as they rode up the elevator
after entering the building.
   As soon as the elevator doors opened at the third floor, they
began attending two gravely injured women, Angela Bowman and Needy.
Two other injured women lay down a nearby hallway, but police
indicated that it was too dangerous for EMS personnel to go to them.
   ``We'd been there just a couple of minutes and they came back on
the radio and said ... that the assailant was back on our floor,''
Ms. Grace said. ``I was petrified.''
   The two waited for what seemed like an eternity for another
ambulance crew to help them evacuate the wounded, Torpey said.
   Normally, paramedics try to stabilize gunshot victims and whisk
them away to a hospital immediately _ ``load and go,'' said
paramedic Kenneth Murray, who also was involved in treating victims
of the shooting.
   Murray, whose voice quavered occasionally, said he wanted to
speak publicly about the experience because ``people should know
what an AK-47 can do.''
   Wesbecker used the Soviet-designed AK-47 assault rifle, two
semiautomatic machine pistols and other weapons during his rampage.
   ``It's tough. We're talking about combat medicine,'' EMS director
Richard Bartlett said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
