<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     09-18 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Stronger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was lower in early European trading
today in the aftermath of Friday's volatile session. Gold prices
were stronger.
   Foreign currency dealers said Friday's price swings and tumbles
had broken the enthusiasm for the dollar which followed much
better-than-expected U.S. trade figures for July.
   Several traders said they expect the dollar to regain some key
ground later this week.
   ``I believe we will go higher again,'' said Jens-Uwe Fischer, a
trader at Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co. in Frankfurt.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.58 yen to close at 146.43 yen despite the Bank of
Japan's dollar-selling intervention. Later, in London, it was quoted
at 146.75 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Friday:
   _1.9734 West German marks, down from 2.0005
   _1.7033 Swiss francs, down from 1.7260
   _6.6565 French francs, down from 6.7430
   _2.2198 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2490
   _1,417.50 Italian lire, down from 1,433.50
   _1.1850 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1880
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.5558 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5390 late Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $360.25 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $356.25. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $360.10.
   In Zurich, the bid price was also $360.10, up from $356.00 late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 60 cents to close at a bid
$360.90.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.07 a troy ounce,
up from Friday's $5.03.
</TEXT>
