<FIRST>r a PM-MineExplosion     09-18 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mine Explosion,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coal Miners Killed in Mine Blast Buried; Methane Levels Delay Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHEATCROFT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives buried the 10 men killed in a
western Kentucky mine blast while company officials tried to reduce
methane gas in the mine so they could begin an investigation into
the explosion.
   Funeral services were held Sunday for Anthony T. McElroy, 36, of
Providence, and Curtis W. Scott, 47, of Madisonville. They were the
last of the victims to be buried from Wednesday's explosion at Pyro
Mining Co.'s William Station Mine.
   Willard Stanley, head of the state Department of Mines and
Minerals, said that a blowtorch found near the site most likely
ignited the blast.
   Federal and state investigators conducting a preliminary check of
the mine found explosive levels of methane Thursday, delaying the
investigation, said Kathy Snyder of the U.S. Mine Safety and Health
Administration.
   Sunday, MSHA spokesman Frank O'Gorman said the probe was still on
hold, although the agency approved a company plan to lower the
methane levels.
   The Pyro mine had been cited for 1,508 violations and fined
$215,757 over the last seven years, according to MSHA. About $53,000
was assessed this year.
</TEXT>
