<FIRST>r a PM-DotsonArrested     09-18 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dotson Arrested,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dotson Arrested For Trespassing At Request of Estranged Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gary Dotson, who was cleared last month of rape
and kidnapping charges more than four years after his accuser
recanted her testimony against him, has had another scrape with the
law.
   Dotson was arrested Sunday at the home of his wife Camille, from
whom he is legally separated, and charged with criminal trespassing,
said Cook County Sheriff's Lt. Arthur Jackson.
   ``They had been attempting some sort of reconciliation, and when
they agreed to reconcile, she gave him a key to her apartment,''
Jackson said.
   ``Things fell through. She asked for the key back. He refused,''
Jackson said. ``She left town, and when she came back he was at the
apartment and refused to go.''
   Mrs. Dotson then called authorities to her apartment, where
Dotson was arrested.
   Dotson was released Sunday night after posting $100 bail. He was
scheduled to appear in court Oct. 6.
   Dotson, 32, was cleared Aug. 14 of charges brought after Cathleen
Crowell Webb accused him of rape and kidnapping in 1977. Dotson was
convicted in 1979, but Mrs. Webb came forward six years later saying
Dotson never committed the crime.
   Dotson was granted clemency and paroled by Gov. James R. Thompson
in 1985, but it wasn't until August that new genetic evidence
proving Dotson could not have committed the rape forced Circuit
Judge Thomas R. Fitzgerald to grant a new trial. The prosecution
then dropped the charges.
   Dotson has been living in an alcohol and drug treatment center.
   Criminal trespassing is a misdemeanor charge punishable by no
more than a year in prison, Jackson said.
   Dotson had been back behind bars several times for parole
violations, including fighting in a bar and failing to report to his
parole officer.
</TEXT>
