<FIRST>r i PM-Australia-Bridge     09-18 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Australia-Bridge,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>United States Defeats Australia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PERTH, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States devastated Australia
77-3 over the first 16 deals in a semifinal of the Bermuda Bowl
world contract bridge championships today.
   The pace slowed tremendously over the second 16 deals, and the
Americans led, 103-25, after 32 deals. The match consists of 160
deals over three days.
   The Americans, who have won every Bermuda Bowl championship since
1976, gave up single points on three deals, all on overtricks,
during the first 16-deal session.
   At the same time they picked up swings on 12 deals, including
four in double digits. The set concluded with Hugh Ross of Oakland,
Calif., bringing home a difficult club slam while the Australian
declarer went down in his slam.
   In the other semifinal, Brazil, winner of the round-robin, took a
45-point lead over Poland, European champion, 85-40.
   In the Venice Cup world women's championship, the defending
champions from the United States fell 10 points behind Canada on the
first 16 deals, but then rallied to take the lead, 86-58, after 32
deals.
   West Germany took a 24-point lead, 73-49, against the
Netherlands, victors in the round-robin. West Germany and the
Netherlands finished 1-2 in the European Championship in Turku,
Finland, earlier this year.
</TEXT>
