<FIRST>r a PM-PlaneCrash     09-18 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plane Crash,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Georgia Men Killed in Alabama Plane Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GORDON, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three men were killed when their small plane
crashed trying to make an emergency landing but a rescuer saved the
pilot's 6-year-old son by pulling him out of the burning wreckage.
   The single-engine Piper Cub smashed into a power line and skidded
under a railroad trestle Sunday near the Chattahoochee River in
eastern Alabama, said Houston County Deputy Sheriff Eddie Ingram.
   The pilot, 47-year-old Roger Kenneth Parmer, had informed flight
controllers that he was low on fuel and attempting to reach a
landing strip at Cedar Springs, Ga., Ingram said.
   Wayne Barfield said he and his wife were fishing when they saw
the crash. They and other fishermen carried buckets of water from
the river to the burning plane until truck drivers arrived with fire
extinguishers.
   The rescuers lifted the aircraft by the tail section and Robert
Bass of Camilla, Ga., crawled under the wreckage and pulled the boy
out.
   ``If it hadn't been for them there's no doubt the child would
have perished,'' Ingram said. ``It was a heroic effort.''
   Bass said he was spraying the burning plane with a fire
extinguisher when he heard a child's cry come from inside the
airplane.
   ``I didn't know if the airplane was going to explode or not,''
Bass said. ``I just knew I had to get that little boy out.
   A relative of one of the victims told Ingram the plane was en
route to Marianna, Fla.
   Killed were Parmer; Edward Prather, 55, and Kenneth S. Partridge,
54, all of LaGrange, Ga., said Houston County Coroner Robert Byrd.
   The boy, Brandon Parmer, was in guarded condition at Southeast
Alabama Medical Center, said hospital spokesman Ray Griffith.
</TEXT>
