<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 0904EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SunkenTreasure     09-18 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sunken Treasure,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists Examine Mysterious Sponge As Explorers Raise Gold</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Researchers found a mysterious ``lacy and
delicate'' creature near some $400 million in gold on a 19th century
shipwreck 200 miles off the South Carolina coast.
   Charles Herdendorf, an oceanographer with the Columbus-America
Discovery Group exploring the ship, said Saturday that researchers
discovered what he believes to be two new invertebrates clinging to
the SS Central America, 8,000 feet below the water's surface.
   A Columbus-America spokesman said both samples were retrieved.
But Herdendorf on Sunday said in a ship-to-shore telephone
conversation that an unmanned submersible ship was able to retrieve
only one of the unusual finds, apparently a type of animal known as
a sponge, and scientists were still trying to determine if it was
already classified.
   ``When (the subersible operator) brought it up, it was beautiful,
very lacy and delicate. The entire animal is supported by a very
clear skeleton of glass spicules,'' Herdendorf said. ``They look
like little ice skeletons.''
   Herdendorf is one of about 20 crew members of the Arctic
Discoverer trying to reclaim as much as $400 million in gold coins
and bars from the Central America.
   The Central America sank during a hurricane Sept. 12, 1857, as it
traveled from Panama to New York. It was carrying a monthly shipment
of gold from the San Francisco Mint to New York banks by way of the
Panamaian isthmus. The wreck claimed 425 lives; 153 people survived.
   Early estimates valued the treasure at $1 billion, but
Columbus-America director Barry Schatz said $400 million is more
realistic.
   The organism captured Saturday, originally thought to be a coral,
looked different when it was brought up from the original pictures
from the ocean floor, Herdendorf said.
   He expected to place it in an alcohol solution for transport to
the shore by midweek.
   The other organism, which Herdendorf still believes may be a
newly discovered sponge, remains out of reach of the submersible, he
said.
   Though Saturday was devoted solely to scientific research, Schatz
said in a ship-to-shore conversation that the submersible Nemo
raised more gold coins Sunday.
   Many of the coins are lying in the rolls they were originally
shipped in, he said.
   In addition to the mint money, Schatz said the Central America
also carried shipments of coins from private companies to banks.
   ``One of the companies was Levi and Company before it became Levi
and Strauss,'' Schatz said. ``So Levi was making money making jeans,
and he was sending it back to New York. So we are looking at some of
his money.''
   While Hurricane Hugo lashed the eastern Caribbean with winds of
up to 140 mph Sunday, Schatz said the storm was not yet a concern on
board.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
