<SECOND>PM-BRF--Peak Challenge,0147</SECOND>
<HEAD>900 Mountaineers Scale Colorado's 14,000-foot Peaks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Groups of mountaineers spent the
day scaling each of Colorado's more than 50 14,000-foot peaks to
raise money for troubled youths.
   ``It's nice to be at the top,'' said climber Becky Albright after
scaling the 14,100-foot Pikes Peak on Sunday. ``It sure is different
from 5,000 feet.'' She was one of 900 mountaineers who took part.
   Peak Challenge '89 was organized by the Griffith Center, a home
in Larkspur for 44 abused or neglected boys. The home ``sold''
business leaders a mountain to climb for $500 each and raised
$27,000.
   ``The challenge of the mountain and the challenges they (the boys
must overcome) _ it's very metaphorical,'' said Albright, who is a
Griffith therapist.
   The Colorado Mountain Club provided guides to each climbing
party, as well as logistical support.
