<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1010EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru   09-18 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0521,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fierce Shelling After Aoun Rejects Security Committee</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with six killed, 14 wounded; picks
up 5th pvs: `The police...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fierce artillery duel broke out before
dawn today after Christian leader Gen. Michel Aoun rejected the
creation of an Arab-proposed security committee that would oversee a
truce in Lebanon.
   Police said at least six people were killed and 14 wounded in the
exchange.
   A police spokesman said ``several people'' were believed to be
buried under the rubble of a seven-story apartment building
devastated by concentrated shelling in Beirut's Shiite Moslem slum
of Haret Hreik.
   By police count, at least 921 people have been killed and 2,713
wounded since the confrontation broke out March 8, pitting Aoun's
mainly Christian troops against Syrian and allied forces.
   The police spokesman, who cannot be named in line with
regulations, said the fierce barrage began at about 1 a.m.
   He said it could not be determined who provoked the duel, which
started 90 minutes after Aoun rejected participation in an
intra-Lebanese security committee to supervise implementation of
cease-fire called by Arab peacemakers.
   ``I won't accept at all a Lebanese-Lebanese committee. This is
what the Syrians wanted, to deceive the world and say the clashes
have been among Lebanese factions,'' Aoun said in a televised
interview.
   Aoun, a Maronite Catholic who commands a 20,000-strong army, was
referring to the absence of a Syrian representative on the proposed
committee. About 40,000 Syrian troops are backing Moslem militias in
Lebanon. They were deployed in Lebanon since 1976 under a
peacekeeping mandate from the Arab League.
   The peace plan was announced Saturday in Saudi Arabia, Morocco
and Algeria, whose leaders make up the three-member mediation
committee entrusted with the task of finding a settlement by
November to the 14-year-old Lebanese civil war.
   The peace plan also called for Lebanon's Parliament members to
meet outside Lebanon Sept. 30 to work out reforms to the 45-year-old
political system, which has been dominated by the Maronites.
   The shelling since March broke out over a blockade by Aoun of
illegal ports run by Syrian-backed militias south of Beirut, in an
effort to reassert government control over the ports.
   The Syrians and allied forces retaliated by shelling and
besieging the 310-square-mile Christian enclave northeast of Beirut.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
