<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1034EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Palme     09-18 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Palme,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>`No Doubt,' Mrs. Palme Says of Convicted Killer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHAN RAPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of Prime Minister Olof Palme,
questioned directly today by the man convicted of killing her
husband, said there was no chance he was innocent.
   ``Unfortunately, there is no doubt,'' Lisbeth Palme said at an
appeals hearing.
   She identified Christer Pettersson as the only person in sight on
the downtown street corner where Palme was shot to death on the
night of Feb. 28, 1986.
   Pettersson was convicted of the killing in July, and the
appellate hearing, which began Sept. 11, has largely been a rehash
of testimony at the lower court trial.
   After Mrs. Palme had been questioned by defense attorneys for
almost two hours, Pettersson was led into the courtroom under heavy
guard and allowed to question her directly for the first time. Mrs.
Palme, appearing shaken, closed her eyes as he was led in.
   Speaking loudly, Pettersson said: ``If I am convicted of this I
can count on 10 years (imprisonment), that is 90,000 hours, before I
have my first furlough.
   ``Therefore, I ask you to look (Judge) Birgitta Blom in the eyes
for 10 seconds and say that it was I that killed your husband,''
Pettersson said.
   The Svea Court of Appeals fell silent until Blom said, ``Mrs.
Palme nodded her head.'' The policemen guarding Mrs. Palme blocked
her from spectators in the courtroom, although she was visible to
Pettersson.
   In today's session, as in the original trial, Mrs. Palme said she
could not testify to seeing a gun in Pettersson's hand.
   ``I was focusing on his face,'' she said. ``That does not exclude
his having a gun in his hand.''
   Pettersson has repeatedly denied he was close to the site of the
slaying. A lower court July 27 sentenced him to life imprisonment,
largely on the basis of Mrs. Palme's identification.
   No murder weapon has been found.
   ``Why would I kill your husband, the friend of the weak and
oppressed?'' said Pettersson, who contends he admired Palme. Mrs.
Palme did not answer.
   The appeal was scheduled to end Oct. 5. If the conviction is
reversed, Pettersson will be freed immediately. If not, Pettersson's
life sentence may be commuted after 20 years, a common practice in
Sweden's penal system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
