<FIRST>r a PM-AuschwitzConvent 1stLd-Writethru a0497 09-18 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auschwitz Convent, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0497,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>O'Connor Says Catholics Should Honor Auschwitz Agreement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to add comments from cardinal on anti-Semitism.
Picks up 6th graf pvs, `If the...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal John J. O'Connor says he supports Jewish
efforts to get a Roman Catholic convent near the Auschwitz death
camp closed, but that many of his fellow Catholics are prejudiced
against Jews.
   The fight over the convent in Poland has put ``fuel on the
fire,'' O'Connor said on the WNBC-TV's ``News Forum'' program,
broadcast Sunday. ``I think there are many Catholics who are
anti-Semitic.
   ``It's deep within them, and this kind of thing then just throws
up the flames. And simultaneously there are Jews who live in fear of
Catholic anti-Semitism and consequently ... it feeds the fear,''
O'Connor said. He said he has received letters criticizing him for
supporting the move of the convent.
   He said he is exploring the possibility of talking to Pope John
Paul II about the dispute, which arose after the church agreed to
close the convent and then local Catholic officials in Poland balked.
   ``It's not a fight between Jews and Catholics,'' O'Connor said.
``Catholics and Jews made an agreement. The agreement hasn't been
honored. It's as basic as that.''
   The convent just outside the Auschwitz concentration camp is seen
by many Jews as an intrusion of Christian symbols at a place where
2.5 million Jews were murdered by the Nazis during World War II.
   A 1987 accord between Jewish and Roman Catholic representatives
stipulated the convent should be moved by Feb. 22, but the deadline
passed and the convent remained. The Polish primate, Cardinal Jozef
Glemp, has termed the accord ``offensive.'' An estimated 1.5 million
Christians also were killed at Auschwitz.
   Nobel laureate Elie Wiesel, an Auschwitz survivor who appeared on
the same program, said Jews are in a no-win situation in the dispute.
   If the convent of Carmelite nuns is allowed to remain, ``We
lost,'' Wiesel said. ``But even if we win, we lost.
   ``Can you imagine when the nuns will leave the convent? There
will be thousands of reporters and TV cameras, and people will say,
`Look, these poor Carmelite nuns thrown out of their convent by
Jews!' We don't need that.''
   O'Connor said he considered ``unwise'' the recent trip by Rabbi
Avraham Weiss and six other Jewish demonstrators from New York to
Auschwitz, where they were attacked when they tried to climb a fence
surrounding the grounds.
   The archbishop also called Glemp's statements after the incident
``unfortunate.'' Glemp said the Jews had launched attacks on the
convent, possibly intending to kill the sisters, and that Jews had
the media ``easily at your disposal in many countries.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
