<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1136EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CrashTape     09-18 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Crash Tape,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transcript of Cockpit Conversation in DC-10 Crash Released</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The captain of the United DC-10 that crashed in
Iowa killing 112 people called for its two remaining engines to be
shut down 15 seconds before impact, but another pilot said, ``I
can't pull 'em off or we'll lose it.''
   The National Transportation Safety Board released a transcript of
the final 33 minutes and 34 seconds of conversation in the cockpit
of Flight 232.
   The tape, which is on a loop that records over itself after about
30 minutes, covered noises beginning about 10 minutes after the
airliner's tail engine failed, shooting debris that cut off the
plane's hydraulic control system.
   Pilot Alfred C. Haynes said the only way he and three other men
in the cockpit could steer and control elevation of the plane was by
applying power selectively to the two working jet engines.
   Here are the final seconds of the conversation before the plane
crashed in Sioux City as it was attempting an emergency landing:
   Haynes: ``Ease the power back, ease the power back.''
   First Officer William R. Records: ``Maybe you can pull 'em all
the way off.''
   Haynes: ``Left turns, left turns...close the throttles.''
   Records: ``Close 'em off.''
   Haynes: ``Right turn. Close the throttles.''
   Records: ``Pull 'em (all) off.'' The transcript indicates that
the word ``all'' is questionable.
   Training pilot Dennis E. Fitch: ``Nah. I can't pull 'em off or
we'll lose it. That's what's turnin' ya.''
   Two responses of ``okay'' are given but the speaker is not
identified. Then Records says, ``Left, Al,'' speaking to the
captain, followed by ``left throttle...left, left, left, left, left,
left, left, left, left left!''
   The transcript then shows one of the crewmen saying repeatedly
either ``we're turnin''' or ``we're tryin,'' and finally a single
word one second before impact: ``God.''
   Fitch, who was on the flight as a passenger, had been brought
into the cockpit to help in the landing and was manipulating the
speed controls. The plane crash-landed short of the runway with the
surviving two engines operating. There were 184 survivors.
   The board had previously released conversations between the
pilots and ground controllers, but had not included the separate
sounds of the cockpit recorder.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
