<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1158EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WitnessMoved     09-18 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Witness Moved,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witness in New York Police Killings Passes Lie Detector Test, Leaves
Town</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who was relocated here after
testifying in the killing of a New York City police officer was
moved again, and even his attorney says he doesn't know where the
man is now.
   The man, a Guyanese immigrant with the single name of Arjune,
came to local attention when he recently claimed that he was roughed
up by a police officer.
   He passed a private lie detector test on that claim, then was
quickly relocated under the federal witness program that brought him
to Spokane originally, attorney Carl Maxey said Friday.
   Arjune, who took the name of Amos Hardeen under his new identity,
was moved to Spokane secretly a year ago after he became a key
witness in the prosecution of two men accused of killing New York
City police officer Edward Byrne, whose death became a factor in
last year's presidential campaign when George Bush said it showed
the need for the death penalty.
   ``All I can tell you is that he's gone,'' said Maxey. ``Even I
don't know where they took him this time.''
   Arjune's cover was effectively blown in his run-in with local
police.
   This past week, he publicly discussed his arrest on Sept. 1 by
officer Patricia Madsen, saying she called him a racial slur,
accused him of being a drug dealer and struck him in the back while
he was arrested and taken to jail.
   Madsen said she stopped Arjune's car for speeding and suspected
him of being drunk. When a blood test showed he had not been
drinking, he was booked on charges of speeding and failure to stop
at a stop sign. He also was accused of resisting arrest.
   Police Chief Terry Mangan called Arjune a liar who ``thinks he is
above the law'' and said another polygraph examination cleared the
arresting officer.
   The New York murder case in which Arjune testified gained
national attention last year when Bush was given the badge from the
father of the slain officer.
   Bush last week also used the badge in a televised address to
schoolchildren about the dangers of drugs.
   Arjune, 47, lived in a crack-ravaged neighborhood in the New York
borough of Queens. Byrne, a 22-year-old rookie police officer, was
shot Feb. 26, 1988, as he guarded Arjune's house because of prior
threats against Arjune.
   Four men were convicted of second-degree murder and weapons
charges and were sentenced to 25 years to life in the killing.
   Arjune had led a quiet life in Spokane, working as a mechanic at
a Ford dealership.
   Armed federal agents were sent to guard Arjune as a moving van
cleared out his house in the Shiloh Hills area.
</TEXT>
