<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1205EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-IowaInvestigation 1stLd-Writethru a0553 09-18 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iowa Investigation, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0553,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede RICHMOND</HEAD>
<HEAD>Congressional Staffers Meet with GAO</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with meeting on probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House staff members met today with
congressional investigators to outline an inquiry an Ohio lawmaker
is seeking into the Navy's report on the explosion aboard the
battleship Iowa.
   Rep. Mary Rose Oakar last week asked the General Accounting
Office and the House Armed Services Committee to investigate the
thoroughness and impartiality of the Navy's probe.
   The Navy said it is standing by its investigation of the April 19
gun turret explosion that killed 47 sailors aboard the battleship.
The study concluded that sabotage by Clayton Hartwig, a gunner's
mate from Cleveland, ``most likely'' caused the blast.
   Aides to the House Banking economic stabilization subcommittee,
which Ms. Oakar chairs, met with GAO officials today to discuss
details of her request for an investigation.
   Media General News Service reported in a copyright story Sunday
that transcripts of interviews done by Navy investigators showed the
Iowa was a floating laboratory for high-explosive experiments at the
time of the blast.
   Investigators were also told improper gunpowder was being used in
experiments when the No. 2 turret exploded.
   ``Everything was very carefully considered,'' said Cmdr. Mark
Baker, a Navy spokesman at the Pentagon, who defended the Navy's
report on the explosion.
   The transcripts showed that the Navy command which requested the
experiments also performed the tests on the powder. Those tests led
to the Navy's conclusion about the cause of the explosion.
   A report the Pentagon released earlier this month said
circumstantial evidence indicated Hartwig sparked the explosion on
purpose. That conclusion could not be proved, however, because all
the witnesses died in the blast, the report added.
   Gunners were firing an experimental load from the No. 2 turret
with powder not approved for the weight of the projectile. The 7,007
pages of transcripts showed the tests were designed to improve the
accuracy and range of the ship's old 16-inch guns.
   The ship's gunners were using five 110-pound bags of the powder
instead of the normal charge of six bags of powder. The report said
the powder was clearly marked that it was not to be used with the
heavyweight projectiles being fired.
   The battleship's commander, Capt. Fred B. Moosally, told
investigators that he did not know a five-bag charge was going to be
used.
   Moosally said he approved the use of a ``reduced charge,'' but
said he thought that meant six 55-pound bags of powder.
   Investigators pursued the theory that Hartwig, who took over as
gun captain on short notice, perhaps was confused to see only five
bags of powder pop out from the powder cars instead of six, and that
somehow in the confusion the powder got rammed into the barrel too
quickly, splitting a bag open and setting off the powder by friction
with the projectile.
   The friction theory was eliminated by a series of technical tests
under the direction of the Naval Sea Systems Command at the Naval
Surface Warfare Center at Dahlgren, Va., the same command that
request and encouraged the tests aboard the Iowa.
   Sens. John Glenn and Howard Metzenbaum, both D-Ohio, last week
made a formal request to the Senate Armed Services Committe for
investigations.
   The letter from Glenn and Metzenbaum said Hartwig's reputation
``has been harmed beyond repair'' by the Navy report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
