<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1234EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-UMWStrike     09-18 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UMW Strike,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Fines Union $13.5 Million, Sit-In Continues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEBANON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today fined the United Mine Workers
$13.5 million _ nearly double the amount of his previous penalties _
for a litany of violations during a strike against the Pittston Coal
Group Inc.
   The UMW now has been fined $22 million by state and federal
judges for violations of injunctions limiting strike activity during
the 5{-month-old walkout.
   In two previous hearings, Russell County Circuit Judge Donald
McGlothlin fined the union $3 million and $4.5 million. U.S.
District Judge Glen Williams has fined the union about $1 million.
   McGlothlin imposed the new fine today after hearing testimony
last week on 60 charges alleged by Pittston.
   In addition to fines for specific incidents of violent and
non-violent violations of strike restrictions he issued in July and
August, the judge imposed a general penalty of $1 million against
the union for failing to control violence.
   Elsewhere today in Russell County, in western Virginia, UMW
members and an Appalachian religious leader continued to occupy
Pittston's main coal preparation plant.
   Outside the plant, 1,200 sympathizers staged a rally in support
of the often-bitter strike, state police spokesman Charlie Vaughan
said.
   Pittston elected against taking immediate action against the 99
people in the plant.
   ``Basically, we consider it trespassing, but as of right now,
nothing's been done,'' Pittston spokeswoman Susan Copeland said
Sunday night after the group entered the Moss No. 3 Preparation
Plant, where coal is cleaned, sorted and shipped. ``Management
people are over there in the area evaluating the situation.''
   When they entered the plant Sunday, the demonstrators said they
were protesting stalled contract talks and court actions since they
went on strike against Pittston on April 5.
   The demonstrators said they had enough provisions to last several
weeks, and they issued a statement saying they wanted their actions
to remain peaceful.
   The strike began when about 1,700 miners from Virginia and West
Virginia walked off their jobs at Pittston operations, and there has
been no resumption set for talks aimed at ending the walkout. After
negotiations broke off last week, UMW officials said they would wait
for Pittston to schedule the next round of discussions.
   At one point earlier this summer, the Pittston walkout sparked
sympathy wildcat walkouts that affected tens of thousands of UMW
members at other mines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
