<FIRST>u a PM-Youth-Murders 1stLd-Writethru a0487 09-18 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Youth-Murders, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0487,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen-ager Held in 1987 Murder and Triple-Slaying</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: NEW throughout to UPDATE with youth also charged with 1987 murder,
name of boy, other detail. No pickup. ADDS byline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARWICK, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 15-year-old boy was charged today with a
1987 slaying and the killings earlier this month of a Warwick woman
and her two daughters.
   Family Court Judge Carmine DiPetrillo said Craig Price was
charged with six counts: four of juvenile delinquency by reason of
first-degree murder and two of delinquency by reason of burglary.
   Price was arraigned under heavy security and was whisked away to
the state Training School, where he will be held until a
probable-cause hearing Thursday. Youths brought to the juvenile
court do not enter a plea until after the probable cause hearing.
   DiPetrillo ordered Price held ``for his protection and the
protection of the public.'' There was no doubt Price would be a
danger if released, the judge said.
   Price was arrested Sunday at a house one block away from where
Joan Heaton, 39, and her daughters, Jennifer, 10, and Melissa, 8,
were found stabbed to death in their home Sept. 4, said Police Chief
Wesley Blanchard.
   Heaton and her daughters had moved to the house four years ago,
following the 1983 suicide of her husband, neighbors said.
   DiPetrillo said Price is also accused of killing Rebecca A.
Spencer, 27, who lived several houses away from Price in 1987.
Police said earlier the murders at the two nearby homes were similar
and that they had suspected the same person committed them.
   Attorney General James E. O'Neil said the youth cannot be tried
as an adult because he is under 16, the minimum age at which a
juvenile can be tried in the adult court system.
   O'Neil said that if Price is convicted, the most severe
punishment he faces is placement in a juvenile detention center
until the age 21.
   Authorities said an intruder broke into the Heaton's home the
night of Sept. 4, but police said there was no apparent motive for
the killings.
   Warrick is a suburb just south of Providence.
</TEXT>
