<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--ProgramRow     09-18 0177</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Program Row,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Miss Saigon' Producer Ends Protest Over Cost of Programs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Theater impresario Cameron Mackintosh has agreed to
stop giving away programs to the new Andrew Lloyd Webber musical
``Miss Saigon,'' produced by Cameron Mackintosh.
   Stoll Moss Theaters Ltd. said Monday the producer promised to
stop giving away the booklets at the Theater Royal, where the
musical is in previews.
   The play, which has already sold $7.75 million worth of tickets,
premieres Wednesday. Mackintosh decided that $1.90 for a program was
too much, so he and 10 of his employees handed out free programs
last week.
   Although programs for plays are generally given away free in the
United States, theatergoers in England pay for them.
   Mackintosh said the protest followed weeks of arguments with the
Stoll Moss Group, owners of 13 theaters in London's West End.
   Last week, Stoll Moss' managing director, Roger Filey, said the
dispute was ``only a little squabble,'' but one that needed to be
resolved.
   Mackintosh has also produced ``Cats,'' ``The Phantom of the
Opera'' and ``Les Miserables.''
</TEXT>
