<DOCNO> AP890918-0094 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1311EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-PeacePlans-Glance     09-18 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peace Plans-Glance,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Main Points of Egyptian, Israeli Peace Plans</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Egypt-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's 10-point
peace plan has divided the major parties in Israel's coalition
Cabinet, with the right-wing Likud bloc against the plan and the
left-leaning Labor Party accepting it in principle.
   Here, at a glance, are the major points of Mubarak's plan; the
Likud and Labor positions; and an outline of Israel's peace plan
calling for Palestinian elections in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip, which Mubarak's proposals are meant to supplement.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EGYPT'S PLAN</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _Israel must accept the U.S-backed formula of trading land for
peace.
   _The 140,000 residents of Israeli-annexed East Jerusalem must
vote in any Palestinian elections in the occupied territories.
   _The building of Jewish settlements in the occupied lands must be
frozen.
   _The Palestinian delegation to preliminary talks with Israel in
Cairo must include Palestinians from outside the occupied lands _
possibly residents who were deported.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>LABOR STAND</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Labor accepts Egypt's plan as a means to start peace talks. It
accepts the formula of trading land for peace and voting by east
Jerusalemites.
   Labor officials agree to a freeze on Jewish settlements once
talks begin and suggest they would accept a role for deported
Palestinians in peace talks.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>LIKUD STAND</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Likud rejects Mubarak's plan as a threat to Israel's security. It
opposes trading land for peace, participation in voting by east
Jerusalem Arabs, and freezing settlements.
   Likud officials say talking to deported Palestinians would be
opening the way for talks with the Palestinian Liberation
Organization, which Israel considers a terrorist organization.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>THE ISRAELI PLAN:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _Elections in the occupied lands will chose Palestinians to
negotiate with Israel on interim self-rule. The final status of the
territories will be decided later.
   _The U.S.-sponsored Camp David accords with Egypt will serve as
the basis for future negotiations.
   _A comprehensive peace settlement must be reached with all Arab
nations.
   _An international effort will resolve the problems of Palestinian
refugees in the West Bank and Gaza.
</TEXT>
