<FIRST>u w PM-Pentagon-Drugs 2ndLd-Writethru a0575-a0579-a0432 09-18
0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pentagon-Drugs, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0575-a0579-a0432,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheney Highlights Pentagon Role in Bush Drug Battle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs, editing throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, declaring the
war on drugs a national security problem, ordered Pentagon chiefs
today to plan an attack on drug flow across the nation's borders
with stepped-up use of planes, radar and troops.
   ``I believe that our military forces have the capability to make
a substantial contribution toward drug interdiction, and I am asking
them to make the necessary preparations to carry out that
responsibility,'' Cheney said.
   In a news conference called to highlight the Pentagon's role in
President Bush's war on drugs, Cheney offered no specifics on how
much new money or personnel would be devoted to interdicting drugs
at the borders.
   He said he could not even give a ballpark cost estimate until the
plans are drawn up.
   Cheney said the Defense Department will not be drawn into a law
enforcement role in the anti-drug battle, and U.S. forces overseas
will not be put in combat situations.
   ``There's a clear line out there,'' Cheney said, that the
military will not cross.
   He acknowledged that using U.S. military personnel to train other
nations' forces can put people at risk.
   `It's a dangerous business. I hope nobody's hurt in the process,
but I can't guarantee it,'' Cheney said.
   Cheney ordered the nation's top military commanders to come up
with plans by Oct. 15 to help stem the flow of drugs through the
Caribbean and across the Mexican border.
   Cheney said he would instruct commanders to plan for:
   _A ``substantial'' Caribbean counter-narcotics task force, with
appropriate planes and ships, to cut the drug flow from Latin
America.
   _Deploying forces to support the counter-narcotics work of U.S.
law enforcement agencies and ``cooperating foreign governments,''
especially on the nation's southern border and the border with
Mexico.
   _Using NORAD (North American Aerospace Defense Command) to help
detect and counter illegal drug traffic across the borders.
   _Plan to combat the production and trafficking of illegal drugs
in conjunction with ``cooperating host countries.''
   Congress has been pressing the Pentagon to do more in the war on
drugs while military leaders have expressed reluctance about using
their ever-dwindling resources to enter a domestic war against
civilian drug-smugglers.
   But Cheney has convinced some military doubters of the need for a
new approach, primarily because of the size of the crack cocaine
epidemic and because the White House has demanded a new emphasis on
the issue, said a senior Defense Department official who did not
wish to be identified.
   Cheney plans to attack the problem of competing interests in the
drug war by improving ways of sharing intelligence information among
the agencies.
   One large question that remains unresolved is where the money for
the drug battle will be found.
   The official said Cheney's plan will not require any more funding
than that proposed by Bush, whose initial strategy has been widely
criticized on Capitol Hill for not being adequately funded or going
far enough.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890918-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1318EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Politics     09-18 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Politics,0749</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jiang Zemin's Road to the Top Could Be Rocky</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jiang Zemin, the Communist Party chief whose name
has surfaced as the possible heir to senior leader Deng Xiaoping,
faces keen rivals and the vagaries of Chinese politics in any future
bid for greater power.
   Deng, China's 85-year-old patriarch, named the former Shanghai
mayor as his heir in ``informal talks'' with other senior officials
in May and June, The New York Times said Monday.
   Diplomats and Chinese sources, however, say Jiang's ascendancy
will be far from automatic.
   Deng's statements, which the Times said referred to Jiang as the
``core'' of the new generation of Chinese leaders, came as the
Communist Party moved to purge reformist party chief Zhao Ziyang.
   Zhao, accused of supporting the student-led, pro-democracy
movement crushed by the military June 3-4, was ousted from all his
posts on June 24 and replaced by Jiang.
   Jiang, 62, by assuming leadership of the 47-million-member
Communist Party, became the post powerful political figure in China
besides Deng, who retains the last word in all major decisions
although he has resigned from all but one of his official posts.
   Deng is still chairman of the Central Military Commission, a
crucial post in a nation where the military has a major say in
politics, particularly after the military suppression of student
dissent in June.
   Deng, widely reported to be suffering from prostate cancer, would
have approved Jiang as party chief with the understanding that Jiang
would become first among equals once Deng passes from the scene.
   But the former engineer and minister of the Electronics Industry
has had little experience in party politics and fewer ties to the
military.
   He has been in Shanghai the past four years as mayor and party
secretary and is said to lack the personal allegiances in Beijing
needed to sustain him in a serious power struggle.
   Jiang is certainly also aware that being Deng's heir apparent is
a highly dangerous position. The last two in his place were both
ousted from their jobs in disgrace for being too lenient toward
student demonstrators.
   The late party General Secretary Hu Yaobang was the first to go,
in January 1986, followed by Zhao in June. Zhao is reportedly under
house arrest and could still face criminal charges for allegedly
supporting what the government calls the ``counterrevolutionary
rebellion'' of this spring.
   Jiang, like Hu and Zhao, has been a solid supporter of Deng's
market-oriented reforms. While in Shanghai, Jiang, who speaks good
English, worked hard to attract foreign investment and modernize
industry in China's largest city.
   Unlike his two predecessors, Jiang has tried to solidify his
position by coming down hard on the need for party discipline and
loyalty to China's socialist system.
   ``We must sternly observe unified party discipline, namely: the
individual obeys the group, the minority obeys the majority, the
lower levels obey the upper levels, the whole party obeys the
center,'' he wrote in a recently published essay. ``We cannot allow
the unchecked spread of individualism, separatism and
money-worship.''
   If Deng were to suddenly leave the scene, Jiang would almost
certainly face strong competition for power from party
conservatives, led by Premier Li Peng and President Yang Shangkun.
   Yang, a robust 82, is a former general who has been general
secretary of the Central Military Commission for the past eight
years. He is the only viable choice at the moment to become chairman
of the commission if Deng were to depart, giving him powerful
leverage in any future political maneuverings.
   Yang is a comrade of Deng's going back to the civil war against
the Nationalists, but some observers feel Deng may try to hold on to
his commission post for a few more years to give Jiang more time to
build up his support within the party.
   Li, 60, joined Yang in declaring martial law in Beijing and
ordering the troops to attack the students and their supporters. He
is thought to be ambitious, and has proved to be ruthless.
   Another variable is the reformists _ Zhao and his supporters who
have been beaten into silence at the moment but, considering the
unpredictable nature of Chinese politics, could stage a comeback.
   If that happens, Jiang could turn out to be only a stopgap party
chief who will be washed into obscurity when the political tide
turns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
