<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Turkey-Strike     09-18 0153</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Turkey-Strike,0157</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands of Iron and Steel Workers End Strike in Turkey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of employees ended a 4{-month-old
strike and returned to work at two state-run iron and steel plans
Monday after management approved a new contract granting them wage
increases.
   It was the longest, major strike in Turkey since the return to
civilian rule in 1983, and union officials said it cost Turkey
nearly $600 million.
   Strikes were banned during military rule in 1980-1983.
   Feridun Tankut, a spokesman for the independent Celik-Is Union,
said the talks were successfully concluded Sunday when management
agreed to increase workers' monthly wages from $60 to $310.
   He added that the workers will receive an additional 45 percent
increase in 1990, the last year of the two-year contract.
   Because of high inflation _ 75 percent last year and expected to
rise _ workers have been demanding large wage increases in contract
talks.
</TEXT>
