<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1355EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AIDS-Reporting     09-18 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Reporting,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Official Says Victims' Privacy Protected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The director of the national AIDS program
office of the Public Health Service said Monday the government is
getting information to fight the disease while protecting the
privacy of its victims.
   Though the federal government has not enacted confidentiality
laws aimed specifically at AIDS patients, states have, Dr. James
Allen told the House Energy and Commerce subcommittee on health and
the environment.
   ``State legal controls as well as the ethical traditions of the
health professions, and the management and administrative practices
of health care institutions, all protect the privacy of patients,''
Allen said.
   He said that when information about a person's HIV status is
disclosed, it is to help treatment of the patient and protect public
health.
   Allen was called before the subcommittee to summarize a report
requested by Congress and issued Monday on state confidentiality
laws regarding AIDS patients.
   Subcommittee chairman Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., said AIDS
patients had to be willing to seek treatment with the assurance they
would be protected from prosecution if they got the illness through
an illegal act such as intravenous drug use or homosexual relations,
which in some states is illegal.
   ``The Centers for Disease Control concluded in 1987 that hundreds
of thousands Americans should be counseled and tested for AIDS, but
that fears of breaches of confidentiality pose a major barrier to
getting these people into clinics,'' Waxman said.
   Allen said that besides the action taken by states to ensure
privacy, anti-discrimination legislation such as that recently
passed by the Senate would make AIDS victims more likely to come
forward.
   The proposed federal Americans with Disabilities Act, supported
by President Bush and awaiting action by the House, would prohibit
employers and others from discriminating against people with any one
of a wide range of physical or mental disabilities and is considered
the most expansive civil rights legislation since the Civil Rights
Act of 1964.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
