<FIRST>r a AM-CampMurder     09-18 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Camp Murder,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mistaken Identity Leads to Slaying, Jailing of 77-Year-Old on Murder
Charge</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: `He' in 4th graf is correct.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANCASTER, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elderly man mistook another man for
someone he believed wronged him 10 years ago, and slit the man's
throat during a church camp meeting, authorities said Monday.
   James W. McGriff, 77, of Fayetteville, N.C., was charged with
murder after Sunday's slaying and remained in jail Monday pending a
bond hearing, Lancaster County Sheriff Williford Faile said.
   McGriff was accused of killing Daniel McCain, 66, of Monroe,
N.C., during a meeting attended by 200 to 300 people in an open
shelter at Steele Hill Methodist Church.
   Connie Belk said he sat next to McGriff during the meeting.
   ``They were between preachers, and (McGriff) ... just looked over
and said, `I'll be back directly,''' Belk said. ``He walked back six
or eight steps. ... I heard a noise, like `Ow!' or something behind
me, and I turned around. He had a knife with blood on it in his
hand.''
   McGriff mistakenly thought McCain had drugged his communion wine
at a similar church meeting 10 years and then laughed at him when he
awoke after passing out, the sheriff said.
   When he learned McCain, a retired public works employee, was not
the man he thought, McGriff said ``I cut the wrong man,'' the
sheriff said.
