<DOCNO> AP890918-0111 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1453EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-US-Hungary 1stLdWritethru a0595 09-18 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Hungary, 1st Ld Writethru, a0595,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Offering Economic Benefits to Hungary</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs graf 2, It would, to CORRECT statement that it would make
Hungary first Eastern European nation having such status. It's first since
enactment of amendment in 1974.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commerce Department announced today the
United States is prepared to provide Hungary with a wide series of
business and economic benefits, including permanent
most-favored-nation trade status.
   It would make Hungary the first Eastern European nation having
such status since enactment of the Jackson-Vanik Amendment in 1974
tying those benefits to free emigration policies, the department
said. Yugoslavia and Poland also have MFN status, but obtained
theirs before 1974.
   In addition, Commerce Secretary Robert A. Mosbacher said the
United States is prepared to improve tariff treatment of Hungarian
products, extend development programs and create a $25 million fund
to help create private business in the Marxist country.
   ``This step is an important part of implementing President Bush's
goal of building an American partnership with Hungary,'' Mosbacher
said in a statement following a meeting with Hungarian Trade
Minister Tamas Beck in Budapest. A copy was made available here.
   ``Such an agreement is fundamental for private sector business
because it would contain investment protection gauartees which boost
confidence and open the way to substantially increased U.S. private
investment in Hungary,'' Mosbacher said.
   He said Beck agreed to open negotiations on the proposals.
   Mosbacher said the proposals include granting Hungary permanent
most-favored-nation trade status in October if the Hungarian
parliament, as expected, enacts legislation on freedom of emigration
by the end of September.
   Such status assures that exports to the United States will not
face discriminatory tariffs. Hungary now receives such benefits only
on a year-to-year basis.
   Mosbacher also said the plan calls for extending Generalized
System of Preferences treatment that would offer Hungarian exporters
duty-free tariff treatment for a broad range of exports to the
United States.
   The commerce secretary said Bush also has submitted to Congress
legislation to extend Overseas Private Investment Corp. programs to
Hungary and create a $256 million Private Enterprise Fund.
   OPIC programs would provide investment guarantees to U.S.
companies investing in Hungary and the enterprise fund would help
establish of private business there.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890918-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1501EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-People     09-18 0810</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0845</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Aykroyd, one of the original Blues
Brothers, says the 1990s will be ripe for a rebirth of the Memphis
sound.
   ``The Memphis sound is fat,'' said the comedian-singer, who
performed as his alter-ego, Elwood Blues, at a concert for the
groundbreaking of The Great American Pyramid, an
entertainment-sports complex.
   ``I guess for me it's the combination of everything. Mainly,
probably just the rhythm and the horns. You can't stop them. It's
just danceable, that's what I loved.''
   Aykroyd, who created the Blues Brothers team with the late John
Belushi on segments of Saturday Night Live, said he is a fan of
Memphis, New Orleans and Chicago blues.
   ``The Chicago electrified sound kind of rides over everything,''
he said. ``Guitar playing in Memphis music sort of builds into that
whole fatness.''
   Aykroyd said he hopes the new complex rejuvenates the Memphis
music scene.
   ``Wherever in the world we can find a city that can bring back an
individual sound and call it its own, I think we should try to
encourage it,'' he said before Friday's concert.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Philip is planning a visit to Southeast Asia
next month to promote nature conservation, Buckingham Palace
announced Monday.
   The Prince will visit Thailand, Singapore, Indonesia, Malaysia,
Brunei and India from Oct. 17 to Nov. 5 as international president
of the Worldwide Fund for Nature, according to palace officials.
   Queen Elizabeth II's husband will call on the King of Thailand,
President Suharto of Indonesia and the Sultan of Brunei.
   Philip has been president of the Fund, formerly known as the
World Wildlife Fund, since 1981 and travels widely promoting its
cause.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>COLBERT, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Woody Harrelson plays a bartender on the
television show ``Cheers'' but he might have a future playing golf.
   Harrelson sank a 6-foot putt under coaching from teammate and pro
golfer Tim Simpson during the second annual Kenny Rogers Classic
weekend sports competition. Sunday's crucial stroke gave his team
the championship title.
   ``The single most exciting event in my entire life,'' Harrelson
said after his putt and a congratulatory lift from another teammate,
Michael Jordan, a star with the NBA's Chicago Bulls.
   ``Are you going to put out a golf video now?'' asked Alan Thicke,
star of TV's ``Growing Pains.''
   Other athletes in the event were Dominique Wilkins of the Atlanta
Hawks, former NBA star Julius ``Doctor J'' Erving and tennis pro
Jimmy Connors.
   The events were staged on Rogers' 1,200-acre Beaver Dam Farms,
featuring an 18-hole golf course, three tennis courts, a horse barn
large enough to house a basketball court and several stocked lakes.
   It drew 10,000 spectators and raised $40,000 for homeless
shelters in the Athens area, 15 miles southwest of Rogers' farm.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GRAND FORKS, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Willie Nelson became an honorary North
Dakota Centennial Farmer in recognition of his Farm Aid concerts,
but he said his songs are not enough to solve their problems.
   State Agriculture Commissioner Sarah Vogel presented a centennial
plaque and several state-made products to Nelson, who performed
before an estimated 1,800 people Sunday night.
   The performance was not an official Farm Aid concert, but was one
in a series at the University of North Dakota.
   Nelson, founder and chairman of Farm Aid, Inc., said his Farm Aid
concerts have raised more than $10 million since they began in 1985.
But he acknowledged their limitations.
   ``It's sort of a drop in the bucket in one way,'' he said.
``These people have been helped, but their problems haven't been
solved.''
   He said there is no longer any incentive for young people to
pursue careers in farming, and that will eventually bring a crisis
in the industry.
   But Vogel was optimistic.
   ``Farm Aid has made a lot of difference in North Dakota,'' she
said. ``People have food that they wouldn't have without Farm Aid.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GLENBROOK, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grammy Award-winning singer Toni Tennille
says she prefers the grandeur of the countryside to the glitter of
show business.
   Tennille, who along with her husband, Daryl Dragon, are better
known as The Captain and Tennille, said they officially ended their
touring act this year to pursue other interests.
   Since moving to this resort community on Lake Tahoe's east shore
in 1984, Tennille has become an avid hiker who has conquered the
Tahoe Basin's highest peaks and climbed Mount Whitney twice. At
14,495 feet, Whitney is the highest peak in the continental U.S.
   She also formed a hiking group called Women in the Sierra, which
makes annual week-long treks into the Sierra high country.
   ``It's like being a Girl Scout again,'' said Tennille, now 49 and
a self-described environmentalist. ``You leave your husband, the
kids, the telephones, the fax machines, everything behind and just
see the land the way it was before we screwed it up.''
</TEXT>
