<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1645EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Malaysia-King     09-18 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Malaysia-King,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ninth King of Malaysia Installed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARI S. MANIAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sultan Azlan Shah on Monday raised
a ceremonial sword and kissed its hilt in a ceremony installing him
as the ninth king of this former British colony.
   As the 61-year-old former Supreme Court justice carried out the
ceremony, which dates back five centuries, his wife, Tuanku Bainun,
seated on the royal yellow throne with a diamond tiara,
automatically became queen of the 17 million Malaysians.
   Palace officials involved in the ceremony at the chandeliered
throne room of the white-domed National Palace said it was not
called a coronation, as in the West, because at no point is a crown
placed on the king's head.
   The king wore a white tengkolok, or Malay royal headdress, made
of silk with the state crest in diamonds pinned at the top. He
entered the ceremonial room in a black suit embroidered with golden
thread.
   Soon after the king was seated on the throne, he was presented
with the kris by the Lord Chamberlain. He rose and kissed the sword,
which has a wavy blade and is embedded with precious stones.
   The ceremony was witnessed by Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad and
690 invited guests.
   Also present was Malaysia's first Prime Minister, Tunku Abdul
Rahman, who invented the system of electing Malaysia's national king
for a five-year term by secret ballot from among the nine rulers, or
sultans, of nine Malay states.
   Tunku, himself a prince from Kedah state, wanted to preserve the
monarchy after Malaysia gained independence in 1957. Since all the
sultans wanted to be king, it was decided they would meet and vote
by secret ballot, electing one for a five-year term, after which he
would return to rule his own state.
   Another sultan is elected deputy king, acting for the king when
he is abroad or ill.
   Sultan Azlan was elected king in a secret ballot March 2.
   He was sworn into office April 26 and began his duties before
Monday's formal installation _ a national holiday complete with
fireworks displays, music, dance and other public entertainment.
   Malaysia's king is a constitutional head of state like Britain's
Queen Elizabeth II or Emperor Akihito of Japan. Political power
rests with a British-style national parliament and the prime
minister.
   Sultan Azlan and his deputy head the Moslem religion in Malaysia.
   The new king was born Raja Azlan on April 19, 1928 to one of the
Perak Royal Families of the Batu Gajah district, 80 miles north of
Kuala Lumpur.
   He studied in local schools before attending Nottingham
University in England, graduating with a law degree in 1955. He then
returned to Malaysia and joined the legal service, becoming in 1982
Lord President of the Supreme Court, the highest ranking judge in
Malaysia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
