<FIRST>r a AM-EthiopianTalks     09-18 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethiopian Talks,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peace Talks Resume Tuesday at Carter Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of Ethiopia and the Eritrean
rebels return to the negotiating table Tuesday to resume preliminary
peace talks they hope could pave the way to ending their 28-year war.
   The delegations recessed over the weekend while former President
Jimmy Carter was in Nicaragua on a fact-finding mission. Tuesday
will be the ninth day of negotiations at the Atlanta-based Carter
Center.
   Carter Center officials are not sure whether the talks will end
Tuesday, said center spokeswoman Beth Carpenter.
   Carter said Friday that the Ethiopian government and the Eritrean
People's Liberation Front had agreed to hold additional talks in
Africa and had made much progress toward setting an agenda for those
talks.
   He said they agreed on items such as the official languages,
publicity, recording and procedural rules for the talks, which would
be held in one or more of these nations: North Yemen, Egypt, Sudan,
Kenya, Tanzania and Zimbabwe.
   About 1 million people have died in fighting and famine related
to the war over the independence of Eritrea, a northern province in
the Horn of Africa that contains Ethiopia's only direct access to
the Red Sea.
   The Eritrean Front in the past has demanded that the people of
Eritrea be allowed to vote on whether they want independence,
federation with Ethiopia or autonomy. The Ethiopian government,
which has proposed a greater measure of autonomy for its
northernmost province, has unequivocally ruled out any referendum.
   Carter has acted as a neutral observer at the Atlanta talks,
which were convened Sept. 7 to draft an agenda for future,
substantive peace negotiations.
   Carter has said the delegations are ``so proud of what they've
done so far'' by holding the talks ``that they are inclined to look
upon this partial success as adequate.''
   The talks have included joint meetings between the Ethiopians and
Eritreans as well as separate sessions with Carter and each side.
</TEXT>
