<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1527EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-AIDS-Prisoners Bjt   09-18 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Prisoners, Bjt,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than Four Percent of Prisoners Infected with AIDS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blood tests of prison and jail inmates across the
country show that about one in 24 is infected with the AIDS virus,
fewer than expected, researchers said Monday.
   The study is the first to try to estimate the prevalence of AIDS
in prisoners, said its principal author, Dr. Ford Brewer of the
Johns Hopkins University School of Hygiene and Public Health in
Baltimore.
   The 11,198 inmates in the study came from 10 prisons and jails.
   ``They were selected to give us a pretty good overall picture''
of the extent of AIDS infection in inmates, Brewer said at a meeting
of the American Society for Microbiology, where he presented his
results.
   Of the inmates tested, 476, or 4.25 percent, were infected with
AIDS, Brewer reported. Smaller local studies by others had found
infection rates of up to 3.2 percent among prisoners, with the
exception of one New York City study that found 17.4 percent of
inmates were infected, Brewer said.
   Brewer found the highest rates of infection, up to 8 percent, in
the mid-Atlantic states, reflecting the high prevalence of AIDS
infections in that population, he said. As few as 2.7 percent of the
inmates were infected in one jail on the West Coast.
   The figures at all the institutions were lower than expected,
Brewer said. ``Most of these prison and jails thought it was going
to be four or five times as high,'' he said.
   That is because other surveys have found that between 27 percent
and 41 percent of inmates report that they are intravenous drug
abusers, and between 3.6 percent and 7 percent report that they have
engaged in homosexual activity.
   Homosexuals and intravenous drug abusers are the groups most
affected by AIDS so far.
   Blood for the testing was obtained from the inmates during
routine medical screening when they entered the jails and prisons,
Brewer said. The blood was frozen and immediately shipped to Johns
Hopkins for testing.
   Brewer said 3,136 cases of AIDS had been reported among prisoners
as of October 1988. With about 3 million adults in prisons and jails
in the United States, his estimate of the number infected with the
AIDS virus suggests that the number of cases will climb as infected
inmates become ill.
   Corrections officials will be required to prepare for treatment
of these inmates, he said. Furthermore, education and monitoring of
inmates can help slow the spread of AIDS, Brewer said.
   The study was conceived in 1984, but Brewer faced numerous
obstacles in getting permission to test inmates' blood for AIDS.
   ``Everybody was concerned that big brother was going to swoop
down'' and that the testing would result in discrimination against
the prisoners, Brewer said.
   The study was funded by the federal Centers for Disease Control
in Atlanta. The CDC is now taking over the study and incorporating
it into its surveys of AIDS infection, said Ida Onorato of the CDC.
   Onorato reported in a separate study that the rate of AIDS
infection among intravenous drug abusers going to drug treatment
clinics ranged as high as 48.8 percent.
   Infection rates were highest in the East and in metropolitan
areas, as they were with the prison study, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
