<FIRST>r w AM-Housing-Democrats     09-18 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Housing-Democrats,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Task Force Formed to Assess Nation's Needs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate Democratic task force to assess the
nation's housing needs and recommend reforms in the Department of
Housing and Urban Development was named Monday by Majority Leader
George Mitchell.
   Sen. Alan Cranston of California, named to head the eight-member
task force, said one of its purposes will be to prod the Bush
administration to take a position on housing for the disadvantaged.
   ``There are still people in the administration who don't want to
see any national housing programs,'' Cranston said.
   He said the eventual aim is to forge a bipartisan approach on
housing and produce a bill President Bush will sign.
   ``The problems of housing affordability are not going away; they
continue to build pressure on millions of Americans,'' Cranston said
in a statement.
   ``Young failies find it harder to buy their first home. Older
people can't find housing that enables them to live with dignity and
independence. The supply of decent housing that low-income people
can afford is fast disappearing. Homelessness remains a shame on the
nation.''
   Mitchell said the task force will issue a report and make
recommendations by the end of the year. He said comprehensive
housing legislation ``will be a high priority for next year.''
   Cranston said he believes such a bill should include a sweeping
overhaul of HUD.
   ``It should prevent any repeat of the recent scandal by ensuring
that HUD resources are used fairly to provide as much decent,
affordable housing as possible where it is most needed,'' he said.
``Insider dealing, rip-offs by consultants and excessive profits
through double-dipping must be eliminated with stiff penalties.''
   Cranston said the legislation also should modernize and rebuild
the Federal Housing Administration, holding managers accountable for
financing and program effectiveness and bringing up to date
financial controls and accounting systems.
   At present, he said, unrealistic FHA mortgage regulations have
``knocked FHA (loans) totally out of the market in many parts of the
country,''
   The bill also should seek to build a national network of
partnerships, including states, communities, private industry,
non-profit organizations and the federal government, to provide an
adequate supply of affordable housing, Cranston said.
   Other members of the task force are Sens. Christopher Dodd,
D-Conn.; Bob Graham, D-Fla.; John Kerry, D-Mass.; Barbara Mikulski,
D-Md.; Donald Riegle, D-Mich.; Terry Sanford, D-N.C., and Paul
Sarbanes, D-Md.
</TEXT>
