<FIRST>r a AM-LandlordConvicted     09-18 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Landlord Convicted,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Landlord Convicted in Fire Deaths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A landlord whose boardinghouse was
gutted by a fire that killed eight people was convicted Monday of
criminally negligent homicide because the building failed to meet
safety standards.
   State Supreme Court Justice Nicholas Colabella convicted Frank
Thomas, 67, of two counts but acquitted him of five additional
counts. He had dismissed an eighth count earlier.
   Colabella's verdict came after a two-week, non-jury trial in New
York state's trial-level court.
   Thomas, who lives in New Rochelle, had been charged with the
deaths of the eight people because the boardinghouse violated
several provisions of the fire code. A fire door was missing, and
the front door was secured by a double dead-bolt lock, which
required a key from the inside to open.
   Thomas was convicted on the two counts in the deaths of Abraham
Wilson, 52, and Allen Piroleau, 61, whose bodies were found by the
door they could not open.
   The Jan. 15 blaze began in the basement of the building through a
resident's careless smoking and spread rapidly.
   Thomas declined to comment on the verdict. He faces 1 1-3 to four
years in prison on each count when he is sentenced Nov. 2.
   His attorney, Neal Comer, said he would appeal.
   He argued that building and fire inspectors had never cited
Thomas for the failure to have a fire retardant door between floors.
Comer said the special lock had been requested by the tenants, who
were concerned about drug addicts outside.
   Westchester District Attorney Carl Vergari's office seized
records of city agencies to determine why full inspections had not
been done in as much as a decade.
</TEXT>
