<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1946EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SouthernGovernors     09-18 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Southern Governors,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Southern Governors Address Economic Development</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State and local governments must form
partnerships with private industry if the United States is to regain
its position as a leader in the global economy, southern governors
were told Monday.
   Top industry representatives told the Southern Governors'
Association that a skilled work force, fair treatment by government
regulators and a cooperative spirit between government and business
are key to improving the United States' position in the industrial
world.
   The governors must work harder to keep plants from relocating to
other countries, said Edgar S. Woolard, chairman and chief executive
of Wilmington-based Du Pont Co.
   ``The fastest economic growth over the next 10 years will be
outside the United States,'' Woolard said, adding that companies
``must locate in the spot where we can best serve customers.''
   The education of America's future workers also preoccupied
members of the association _ which represents 17 states, Puerto Rico
and the U.S. Virgin Islands _ on the first day of their three-day
annual meeting.
   ``From our perspective, we need people with basic skills,''
Woolard said. He said industry should cooperate with government to
help identify skills that are expected to be in demand, and help
provide needed training programs.
   Ira Magaziner, an author and international corporate consultant,
said that in addition to improving education, states should support
research and development activities that benefit industry.
   ``We have to take drastic steps ... and think very boldly about
the future ... to make us competitive again,'' Magaziner said.
   Peter H. Mills, chief administrative officer of Sematech, a
superconductor research company in Austin, Texas, cautioned the
governors not to court businesses indiscriminately.
   ``You must understand the needs of the company. ... You must
understand the competition in a global perspective,'' Mills said.
``States should not be encouraged to pursue every economic
development advantage that comes down the street,'' but instead
concentrate on what the state needs and has to offer.
   Magaziner added that states ought to look beyond nailing down an
initial agreement for a new business to open.
   In other countries, government officials continue negotiating
with new businesses ``to get them to deepen what they are doing
there. ... European companies are used to that kind of dialogue and
probably would be open to that.''
   Premier David Peterson of Ontario, Canada, held a breakfast
meeting with some of the governors, and told them he was initially
opposed to the U.S.-Canadian free trade agreement signed in January.
   Peterson said that although he now supports it, strength of the
new settlement is untested. ``We don't know how it's going to shake
down,'' he said.
   He said Ontario did about $84 billion in trade with the Great
Lakes Region last year, compared to $18 billion with the South.
Ontario now has an office in Atlanta and officials there hope to
increase trade with the Southern states.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
