<FIRST>r a AM-MissAmerica     09-18 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Miss America,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miss America: Photographers `Looked Like Aliens'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY37</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Debbye Turner said Monday that she hopes to use
her new Miss America title to get ahead in her chosen field:
veterinary medicine.
   ``I'll milk it for all it's worth,'' joked the University of
Missouri-Columbia Veterinary School senior. ``If being Miss America
can get me into an intern program, I'll certainly use it.''
   Miss Turner, who was crowned Saturday night, insisted she's not
angling for a modeling or movie career. But she added that she's
``not a fortune teller'' and said she's prepared to ``accept
anything that life wants to hand me.''
   At her first New York appearance, Miss Turner said she would seek
to motivate youth to reach for lofty goals and resist peer pressure.
In that vein, she will ``tell them about my experiences growing up,
tell them about some of the mistakes that I've made and how I think
that they can make their life a little easier by setting some goals
and being determined.''
   What were some of her mistakes?
   ``Not keeping up with piano lessons, not being more diligent in
high school in my studies.''
   Miss Turner confided that although she was an ``A'' student, ``I
had no study skills. ... I had to develop my skills at veterinary
school, which is a bad place to do it.''
   A day after becoming the third black woman to wear the crown,
Miss Turner said that her race ``is the very least of who I am. I
had nothing to do with it, and that's not landmark. I just came that
way.''
   When told of a black person who was disappointed with that
statement, Miss Turner said she was sorry _ then reiterated her
feelings.
   ``Certainly, I've gained and grown from the experiences that I've
had to confront as being an ethnic minority in this country,'' she
said.
   ``However, I grew up in the South; I'm a veterinary student; I'm
hard working; I'm self-motivated; I'm a Christian. And those are all
a part of who I am,'' she said. ``I'm certainly proud of who I am _
I'm not ashamed of it at all _ but I don't think I'm limited to
being black.''
   Asked how to improve race relations, she said, ``Start teaching,
from a very young age, that merit is based upon substance on the
inside and not upon the decoration on the outside.''
   After the news conference, she posed with a hot dog from vendor
Gamal Ahmed, who came here from Egypt two years ago.
   ``What's Miss America?'' said the befuddled vendor as
photographers nudged him aside.
   On Tuesday, Miss Turner's 24th birthday, she will pose for
official portraits, appear with Donald Trump and possibly appear on
the David Letterman show.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
