<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1953EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NewDestroyer     09-18 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-New Destroyer,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armed Services Subcommittee Chairman Defends New Destroyer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of a House subcommittee defended
the Navy's new $1.2 billion destroyer Monday, calling another
lawmaker's claims that the ship is a ``procurement nightmare'' a
disservice to the Navy and all involved.
   Rep. Charles E. Bennett, chairman of the House Armed Services
subcommittee on seapower and strategic and critical materials, said
that on-site inspections by the panel, testimony and briefings show
that work on the DDG-51 destroyer ``is going as well as any in
recent history.''
   ``The design concept is sound, drawings have been produced in a
timely manner and the ship will be delivered to the Navy in a
reasonable amount of time,'' the Florida Democrat said.
   The ship, named the Arleigh Burke for the World War II naval hero
and former chief of naval operations, was launched Saturday in Bath,
Maine.
   Bennett's comments about the guided-missile destroyer came in a
two-page letter to Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the House
Energy and Commerce subcommittee on oversight and investigations.
   Dingell, in a letter last week to Navy Secretary H. Lawrence
Garrett III, charged that construction of the destroyer has been
marked by cost overruns and schedule delays. He said a preliminary
report by the General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of
Congress, showed that the destroyer is 18 months behind schedule and
only 38 percent complete.
   ``The acquisition of the DDG-51 has turned into a procurement
nightmare,'' Dingell said.
   Bennett, in his letter, told Dingell that ``while it is a truism
that there is always room for improvement, to state that the
construction on DDG-51 is a `procurement nightmare' does a
significant disservice to this committee, the Navy and its personnel
and contractors.''
   Bennett said cost overruns and change orders are common in the
production of any new major ship and, in fact, shipbuilding
contracts expect increases in cost and change orders because of the
long construction time and uncertainties about the design.
</TEXT>
