<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1954EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Mandela     09-18 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mandela,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Official Says Mandela Could Be Freed Within Weeks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nelson Mandela, the African National Congress
leader, could be freed within weeks, a South African Cabinet
minister said in a British radio interview on Monday.
   But Desmond Tutu, the Anglican archbishop of Cape Town and a
leading anti-apartheid campaigner, said it would be ``disastrous''
to release Mandela without lifting state of emergency regulations
that restrict black political activity in South Africa.
   The South African minister for constitutional development, Gerrit
Viljoen, said the release of Mandela and ``other people who have
been convicted of security offenses is a matter very high on the
agenda of the government.''
   Asked if Mandela's release could be within weeks, Viljoen said,
``I think it could.''
   Speculation that Mandela soon will be freed grew after the
re-election victory this month of the whites-only National Party
under a new leader, F.W. de Klerk, who has promised reforms. Under
apartheid, the country's black majority does not have the vote.
   Mandela, 71, was sentenced to life imprisonment in 1964 after his
conviction of plotting sabotage.
   Viljoen, interviewed from South Africa by British Broadcasting
Corp.'s radio, said of Mandela's release, ``the fewer conditions
that are involved the better.''
   He did not repeat the key condition laid down by the previous
South African president, P.W. Botha, that Mandela first renounce
violence. But Viljoen added, ``Mr. Mandela has expressed himself in
terms which clearly indicate his preference for a peacefully
negotiated solution.''
   Tutu, also speaking in a telephone interview, said de Klerk's
government first would need to show good faith by lifting the state
of emergency and legalizing banned black movements.
   ``It is no use releasing Mr. Mandela and other political
prisoners into a state of emergency situation,'' said Tutu. ``It
would actually be quite, quite disastrous.''
   He added that if Mandela were released he would have to be
completely free and not, for example, restricted to Soweto, the
black township outside Johannesburg.
   He added that the state of emergency that includes bans on mass
rallies, ``has proved totally ineffective ... it has not done what
the government hoped it would do which is knock the stuffing out of
black opposition.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
