<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Reaction     09-18 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Reaction,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Wrangles Over Egyptian Proposal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Egypt-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wrangling between Israel's coalition partners
grew hotter Monday over Egypt's peace plan. Leaders of both the
right-wing Likud bloc and left-leaning Labor Party said the rift
could turn into a government crisis.
   The infighting came as Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin met in
Cairo with President Hosni Mubarak on the Egyptian leader's call for
Israel to accept the U.S.-backed formula of trading occupied land
for peace.
   Rabin's Labor Party has accepted Mubarak's plan in principle and
is pressing the government to agree to his offer to arrange an
Israeli-Palestinian meeting in Cairo. Likud Cabinet ministers have
rejected the 10-point Egyptian plan.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, leader of Likud, said on Israel
radio that in a government of the two divergent parties, ``there is
always the danger of strong differences of opinion which turn into a
crisis.''
   ``I personally would like to see the coalition remain, but I must
say that unity ... cannot be equal to any price.''
   On Israel television, Industry Minister Ariel Sharon defended
Likud's stand of never giving up land, even in exchange for peace.
   ``The question is not always what are the Jews prepared to give,
but should also be what are the Arabs prepared to give in exchange
for peace,'' he said.
   Rabin noted the differences between the two sides upon return
from Cairo but said he hoped they could reach a compromise on
Mubarak's proposals.
   ``I hope very much that the majority of the government members
can make a decision on this and that the unity of the coalition
government can be preserved,'' he told reporters at Ben-Gurion
airport.
   Israel's own peace plan already has led to one crisis in the
Cabinet formed last December. In July, Shamir's party sought to
toughen the plan and Labor threatened to pull out of the government.
   Labor withdrew its threat when Shamir said he would not accept
demands from Likud hard-liners to include the party's tough stand in
the formal plan.
   The government peace initiative, approved in May, calls for
Palestinian elections leading to negotiations between Israel and
representatives of the West Bank and Gaza Strip on limited autonomy
in the occupied territories.
   After Palestinians rejected the plan, Mubarak called for
supplementing it, basing the negotiations on the land-for-peace
principle and letting the 140,000 Arabs in Israeli-annexed east
Jerusalem vote in the Palestinian elections.
   Likud ministers issued a statement Sunday saying the government
``must not accept any additions or changes'' to the government peace
plan.
   In contrast, Labor leaders have said the Egyptian plan could help
bridge the gap between Israelis and Palestinians.
   ``The subject is how to advance the peace process and not how to
bring about the collapse of the government,'' Labor leader and
Finance Minister Shimon Peres said on Israel radio.
   Israel captured the West Bank from Jordan and the Gaza Strip from
Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war.
</TEXT>
