<FIRST>r a AM-Weinbergs     09-18 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weinbergs,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Couple Convicted of Largest Medicaid Fraud Ever Indicted Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple who fled after the husband was convicted
in the nation's largest Medicaid fraud case were indicted for bail
jumping. The husband was recaptured after the case was featured on
national televison.
   Sheldon Weinberg, 64, serving a seven- to 21-year sentence at
Attica state prison, was indicted by a state grand jury on one count
of bail jumping, said Deputy Attorney General Edward J. Kuriansky.
   Roslyn Weinberg, 61, of Batavia, also was charged with bail
jumping and two lesser counts in the indictment unsealed Monday for
allegedly helping her husband flee to Arizona.
   Both pleaded innocent at arraignment before state court Judge
Ruth Moskowitz. Mrs. Weinberg was released in her own recognizance.
   Weinberg and his two sons were convicted Nov. 30 of defrauding
the Medicaid program of $16 million, the largest such theft in the
22-year history of the program. While free on $250,000 bail, he and
his wife disappeared in January, days before he was to be sentenced.
   Weinberg was recaptured in Scottsdale, Ariz., on May 17, just
hours after his case was described on the NBC-TV program, ``Unsolved
Mysteries.'' Mrs. Weinberg flew back to New York three days later
and was met at the airport by state investigators, who confiscated
jewelry and $105,000 in cash.
   Kuriansky said Weinberg and his sons falsely billed Medicaid by
submitting reimbursement claims for about 400,000 phony patients at
their Bed-Stuy Health Care Corp. in Brooklyn.
</TEXT>
