<FIRST>u w AM-Mitchell-EasternEurope     09-18 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mitchell-Eastern Europe,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Leader Says Bush Reacting Slowly to Eastern European Change</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration has reacted timidly to
the rush of change in Eastern Europe and should shift gears and
actively support the forces of democratic change in the communist
empire, Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell said Monday.
   The Maine Democrat called on President Bush to support the entry
of communist nations into Western economic institutions, ``once
their internal reforms merit such participation.''
   ``The president should clearly state that he will let these
countries into the economic game if they will play by the rules,''
Mitchell told the Senate.
   He cited reform movements under way in Poland and Hungary and
said they are clear signs of the failure of communism as a viable
economic and political ideology.
   ``Now is the time for the United States to encourage and
capitalize upon the changes we have sought for so long,'' Mitchell
said.
   ``The administration's timidity in the face of these
opportunities is puzzling and dismaying,'' he said. ``Instead of
encouragement and engagement, the administration has adopted an
almost passive stance.''
   ``President Bush must reach beyond the status quo thinking that
appears to dominate administration thinking,'' Mitchell said. ``He
must cast aside ambivalence and hesitation and timidity and adopt a
more energetic and engaged policy toward the Soviet Union and
Eastern Europe.''
   The Bush administration, Mitchell said, ``seems almost nostalgic
about the Cold War and the rigid superpower relationships that
divided the world into two hostile and isolated camps for 40 years.''
   ``The possibility of our relations with the Soviet Union becoming
more complex and cooperative should be welcomed, not feared,'' he
said.
   The new situation will create new hazards and uncertainties, he
said.
   ``But there is no question in my mind that the greatest risk is
the failure of continued progress toward democratization and a
reversion to the Cold War policies of the past.
   ``The United States should not be afraid of its own success,''
Mitchell said. ``The administration should actively try to shape the
final outcome of the process of change we have demanded for so many
years.
   ``While the president has called for a policy of `beyond
containment,' he has failed to explain or adopt it,'' he said.
   ``There is a pressing need for the president to articulate his
vision of where he hopes this transformation will lead and devise an
American strategy to help achieve that result,'' Mitchell said.
</TEXT>
