<FIRST>r a AM-Brite     09-18 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brite,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When shoppers say ``charge it,'' a state
lawmaker wants them to say ``I Love New York'' at the same time.
   An ``I Love New York'' credit card could raise money for the
state, boost state pride and promote tourism, says Assemblyman Robin
Schimminger, who is promoting the idea.
   The card would work in the same way any major credit card
operates and would have competitive interest rates. But the cards
would be embossed with different tourist attractions, said
Schimminger.
   For example, a card issued in Niagara Falls would have a picture
of the famous cascade and a card issued in New York City would have
the Empire State Building, Schimminger said.
   ``This is a way to raise millions of dollars in revenue without
hiking taxes,'' he said Monday. ``It also helps promote community
spirit and give consumers an opportunity to play a part in tourism
and cultural development.''
   Schimminger said Montana is promoting such a card and expects to
raise more than $12 million in revenues. He said New York state
could raise much more because its population is 20 times greater.
   Under the proposal, the state Department of Economic Development
would establish a state-affiliated credit card and contract with
banks to distribute the card.
   The state would get a percentage of an annual card fee and a
small percentage of the value of goods and services charged, while
participating banks would retain a share and get the extra business
the cards generate, Schimminger said.
</TEXT>
