<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 2017EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Emmys     09-18 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Emmys,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fox Scores Ratings Win for Emmy Show; Aaron Spelling Basks in First
Victory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Fox Broadcasting Co. scored a rare double
at the 41st annual Emmy awards: The telecast brought the fledgling
television network its second-best ratings ever and its first Emmy
statuettes.
   According to preliminary ratings released Monday by Fox, the
nationally televised awards program delivered a rating of 15.4 and a
25 share in 20 top cities. A rating point is equivalent to 904,000
households with television; the share is the percentage of sets in
use.
   The awards show also saw producer Aaron Spelling collect his
first Emmy. Spelling, who has been blasted for such titillating
series as ``Charlie's Angels'' and ``Nightingales,'' won for his CBS
movie ``Day One,'' a look at the personal and scientific struggles
behind the building of the first atomic bomb.
   ``I'd never thought I'd be so ostentatious and pretentious as to
have an Emmy sitting on the desk. ... I'm going to take it home
tonight and show the family,'' Spelling said in a rare phone
interview from his office Monday.
   Spelling said his Emmy, won in a tie with ``Roe vs. Wade'' for
best drama special, probably wouldn't change his reputation.
   ``You always hear `Charlie's Angels' or `Love Boat.' So I don't
know if this is going to change anything,'' he said.
   Spelling said he won't abandon his commitment to producing
mass-appeal programming just to capture awards.
   ``We have a responsibility to the people in this company to keep
them working,'' he said.
   In addition to ``Day One,'' top winners at this year's Emmys were
the sometimes opinionated programs ``Roe vs. Wade'' and ``War and
Remembrance.''
   ``Roe vs. Wade,'' a chronicle of the fight for legalized
abortion, was subject to 20 network-mandated script rewrites and
targeted by advocacy groups who believed the show was biased toward
the pro-choice movement.
   Advertiser defections cost NBC about $1 million on the movie.
   ``It's certainly a sweet victory,'' Anthony Masucci, NBC's senior
vice president of miniseries and motion picture for television, said
Monday.
   ``I think we can all be encouraged by'' the Emmy victory, Masucci
said. ``We have to be there and stand up creatively and be counted.
Sometimes you have to say, `To hell with the advertisers who have no
guts.'''
   Sunday's awards ceremony, in which 29 Emmys were handed out with
five minutes to spare in the allotted three hours, gave Fox a
ratings win for the night over CBS, NBC and ABC.
   The Emmy show, broadcast from the Pasadena Civic Auditorium, was
No. 1 in New York, Los Angeles, San Francisco and other leading
markets.
   Fox's most popular show to date is an episode of the situation
comedy ``Married ... With Children'' earlier this month.
   Equally important to the fourth network was the four Emmys it
collected for its offbeat comedy-variety series ``The Tracey Ullman
Show.'' The program, winner of the best variety, music or comedy
program, was the first Fox show to win one of television's top
prizes.
   ``It's a beginning,'' Barry Diller, chairman of Fox Inc., said in
a backstage interview. ``The first is always the best.''
   ``There was not a single person in the entertainment business who
thought that we were anything but a fool's errand, and that we would
dismally fail,'' he said.
</TEXT>
