<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Earthquake     09-18 0141</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Earthquake,0144</SECOND>
<HEAD>Medium-Intensity Quake Felt in Southeastern Mexico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderate earthquake struck southeastern
Mexico early Monday, according to the National Seismic Service.
   There were no reports of damage or casualties from the quake,
which measured 4.5 on the Richter Scale.
   The Geophysical Institute at Mexico's National Autonomous
University said the quake struck at 5:32 a.m. in the Tehuantepec
isthmus, 460 miles southeast of Mexico City.
   Francisco Celemente, a Red Cross spokesman in Tehuantepec, said
by telephone that the quake was mild and apparently caused no
problems in the area.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. A quake of magnitude 4 can cause moderate damage in
populated areas, and one of magnitude 5 can cause considerable
damage in populated region.
</TEXT>
