<FIRST>r a AM-ZsaZsaTrial     09-18 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zsa Zsa Trial,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zsa Zsa Obeys Court Warning, Keeps Her Mouth Shut About Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note language in 6th graf, `Last week...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zsa Zsa Gabor kept her lip buttoned
Monday regarding her trial on a charge of slapping a policeman,
taking to heart a judge's warning that further comments about the
case could land her in trouble.
   ``I'm under gagging order,'' Miss Gabor told reporters at Beverly
Hills Municipal Court, where her trial began its second week.
   She is charged with four misdemeanor charges: battery on a police
officer, disobeying an officer's orders, driving with an expired
license and having an open container of alcohol in her car. If
convicted, she faces a possible 18 months in jail.
   Last week, Miss Gabor got in her best zingers when she arrived at
court, but Monday morning she glided out of her Chevrolet station
wagon and said ``no comment'' more than seven times when questioned
by a dozen reporters and television camera crews.
   She even said ``no comment'' when asked about her ensemble, white
slacks and a navy blue blazer.
   Last week, Miss Gabor said she was afraid of going to jail
because of lesbians there. She also made unflattering remarks about
the prosecutor, saying: ``He has a Napoleon complex,'' and
confronted a TV reporter the actress deemed ``a jealous bitch.''
   She also called the policeman she is accused of striking a liar.
   When Miss Gabor did talk to reporters Monday, she limited her
comments to small talk. ``My mother is very upset and (sister) Eva
could kill me'' regarding the publicity accompanying the trial, she
said.
   Gone from the courthouse were Zsa Zsa look-alikes and throngs of
sympathetic fans. In their place was a man wearing a ``Hang Zsa
Zsa'' T-shirt and a woman who gave a long-winded story to the
actress about needing $480 to pay a speeding ticket in Texas.
   Miss Gabor gave her a $20 traveler's check and the woman
complained it wasn't enough.
   Motorcycle policeman Paul Kramer said the alleged June 14 assault
was unprovoked. Miss Gabor, a foot shorter and 100 pounds lighter
than Kramer, said she struck in self defense.
   Kramer pulled over Miss Gabor's Rolls-Royce for having expired
registration tags. As he checked for other violations, Miss Gabor
allegedly drove off, was stopped again and ultimately slapped
Kramer's face.
   Kramer, who conceded at one point that he wore a ``Free Zsa Zsa''
T-shirt at his recent 38th birthday party, testified that Miss Gabor
cursed, spit and slapped him.
   Deputy District Attorney Elden Fox called four witnesses to the
stand during the morning Monday, with only one of them saying she
actually saw the slap.
   Maureen Cassidy said she was looking in her rearview mirror when
she saw Kramer being struck.
   Defense attorney William Graysen informed Municipal Judge Charles
G. Rubin that Miss Gabor's house was broken into over the weekend.
He attributed the incident to publication of her address in a
newspaper story.
   ``It's just unfortunate it occurred,'' the judge said, saying
there was little he could do.
</TEXT>
