<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 2042EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-ThirdWorldDebt     09-18 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Third World Debt,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Banks Seek More Government Aid to Cut Third World Debt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banks are asking the U.S. government and others
for more help in reducing the debt burden that led to the transfer
last year of more than $50 billion from the Third World to creditor
countries.
   ``If sufficient collateral is not made available, large numbers
of banks may turn away from the transaction,'' said Horst Schulmann,
managing director of the Institute of International Finance, which
includes major international banks.
   Schulmann was talking about the first part of a debt reduction
plan proposed by Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady that gives
commercial banks a choice on dealing with about half of Mexico's
$108 billion debt. The banks may either reduce the debt, reduce the
interest payments or lend new money to pay interest at old rates.
   Choices by hundreds of banks have yet to be made. The collateral
that some of them want could be in the form of U.S. government
bonds, which Mexico would put up as security for loans at lower
rates of interest than it now pays. Money to buy those bonds can be
lent to debtor countries by the World Bank and International
Monetary Fund if the United States agrees to make them available.
   Schulmann's warning was in a letter he sent Sept. 12 to leaders
of the twin organizations, which he made public Monday. Officials
and bankers from the member countries are gathering for their annual
meetings, which will begin at the end of this week and end the week
after.
   Third World debt and the progress of Brady's plan are expected to
be among the major topics. Brady will be the chief U.S.
representative at the meetings.
   On Sunday, the World Bank published its annual report, including
a table that showed how transfers _ including payments for goods _
from Third World countries to creditors grew to $50.1 billion last
year from $10.2 billion in 1984. Before that, the flow had been in
the opposite direction, with money going from the creditor countries
to the Third World.
   J. Fred Bergsten, a former assistant secretary of the Treasury,
has suggested that the outflow should be the direct target of attack
by the world's financial experts. It is the outflow of funds from
Third World countries, largely payments to banks, that keeps them
from spending more on goods from the United States and other
countries to create jobs and raise living standards in their own.
   In 1988 they paid $75.4 billion on their foreign debts, and $67
billion of interest, the World Bank reported. Another source of
outflow is the billions _ uncounted because often illegal _ sent by
their citizens for safekeeping to the United States and other
havens. One recent estimate put this flight of capital at $12
billion a year from Brazil alone.
   The Treasury Department calculated that 39 countries could be
eligible for debt reductions, but Schulmann told reporters on Monday
he did not see so many.
   ``The list would be rather short,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890918-0146 </DOCNO>
