<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador-Duarte     09-18 0149</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Duarte,0156</SECOND>
<HEAD>Duarte Gives Up Cancer Fight, Doctor Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Jose Napoleon
Duarte, who has terminal liver cancer, has given up his struggle
against the disease, his physician said Monday.
   Dr. Jose Luis Saca said in an interview that Duarte ``is in low
spirits and doesn't want to fight against the disease.''
   Duarte, 63, who left office on June 1 after a five years in the
presidency, has received regular treatment in the United States.
   Duarte ``doesn't get out of bed and feels pain,'' Saca said.
``He's always been a fighter, but he has thrown in the towel.''
   In June 1988, Duarte underwent surgery at Walter Reed Hospital in
Washington. Doctors at that time gave him six to 18 more months to
live.
   Saca would not predict how much longer Duarte would survive.
   ``The cancer has picked up speed,'' he said.
</TEXT>
