<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 2045EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CoalStrike     09-18 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coal Strike,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Fines UMW As Members Continue Demonstrations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEBANON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge fined the United Mine Workers union
$13.5 million Monday for illegal strike activities in its lengthy
contract dispute with Pittston Coal Group.
   But elsewhere in Russell County, UMW members continued to occupy
the control room of Pittston's main coal preparation plant, where
they locked themselves in with padlocks and steel cables.
   Union leaders said the takeover that began Sunday would remain
peaceful and promised that no damage would be done to the plant,
where coal is sorted, cleaned and shipped. They said the
demonstration was designed to persuade Pittston Co. Chairman Paul
Douglas to come to the bargaining table and as a statement against
unfair labor laws.
   The plant was shut down Monday, but Pittston spokeswoman Susan
Copeland said mines operated by replacement workers continued to
operate.
   Pittston's 1,695 UMW employees from Virginia, West Virginia and
Kentucky are involved in the strike that began April 5. But the
strike has become a symbolic dispute for organized labor across the
country because the workers believe Pittston is attempting to break
the union.
   The Pittston strike prompted wildcat walkouts by miners elsewhere
in June and July.
   In Richmond, union members pitched an awning on grounds of the
state Capitol and began a weeklong demonstration against what they
called injustices in the coalfields.
   The fines imposed Monday by Russell County Circuit Judge Donald
McGlothlin bring the total to roughly $22 million the fines imposed
by state and federal judges for illegal demonstrations against
Pittston and for acts of violence against company property and
employees.
   The fines have been appealed.
   An industry observer who spoke on condition he not be identified
because he arbitrates labor disputes, said Monday that the UMW
strike fund can easily cover the $22 million in fines if appeals
fail. Also, companies often forego damages after a contract
settlement is reached.
   ``I wouldn't call it a drop in the bucket but I wouldn't call it
a mortal blow, either,'' he said. ``If allowed to stand, it could
have a crippling effect on the union's use of civil disobedience.''
   The charges of violence during the past two months range from
shooting at moving coal trucks to peppering employee vehicles with
rocks. Charges of non-violent activities included sit-down
demonstrations and rolling roadblocks designed to slow coal truck
traffic.
   UMW attorneys argued last week that union leaders have
continually preached non-violence to members and that the union
should not be punished for acts by individuals.
   McGlothlin said testimony proved beyond a reasonable doubt that
union leaders had encouraged the illegal activities.
   One provision in McGlothlin's injunction prohibits union members
and supporters from impeding Pittston's operations.
   However, neither the judge nor Pittston took action by
mid-afternoon to remove the demonstrators occupying the preparation
plant.
   State police will take no action until either the company issues
a trespassing complaint or a judge requests enforcement of his
injunction, said spokesman Charlie Vaughan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
