<HEAD>HELENA, Mont.: ... disconnect there.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Q: Mr. President?
   President Bush: Yeah, Norm.
   Q: Why hasn't there been more progress on START? By the time that
Shevardnadze arrives on Thursday, you'll have _ or be close to
having a couple of modest agreements, one on chemical arms
inspection, one on nuclear testing. You're moving ahead with an
innovative plan on conventional weapons, but there's a perception
here that the administration just has not been willing or had the
desire to move forward as fast and with concrete action on START as
it has elsewhere.
   President Bush: That may _ that perception may have come about
because we did put the earliest effort into conventional forces.
   I happen to think that that's the place the earliest efforts
should have gone, into getting some conventional force stability.
And therefore, we did move forward more quickly on that, but I don't
think it's right to read into that effort _ incidentally, a proposal
that captured the imagination not just of the West, but of many in
the East as well _ to indicate from that we're not interested in
going forward on START.
   Or let me throw in chemical weapons. You know, most of you here
have heard me speak about the importance of trying to do something
in the chemical weapons area. So the fact that we've tabled one
imaginative and I'd say far-reaching proposal should not mean that
we're not interested or unwilling to go forward with START.
   But that may be how, if there is such a perception, how it came
about.
   Q: Is it that those START issues, or the last four remaining big
issues on START, are too difficult? Are the differences between the
U.S. and the Soviets too deep? Are the problems with the current
administration too great?
   President Bush: I don't think any of that. I mean, maybe some of
the above, but not all. I mean, these are not easy problems.
Verification issues aren't easy. I would simply say that I don't see
any insurmountable stumbling blocks there, though.
   Ellen?
   Q: Mr. President, closer to home _ in the past few months there
have been a number of racial incidents in this country _ blacks
attacking whites, whites attacking blacks. Sir, what does this say
about the state of racial relations in our country?
   President Bush: Well, it says something ugly whenever there's an
incident of that nature. I hope there's no trend toward more and
more divisiveness along racial lines. And I will do my best to speak
out against bigotry wherever it occurs, racism wherever it occurs,
in what direction it goes, and against violence of any kind.
   Q: But to the crux of the matter, sir: Is there anything that
either yourself or the present government or even the state
government can do to end what seems to be a new trend in interracial
violence?
   President Bush: I don't want to give you this _ I don't want to
say to you, it's a new _ I don't want to accept that premise. I
don't feel that there's a new trend of racial hostility. But when
these _ these regrettable incidents occur, I think that all of us
should unite in speaking out against them. But I don't think that
there's a federal statute that is going to take care of an incident
of that nature.
   Yeah?
   Q: Mr. President, the Colombia media are saying that the drug
cartels are arming themselves with rapid-fire weapons manufactured
in the United States and smuggled into their country. Given the fact
that we're asking Colombian authorities to put themselves at risk in
order to deal with this drug problem, how can you justify refusing
to ban the sale and manufacture of those weapons in the United
States?
   President Bush: Well, I think everybody here knows my position on
guns and banning guns. I do feel one thing we can do is cut down on
the automatic clips that are used, the amount of fire coming out of
one of those guns. We've made proposals. And I think we ought to get
in _ get along supporting the president's proposals in the
anti-crime package. And that will send a very strong signal to
Colombia.
   Yeah?
   Q: Can I follow up ...
   President Bush: You want to follow his question?
   No. He's goes here, and then you're second, however. (Chuckles.)
   Q: Mr. President, there have been reports that the Colombian drug
lords have targeted people in the United States and maybe even
members of your own family. I was wondering if you had any message
for any drug traffickers in Colombia who might be thinking along
those lines?
   President Bush: I think I take a rather dim view of it. But there
_ look, I know there's speculation on this, but there is no hard
intelligence evidence of such targeting.
</TEXT>
