<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Police     09-18 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa-Police,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dissident Policeman Says South African Minister Should Resign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police lieutenant who stirred
controversy by accusing riot squad members of brutality said Monday
that Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok should resign.
   Lt. Gregory Rockman commented after he and other mixed-race
policemen waited 40 minutes before being told a scheduled meeting
with Vlok was canceled.
   Two hours later, Vlok showed up at the police station in
Mitchell's Plain, Cape Town's largest mixed-race township. Rockman
was away on police business, but he later told reporters Vlok ``just
gave another pep talk'' without listening to officers' complaints.
   ``A lot was said and it meant nothing,'' Rockman said. ``I
definitely feel he should resign.''
   The state-run South African Broadcasting Corp. said Vlok
apologized for a ``misunderstanding'' which caused him to to miss
the meeting.
   Rockman moved into the spotlight on Sept. 6, when he publicly
accused white riot squad officers of having behaved like ``wild
dogs,'' beating and whipping schoolchildren and bystanders at an
anti-election protest in Mitchell's Plain.
   Vlok visited several police stations near Cape Town on Monday. He
told riot squad members a smile could be more effective than a club
at times in defusing trouble. He also said problems in the police
force should be handled ``within the family.''
</TEXT>
