<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Party     09-18 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Party,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polish Communists Invite Western Reporters to Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The communist party's Central Committee
decided on Monday to poll party members to see if support exists for
increasing democracy within the party and Poland.
   For the first time in memory, Western reporters were invited to
watch party leaders convene the Central Committee meeting. It was
closed to the reporters later in the day.
   The meeting also was the first committee plenum since the
Solidarity-led government took over a week ago.
   Politburo member Leszek Miller told reporters after the 11-hour
meeting that the plenum's second half will be held Sept. 30, when
results of the poll are known.
   In a speech opening the meeting, Miller urged greater solidarity
among party members facing the first government in the East bloc not
led by communists . He said the communists must form ``a front of
the social left.''
   Miller said the poll will ask members four questions: If they
support direct election of delegates to the planned 11th communist
party congress; if candidates for party membership should be allowed
to vote for delegates; if competing platforms to develop the party
program will be allowed, and whether deep changes in the party are
favored.
   He said options for the party's future include if it should stay
the same, become a more leftist force or form a new socialist party.
He did not elaborate.
   Miller said the Central Committee will follow the recommendations
of the majority. The powerful Central Committee carries on the work
of the party between congresses and forms the policy-making
Politburo.
   Party First Secretary Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski, who invited Western
journalists to the plenum, said, ``I would not say this is the
beginning of a new style of work but we assume that our debate ...
is not secret and cannot be secret because the party is functioning
before the eyes of the whole society.''
   No exact date has been set for the party congress, but the
Central Committee plenum is to advise the congress on the structure
and goals of the party. The party controlled the government for four
decades until Solidarity's Tadeusz Mazowiecki was sworn in as prime
minister.
   Central Committee secretary Slawomir Wiatr rejected a suggestion
that the party might split into reform and hard-line wings,
according to the state news agency PAP.
   It quoted Wiatr as saying, ``Emotions are high and postulates
clashing but there will be no break up of the party.''
   Since the independent trade union Solidarity was first legalized
in August 1980, communist party membership has fallen from 3.15
million to just below 2.1 million. The average age of a party member
is 46, compared with 40 in 1980, according to a party report
published last month.
   Solidarity was suspended in December 1981 and later outlawed. It
was legalized again this year and scored stunning victories in
parliamentary elections in June.
   Fully democratic elections are scheduled in four years and the
communist party has vowed to be ready.
   More than 20 speakers adressed the Central Committee plenum and
discussed ways ``to strengthen the party's authority and gain broad
social support,'' PAP said.
   The agency reported committee members expressed special concern
about Mazowiecki's plans to create more private business,
restructure industry and turn toward a market-oriented economy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890918-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1919EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a BC-BushTranscript 3rdAdd 900 09-18 0906</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bush Transcript, 3rd Add, 900</SECOND>
<HEAD>HELENA, Mont.: ... Yeah, John.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Q: Mr. President, a few minutes ago you told the state
legislators that Washington does not know best on the subject of
education. At the summit, education summit next week in Charlotte,
though, many of the governors, not all Democratic, are going to say
they want more from Washington. How are you going to reconcile those
differences?
   President Bush: Many want more, and sometimes justifiably so. But
I can't think of a governor that's going to come to me and say,
``Tell us how to do it. Mandate it.'' Mandated benefits from
Washington. We've had enough of that. And I am against that. And I
will make it clear _ I don't care how many of them come and say that.
   But I don't think any will, John. I don't think they want
control. Of course governors are going to want additional resources
of one kind or another. And maybe we can accommodate them, or maybe
we can't. But I don't think they want that control of education,
what they call ``mandated benefits.'' I'm absolutely certain they
don't. Yes?
   Q: Mr. President, how much did it figure in your decision on
Hungary and trade their facilitating the travel to the West of East
Germans?
   President Bush: Well, to be candid with you, it was in the mix
before that rather _ those dramatic happenings. And I think their
overall economic performance merits it.
   But clearly when a country takes a courageous decision, that's
just of additional benefit to this relationship that's growing and
that is very, very important. Way in the back.
   Q: Mr. President, the recent access of East Germans to West
Germany has got a lot of people thinking about eventual
reunification of Germany, whether that would be a good idea or not.
Do you think a reunified Germany would be a stabilizing force for
America or a destabilizing force?
   President Bush: Well, I don't _ I would think it's a matter for
the Germans to decide. But put it this way: If that was worked out
between the Germanys, I do not think we should view that as bad for
Western interests.
   I think there's been a dramatic change in post-World War II
Germany. And so I don't fear it, but I _ and I noticed that the
Chancellor had something to say on this the other day; I might need
help from Bob. But nevertheless, he _ this is something that should
be for them to determine. But I think there is in some quarters the
feeling, ``Well, a reunified Germany would be detrimental to the
peace of Europe, of Western Europe, some way,'' and I don't accept
that at all. I simply don't.
   Yeah, Frank.
   Q: Mr. President, throughout your speeches today, you've talked a
great deal about the stewardship of the environment. Yet you haven't
mentioned the Alaska oil spill, and you decided not to go _ you
dropped plans to go to Alaska as an extension of this trip.
Shouldn't an environmental president have visited the site of this
terrible oil spill?
   President Bush: We had an environmental vice president that went,
and gave an accurate report, and an environmental head of the EPA
that went and gave a good report, and an environmentally conscious
head of the Coast Guard that went. And I would like to have gone up
there, and maybe I'll get to go.
   But I don't think the fact that you don't go somewhere shows _ of
this nature, with this _ at this time _ shows a lack of interest at
all. And I am hopeful that the winter will be kind to the
environmental damage there and help follow on to what man has tried
to do.
   But please don't associate my not going to Alaska, at a rather
busy time, with a lack of interest in Prince William Sound.
   Q: If I may follow up, sir, are you satisfied with Exxon's
efforts? Do you believe that they will either themselves be back in
the spring or that you'll be sending them the bill for more work to
be done?
   President Bush: Well, we have to see, but they will come back
there, I'm convinced of that, if the matter is not further along;
there's no question, and I think they've said that. But we will be
looking to them.
   Yeah _ one, two, three.
   Q: Mr. President, it's been 3{ months since the massacre in
Tiananmen Square, and American businessmen, including your brother,
are now back making deals with the Chinese. Are you willing now to
resume normal relations with the Chinese government?
   President Bush: We _ no, no, we're not. We have relations. I've
tried to protect and preserve a long-time relationship that is very
important to us _ to the United States. It's in the national
security interest, in the geopolitical interest of the United States
to have a relationship.
   But, no, it's not time for total normalcy; and I would hope that
we would see proper signals that would indicate to me that is, you
know, in the future. But I don't want to hurt the people by cutting
off commerce from the West. I've said that early on, right at the
beginning, and I haven't changed my mind on that one. But there are
still difficulties, great difficulties there.
   Yes, Saul. And then Chuck.
</TEXT>
