<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Unrest     09-18 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Unrest,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinians Mark 1982 Beirut Massacres with Marches, Strikes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians in the occupied territories closed
shops and schools, and marched on the seventh anniversary Monday of
the Sabra and Chatilla camp massacres in Beirut, Arab reports said.
   At least 19 Palestinians were reported wounded, including a
13-year-old boy shot in the chest, in clashes with soldiers in the
West Bank and Gaza Strip, hospital officials said.
   Residents raised outlawed PLO flags in Yata, 7 miles south of
Jerusalem, and marched with pictures of Palestinians killed in the
21-month-long uprising against Israeli rule, Arab reports said. Two
residents were reportedly shot by soldiers during the march.
   Three Palestinians were wounded in a similar clash in nearby
Dura, Arab reports said.
   The army said troops in Dura came under a hail of stones and
fired, wounding three Arabs. It said it was checking the other
reports.
   In the Gaza Strip, at least 14 Arabs were wounded by Israeli army
gunfire, hospital officials said.
   The general strike, called by the uprising leadership, shut down
the occupied territories to mark the 1982 massacre of hundreds of
Palestinians by Israel's Christian allies in the Sabra and Chatilla
refugee camps in Beirut.
   Since the uprising against Israeli rule began in December 1987,
572 Palestinians have been killed by Israeli soldiers or civilians
and 114 have been slain by fellow Arabs as suspected collaborators
with Israel. Forty Israelis also have died in the violence.
</TEXT>
