<FIRST>u w AM-Shuttle-Hurricane     09-18 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shuttle-Hurricane,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA Prepares For Shuttle Rollback If Hurricane Approaches</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Aeronautics and Space
Administration said Monday it may roll the space shuttle Atlantis
back from its seaside launch pad at the Kennedy Space Center in
Florida if hurricane Hugo continues to pose a threat.
   NASA spokeswoman Sarah Keegan said preparations also were being
made to remove a satellite from an Atlas-Centaur rocket which had
been scheduled for launch on Friday.
   She said a final decision was to be made Tuesday morning on both
space vehicles after a weather briefing.
   Atlantis is scheduled to be launched Oct. 12 with the Galileo
space probe in its cargo bay. The five astronauts on the flight are
to release the probe and send it on a six-year voyage to the planet
Jupiter.
   The space probe is powered by a small nuclear generator.
   ``We are starting preparations'' to pull Atlantis back into the
relative safety of its hangar in the giant Vehicle Assembly
Building, Miss Keegan said. ``We decided to take preliminary steps
if they decide to roll back tomorrow.''
   A return to the hangar would certainly mean a delay in the
launch, but NASA has an opportunity to send the probe on its way
until late November.
   The payload on top of the Atlas-Centaur rocket is the last of a
series of communications satellites for the Navy.
   On Monday, the hurricane hit Puerto Rico with 125 mph winds, as
it moved across islands in the eastern Caribbean, killing 14 people
and leaving thousands homeless.
   By evening on Monday the center of the hurricane was 90 miles
northwest of San Juan and was moving at 13 mph in a direction
varying from west-northwest to northwest.
   Forecasters have said it was too early to tell whether the
hurricane would strike the U.S. mainland.
</TEXT>
