<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Family 1stLd-Writethru   09-18 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Family, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0742,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Says He Has No Hard Intelligence That His Family Is Target</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lede to include ``wrath'' quote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, amid reports that he has
ordered stepped-up security for his family, said Monday he has no
``hard intelligence'' about threats from drug lords and any such
attacks would provoke the ``entire wrath'' of the American people
   ``I can't say I'm totally unconcerned, but I don't have any hard
evidence that should further alarm the American people in this
context,'' he said at a news conference in Helena, Mont. on a
two-day swing through the West.
   ``I know there's speculation on this, but there is no hard
intelligence evidence of such targeting,'' when asked if he knew of
threats against his family. ``Clearly any such action would I think
just bring down the entire wrath of the American people and the
American government.''
   Earlier, Bush's spokesman, Marlin Fitzwater, declined comment on
what type of Secret Service protection was afforded the five grown
Bush children. ``We don't comment on security, period,'' he said.
   On Friday, the Secret Service beefed up security for Dorothy Bush
LeBlond, the president's daughter who lives near Portland, Maine and
works for the Portland Chamber of Commerce.
   Neither Secret Service spokesman Robert Snow nor authorities in
Portland would say specifically why the action was taken. But local
police said they were notified of the service's plan to increase
security for Mrs. LeBlond before five Colombian men were arrested
with a large arsenal of firearms in Canada near the Maine border
last Wednesday.
   Newsweek magazine reported in this week's editions that Bush had
ordered 24-hour Secret Service protection for his children at the
recommendation of the agency.
   Mrs. LeBlond, who is separated from the husband and has two
children, and her brothers and sisters did not respond to telephone
calls. The other children are Jeb in Miami, George Jr., in Dallas,
Neil in Denver and Marvin in Alexandria, Va.
   Allan Kramer, another Secret Service spokesman, said the
president and his family are authorized to receive round-the-clock
protection.
   Kramer would not provide any details of security for the Bush
children, but a White House source who spoke on condition on
anonymity said the children were not guarded on a regular basis in
the past.
   Kramer said presidential children do not always want protection.
For instance, former President Reagan's children were not happy
about full-time agents in their lives so Reagan signed an ordered
relinquishing protection for some of them.
</TEXT>
