<FIRST>u w AM-Congress-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru a0735 09-18 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0735,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Looks for Path Out of Drug-Package Standoff</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS grafs 2-3 with three grafs on meeting recessing for the
night; picks up 4th graf pvs, now 5th graf, edited to remove Byrd's first
name and now bgng: ``Byrd, backed,'' Will stand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Democrats and Republicans searched for a
compromise Monday in their struggle over the size and shape of an
anti-drug package as President Bush stood by his $7.9 billion
proposal as sufficient to do the job.
   Lawmakers from both parties met for two hours Monday evening
without settling any of the differences between them, and said they
would resume their talks Tuesday.
   ``We on our side of the table are still waiting for our friends
on the other side of the table to come up with what they would
consider a counter-proposal,'' said Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., after
the meeting.
   ``If we are talking about a specific plan on the Republican side,
it is the president's plan,'' said the chief Republican negotiator,
Sen. Mark Hartfield of Oregon.
   Byrd, backed by Democratic leaders, offered legislation last week
doubling Bush's proposal to increase financing for anti-drug
initiatives by $2.2 billion. Both sides believe that illegal drugs,
and the crime and violence springing from them, are the top issue on
the minds of the public.
   Bush is asking for $7.9 billion, mostly for law enforcement, for
fiscal 1990, which begins Oct. 1. Byrd's $10.1 billion package puts
more emphasis than Bush hasd on prevention and treatment efforts.
   For his part, the president told a news conference in Helena,
Mont., ``We've allocated the right amount of money. ... I'd like to
urge the Congress to get on with it. The American people want
action.''
   As for raising taxes to finance the war on drugs, Bush said, ``We
don't have to do that.''
   Although defending his proposal, Bush indicated he was willing to
compromise with Democrats on the final shape of an anti-drug program.
   ``There may be a compromise in the Senate and I hope there is,''
the president said. Still, he complained that the initial Democratic
response was ``spend more and raise taxes.''
   As written, Byrd's proposal drew an immediate veto threat from
White House officials, who complained that it was too expensive.
They also objected to its formula for providing the extra money:
cutting most other federal programs by 0.575 percent, which results
in a $1.8 billion slash in the military's $300 billion budget.
   The two sides have been bargaining since last week, with
Republicans hoping to reduce the size of the package, shift more of
its resources to law enforcement agencies, and shield the Pentagon
from cuts.
   Because of the standoff, Republicans on Monday slowed the
Senate's work on the remaining five annual spending bills to operate
the government next year. They fear that the chamber's Democratic
majority will leave the Pentagon spending bill for last, leaving it
vulnerable to cuts to finance anti-drug efforts.
   Debate on a $67.2 billion measure for housing, veterans and space
programs began in the late afternoon _ three hours behind schedule _
but Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas said he might block
a vote on final passage.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, chided the GOP
for blocking the bills. He noted that in the past, then-President
Reagan and other Republicans have lambasted congressional Democrats
for failing to approve spending legislation on time.
   ``No useful purpose would be served'' by blocking the bills,
Mitchell said. ``No political purpose, no substantive purpose.''
   Congress has so far sent only one of the 13 annual appropriations
bills for fiscal 1990 to Bush for his signature.
</TEXT>
