<FIRST>u i AM-HurricaneAid     09-18 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hurricane Aid,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>French, British Send Military to Help Hurricane Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   France assigned 3,000 soldiers and military transports to aid
hurricane-ravaged Guadeloupe on Monday and a British warship put
ashore a landing party to help the residents of Montserrat.
   In the United States, voluntary relief organizations asked for
donations to help storm victims including those in Puerto Rico, a
U.S. commonwealth, and the U.S. Virgin Islands.
   New York City's Puerto Rican community began raising funds to
provide aid. The Department of Puerto Rican Community Affairs, a New
York City-based organization run by the Commonwealth of Puerto Rico,
was coordinating the citywide effort of churches, banks and
individuals interested in helping the disaster relief effort.
   No U.S. federal aid was being sent to Pureto Rican or the U.S.
Virgin islands either because airports were closed or no formal
request for assistance has been received.
   ``There's not much we can do,'' said Bill McAda, a spokesman for
the Federal Emergency Management Agency. `Under law we have to have
a request from one or both governors (of Puerto Rica and the Virgin
Islands) for presidential action.''
   The French Defense Ministry in Paris announced it has assigned
3,000 soldiers, two military transport aircraft and four cargo
vessels to help restore communications and emergency services to
Guadeloupe, a French overseas territory.
   It said the troops and equipment will come from the regional
Antilles-Guyana command and the planes and ships will ferry medical
and radio equipment, building materials and aid workers to the
island.
   The government also alerted French ships in the Caribbean to be
ready to render assistance in rescue operations while the state
airline Air France lowered fares to and from Guadeloupe and
scheduled more cargo flights.
   Two aircraft arrived Monday at Point-a-Pitre, Guadeloupe, from
France, the first since Friday, and they delivered 45 tons of
emergency supplies and 200 rescue workers.
   Britain reported the Royal Navy warship Alacrity had a 150-member
landing party standing by to go ashore in Montserrat.
   It said a 16-member working party landed Monday to clear debris
from the airport and other members of the landing party will go
ashore Tuesday to help restore comunications and other facilities.
   A spokesman for the Overseas Development Administration in London
said: ``The frigate has landed some basic medical supplies and they
have sent some men ashore to clear the runway to enable further
supplies to be flown in'' to the British island.
   British Airways said Monday night that it was sending two Boeing
747 jumbo jets to Antigua Tuesday to evacuate up to 400 people from
the island. The Caribbean nation of Antigua and Barbuda is in the
British-led Commonwealth.
   A British Defense Ministry said the Alacrity had radioed that its
medical officer, flown to Montserrat by helicopter, reported 80
percent of the island's buildings were flattened.
   The Philadelphia-based American Friends Service Committee
announced it was accepting donations to aid hurricane victims.
   Paul Brink, information director, said the funds would be used
for emergency relief and reconstruction and will be administered
through the Caribbean Project for Justice and Peace.
   In Washington, an organization of voluntary relief agencies urged
aid donors to provide cash rather than goods.
   It said it made the appeal for cash donations to avoid problems
that occurred in recent disasters when relief agencies were flooded
with unneeded goods that hampered delivery of necessary items.
   ``Goods should not be collected or sent unless they have been
requested by the disaster-stricken country or private voluntary
organizations,'' said InterAction.
   InterAction represents about 120 relief organizations including
the American Red Cross, CARE, Save the Children, World Vision, Oxfam
and the Christian Children's Fund.
</TEXT>
