<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 2115EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-UN     09-18 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>43rd General Assembly Closes; Highlight Was `End to Cold War'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The yearlong 43rd General Assembly ended
Monday, a session that saw ``the end of the Cold War'' declared by
Ronald Reagan and Mikhail Gorbachev, said Assembly President Dante
Caputo.
   Before his presidential term ended in January, Reagan joined the
Soviet president in opening a new era of warmer superpower
relations, which was reflected in the speeches both men gave to the
General Assembly almost a year ago.
   Caputo said those declarations ``are the deepest and most
eloquent reflection of profound change that has occurred.
   ``They demonstrate, I would venture to say, the end of the Cold
War, which hovered over our world for such a long period.''
   Monday's brief closing session was mainly procedural. Unresolved
questions such as the Palestinian issue, Cyprus and the uneasy
Iran-Iraq truce were carried over to the 44th General Assembly,
which opens Tuesday.
   The assembly took the unprecedented step of moving to Geneva to
hear Yasser Arafat last December after the State Department refused
to give Palestine Liberation Organization chief an entry visa to
address the General Assembly.
   At Geneva, Arafat renounced the use of terrorism and recognized
Israel's right to exist, eliminating the major issues that prompted
the State Department to refuse his visa request.
   Arafat has said he would like to address this year's General
Assembly.
   Arab League Ambassador Clovis Maksoud said he was confident the
new U.S. administration would grant a visa if one was asked, but if
not, ``of course we would want to go back to Geneva.''
   The undersecretary-general for General Assembly affairs, Ronald
Spiers, told reporters Arafat should be allowed to speak if he
wishes.
   Spiers is a former undersecretary at the State Department and the
top American official at the United Nations.
   Caputo, Argentina's former foreign minister, reviewed the closing
assembly's major accomplishments.
   He noted it set in motion Namibia's transition toward
independence, which may end in the sovereign nation of Namibia's
becoming the 160th member of the General Assembly next year.
   Caputo hailed the unanimous adoption of the Afghanistan
resolution that called for outside parties not to interfere in
Afghan affairs, and for a government of national reconciliation.
   Other landmark resolutions included calls for peace settlements
in Central America, Western Sahara and Cambodia.
   ``This, more than any other time, is the time of the United
Nations. As the Cold War yields to dialogue and detente, new
possibilities are opened for the collective security enshrined in
our Charter,'' said Caputo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
