<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are some of the major
points raised by President Bush at his news conference on Monday.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>SOVIET RELATIONS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bush, who sees Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze later
this week, said he felt ``under no rush'' to arrange a summit with
Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev and does not see ``any
insurmountable stumbling blocks'' to an arms control agreement. The
president noted an increased flow of Soviet-bloc arms from Cuba to
Nicaragua, called it ``not a very kind and gentle approach to this
hemisphere'' and said he would take it up with Shevardnadze.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>CAPITAL GAINS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The president rejected what he called ``threats'' by
congressional Democrats who have said they will not negotiate with
the White House over budget matters if a proposal to cut the capital
gains tax is approved. ``This idea that we won't talk _ I don't
think that's right and I don't think the American people would
support that,'' Bush said.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>ASSAULT RIFLES</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bush maintained his opposition to a ban on assault rifles. ``I
have long felt that the answer is to go after the criminal and not
in the process to do violence to the rights of legitimate gun
owners,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>DRUG LORDS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bush said he had no ``hard intelligence evidence'' that Colombian
drug lords are planning attacks on Americans and said any such
activity would ``bring down the entire wrath of the American people
and the American government'' if undertaken against his family.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>CHINA</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The president said he was not yet ready to normalize relations
with the People's Republic of China, which were chilled after a
military crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrations there. ``No, it
is not time for normalcy ... but I don't want to hurt the (Chinese)
people by cutting off commerce,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>ALASKA</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The president predicted that Exxon would return in the spring, if
necessary, to finish cleanup work on its oil spill in Alaska's
Prince William Sound. In the meantime, he said he hoped the ``winter
will be kind'' to the environment there.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>REFUGEES</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bush defended the administration's acceptance of no more than
50,000 refugees from the Soviet Union during the fiscal year that
begins Oct. 1. We have to have an orderly immigration policy,'' he
said
</TEXT>
