<FIRST>r a AM-AgentSentenced     09-18 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Agent Sentenced,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Secret Service Agent Draws Six Months in Halfway House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Secret Service agent convicted of using
excessive force to arrest a man near a presidential candidate's New
York motorcade last year was sentenced Monday to six months in a
halfway house.
   U.S. District Judge Pierre Leval imposed the sentence on Kevin
Schatzle after viewing a videotape of the April 10, 1988 incident.
At the time, Schatzle was in the security detail for Sen. Albert
Gore, then campaigning for the Democratic presidential nomination.
   A jury convicted Schatzle, 28, in June of using excessive force
when he kicked and punched attorney Christopher Gorayeb, 32. He had
faced up to one year in prison.
   During the trial, Schatzle testified that the lawyer spat at him.
But Gorayeb said he was attacked when he yelled an obsenity at the
passing motorcade because one of its cars almost hit him as he
legally crossed the street. Gorayeb testified that he suffered a
broken nose and deep bruises.
   Schatzle had been acquitted of a second charge of making a false
arrest.
   ``I think that what happened is that when Gorayeb spat, the agent
simply blew his stack,'' Leval said. He also imposed three years
probation and a $2,000.
   While noting Schatzle's previous good record as a law enforcement
officer, the judge said the agent had engaged in ``serious
misconduct'' during the incident.
   His attorney, Maurice Nadjari, had urged the judge not to impose
any prison time. He said Schatzle had earned the respect of his
colleagues and superiors during five years in the New York Police
Department and four years with the Secret Service.
   Leval allowed Nadjari time to submit a written motion to postpone
the sentence pending appeal. Schatzle remains free until the judge
rules.
</TEXT>
