<FIRST>r a BC-APIndustryNews Advisory-6thAdd   09-18 0837</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Industry News, Advisory-6th Add,0864</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anchorman Sues Television Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ERIE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former television anchorman has sued his
station in federal court, charging he was demoted because of his age.
   Hyle Richmond, 62, filed suit in U.S. District Court against
WICU-TV and its parent company, Great Lakes Communications Inc.,
seeking reinstatement to his job as an on-air newscaster and
anchorman. He is still employed by the station.
   The Equal Employment Opportunity Commission found in May that the
station violated age discrimination laws in actions against Richmond
and other older employees of the station, according to Richmond's
lawsuit.
   The lawsuit, which was filed in early September, claims that
Richmond, who had more than 30 years on the air, was demoted to a
reporter's job on Sept. 28, 1987, and was replaced by Lisa Adams,
who is in her early 30s.
   It further says the station also fired or demoted three other
on-air newscasters or anchor people who were more than 40 years old
and replaced them with younger employees. The three others did not
join in the suit.
   Clarence Paolella, the station's general manager, could not be
reached for comment. A station telephone operator said no other
executives could comment.
   Richmond is seeking reinstatement to his former on-air job,
damages for loss of earnings, benefits because of his demotion, and
other damages.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FCC Chief Suggests Voluntary Code Against `Shock Radio'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Federal Communications
Commission suggests broadcasters adopt a voluntary code to control
``shock radio'' _ the use of sexually and racially oriented humor to
attract audiences.
   ``We are not simply recorders, transmitters and antennas,'' FCC
Chairman Alfred Sikes told a group of broadcasters attending the
National Association of Broadcasters radio convention Sept. 15. ``We
are what we broadcast.''
   Sikes, a former owner of several radio stations, suggested
reviving the NAB's programming code, which was dropped in the early
1980s as the result of a federal antitrust suit against provisions
regarding commercials.
   Standards should be drawn up by the industry, without government
pressure, said Sikes, who took over the FCC chairmanship in August.
   ``The government rightly leaves all programming decisions to
broadcasters today,'' he said. ``Not only is that as it should be,
but it should also be seen as an invitation to work among
yourselves.''
   Sikes said he was prepared to work with the industry and the U.S.
Justice Department, which filed the antitrust suit, ``to ensure that
broadcasters have the freedom to develop sound, voluntary,
programming standards.''
   The FCC announced on Aug. 24 that it was beginning enforcement
action against three stations _ WLUP-AM in Chicago, KSJO-FM in San
Jose, Calif., and WFBQ-FM in Indianapolis _ ``which may have
broadcast indecent programs in violation of the law.''
   NAB President Edward Fritts said the organization could not
consider a code unless pending legislation granting the broadcast
industry an antitrust exemption for programming content codes passes
Congress.
   Even if an antitrust exemption is granted, a code could still
lead to legal problems, Fritts said.
   ``It doesn't preclude the NAB from being sued on civil grounds,
on First Amendment rights,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>White House Reprimands Mosbacher on HDTV, Source Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher won't
concentrate on promoting a high-definition television industry in
the United States after being reprimanded by the White House, a
congressional source said.
   ``Mosbacher in their eyes is a renegade promoting industial
policy and they thought it was absolutely necessary to reprimand
him,'' said the source, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Mosbacher ``was made to stand in front of the class and made to
say `I believe in the free market 500 times,''' the source said.
   As a result, the Commerce Department will consider HDTV, the next
generation of television, only as part of a broad-based effort to
boost U.S. technological competitiveness, an administration source
said Sept. 11.
   Mosbacher said that for months he was prepared to recommend that
the Bush administration loosen tax and antitrust laws to jump-start
private American industry efforts to compete with Europe and Japan
to build HDTV, which promises motion-picture clarity and compact
disc-quality sound.
   Commerce Department officials first promised Congress they would
unveil the government plans for HDTV by midsummer and, later, by the
end of the year.
   Now, the administration official said, the HDTV initiative is on
hold.
   Advocates of HDTV say it could revitalize a moribund U.S.
electronics industry and have important applications in medicine,
defense and other industries.
   It is envisioned as a $20 billion industry by 2000 and would be a
``technology driver'' for industries such as computer chips.
   The American Electronics Association has asked Congress for more
than a billion dollars in development money for HDTV, and several
bills are pending in Congress that would provide taxpayer money to
spur the industry.
   But a Congressional Budget Office report last month said HDTV
claims were ``very optimistic'' and that even under the rosiest of
scenarios, HDTV sales would be small relative to other electronic
equipment markets.
</TEXT>
