<FIRST>a i PM-BeirutLife-Refugees Adv22   09-18 0944</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Beirut Life-Refugees, Adv 22,0979</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri PMs Sept. 22 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Beirut Life: Refugees Live in Squalor Outside Beleaguered City</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   By the thousands, people have fled Beirut,
escaping the perils of civil war. But while they find life safer in
the countryside, many still face other kinds of hardship. This is
one of a series of periodic reports by Associated Press
correspondents on life in Beirut, an emptying city.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AWALI RIVER, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iman Batal, now a refugee 25 miles
from her home in beleaguered Beirut, clustered her whimpering,
hungry children around her beside their makeshift tent.
   ``We only eat meat in our dreams,'' she said.
   A pot of potatoes boiled on an open fire, their only food this
day in their new life on a bank of the Awali River in southern
Lebanon.
   Like tens of thousands of other Beirutis who have fled their
homes in six months of fierce shelling between Christian and Syrian
forces, Mrs. Batal, her husband Ahmed and their nine children, aged
1 to 10, live hand-to-mouth in squalid camps of ragged tents
fashioned from blankets and plastic sheets in southern Lebanon and
the mountains northeast of the city.
   The Batals are Sunni Moslems from one side of the Green Line that
divides Beirut into Moslem and Christian sectors.
   Elie Haddad and his family are Christians from the other side of
the line.
   The Haddads have been living for four months in a shelter made of
nylon sheets, cardboard and tree branches at a camp near the St.
Sharbel Maronite Catholic Church in the mountains.
   Haddad, his wife Ilham and their five children, aged 4 to 11,
watched helplessly as their shelter on a rock-studded hillside
overlooking vineyards was battered by unseasonal torrential rains.
   ``What are we going to do when the rainy season starts?'' Mrs.
Haddad lamented.
   Police estimate that around 1.35 million of Beirut's 1.50 million
people have abandoned their homes in the shell-battered city over
the last few months, fleeing the battles in which more than 900
people have been killed and 2,680 wounded.
   Many refugees have moved in with relatives and friends, or rented
apartments, or anything they can find, in southern, northern or
eastern Lebanon. Rents have soared.
   But an estimated 35,000 people, like the Batals and the Haddads,
are living as squatters in mosques, churches, schools, empty
buildings and in the fields.
   The Haddads fled from their home in the Ashrafiyeh neighborhood
near the Green Line because their apartment block had no bomb
shelter.
   ``Now we're refugees in our own country,'' said Haddad.
   Despite their parlous situation, the Haddads and other Christian
families around the church at Innaya are better off than many other
refugees. The church has provided fresh water, some food and outdoor
sanitary facilities.
   Haddad is a police officer who works every couple of days, which
means he is paid regularly and can buy food and other essentials.
   Ahmed Batal, on the other hand, is penniless. He lost his job at
a tile factory four months ago when it closed because it had lost
electric power and so few employees were showing up anyway due to
the shelling.
   ``We've sold our washing machine, the television set and the
refrigerator to buy food,'' Mrs. Batal said. ``We've nothing else to
sell. Most of our belongings were smashed in the bombardment. Now
the money's run out.''
   The Batals live with 1,500 other Beirutis on the banks of the
Awali River. They fled the capital two months ago after their
apartment in the Ein Mreisseh district of west Beirut was hit by a
155mm-shell.
   Batal watches in despair as his children, barefoot and wearing
soiled, tattered clothes, go hungry in the miserable camp just north
of the coastal city of Sidon.
   Their most acute problem is the lack of potable water: only one
faucet is available for about 300 families.
   There are no latrines. Some of the refugees use a rest room in a
nearby gas station, when the owners allow them.
   The stench of garbage and other waste pervades the camp.
   Mrs. Batal said she has worn the same clothes she had on when she
fled Beirut.
   ``I take a bath, fully clothed, in the river,'' she said.
   Health is a problem.
   ``The conditions in camps likes these have caused skin
diseases,'' said Michel Dufour, chief of the International Committee
of the Red Cross team in Lebanon.
   He said the Red Cross has supplied medicines to clinics in
southern Lebanon to treat skin problems among refugees.
   The Red Cross also has handed out food parcels, blankets, kitchen
supplies and cleaning materials to supplement aid from Moslem and
Christian militias. The exodus from Beirut has sent prices in
regions like southern Lebanon soaring. A two-room unfurnished
apartment in Sidon, south of the Awali, which rented for the
equivalent of $50 a month before March, now costs $400.
   A bundle of 12 Arabic bread loaves costs $2, double what it was a
few months ago. Meat and vegetable prices have also doubled.
   The influx of refugees has antagonized the people of the south,
mostly Shiite Moslems, who have to pay the same inflated prices.
   The conservative southerners are also offended by the miniskirted
Beirut women on the streets of Sidon and Tyre.
   Said Abdullah, a Sunni clergyman in the village of Mazboud
declared: ``These visitors must respect the social traditions of
this region. Women must be decently dressed in line with Moslem
custom. Our young men are not accustomed to the way of life in the
big city.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Sept. 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
