<SECOND>BC-History, Adv24,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 24</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Sunday, September 24, the 267th day of 1989. There are
98 days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   Two hundred years ago, on September 24, 1789, Congress passed the
First Judiciary Act, which provided for an Attorney General and a
Supreme Court.
   On this date:
   In 1869, thousands of businessmen were ruined in a Wall Street
panic after financiers Jay Gould and James Fisk attempted to corner
the gold market.
   In 1896, author F. Scott Fitzgerald was born in St. Paul, Minn.
   In 1929, Lieutenant James H. Doolittle guided a Consolidated NY-2
Biplane over Mitchell Field in New York in the first all-instrument
flight.
   In 1934, Babe Ruth made his farewell appearance as a regular
baseball player with the New York Yankees in a game against the
Boston Red Sox. (The Sox won, 5-0.)
   In 1948, Mildred Gillars, accused of being Nazi wartime radio
propagandist ``Axis Sally,'' pleaded innocent in a Washington, D.C.,
courtroom to charges of treason.
   In 1955, President Eisenhower suffered a heart attack while on
vacation in Denver.
   In 1957, the Brooklyn Dodgers played their last game at Ebbets
Field, defeating the Pittsburgh Pirates 2-0.
   In 1960, the USS Enterprise, the first nuclear-powered aircraft
carrier, was launched at Newport News, Va.
   In 1963, the Senate ratified a treaty with Britain and the Soviet
Union limiting nuclear testing.
   In 1968, the CBS television magazine ``60 Minutes'' premiered.
   In 1969, the trial of the Chicago 8 began.
   In 1976, newspaper heiress Patricia Hearst was sentenced to seven
years in prison for her part in a 1974 bank robbery.
   Ten years ago: Black guerrilla leaders at the Zimbabwe-Rhodesia
peace talks in London reluctantly agreed to give the white minority
20 percent of the seats in a new parliament for the war-torn nation.
   Five years ago: President Reagan, in an address to the UN General
Assembly, sounded a conciliatory chord as he promised to work to
narrow ``the clear differences'' between the United States and the
Soviet Union.
   One year ago: Canadian sprinter Ben Johnson came in first in the
men's 100-meter dash at the Seoul Summer Olympics _ a victory that
dissolved three days later when officials disqualified Johnson for
using anabolic steroids. Members of the eastern Massachusetts
Episcopal diocese elected Barbara C. Harris to be the first woman
bishop in the church's history.
   Today's Birthdays: ABC sportscaster Jim McKay is 68. Actress
Sheila MacRae is 65. Actor-singer Anthony Newley is 58.
``Muppeteer'' Jim Henson is 53.
   Thought for Today: ``If you are losing your leisure, look out;
you may be losing your soul.'' _ Logan Pearsall Smith,
Anglo-American author (1865-1946).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance for Use Sunday, September 24</NOTE>
