<SECOND>BC-History, Adv25,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, Sept. 25</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Monday, September 25, the 268th day of 1989. There are
97 days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   Two hundred years ago, on September 25, 1789, the first U.S.
Congress, meeting in New York, adopted 12 amendments to the
Constitution and sent them to the states for ratification. Ten of
the amendments became the Bill of Rights.
   On this date:
   In 1513, Spanish explorer Vasco Nunez de Balboa crossed the
Isthmus of Panama and discovered the Pacific Ocean.
   In 1690, ``Publick Occurrences,'' the first American newspaper,
published its first and last edition in Boston.
   In 1775, American Revolutionary War hero Ethan Allen was captured
by the British as he led an attack on Montreal.
   In 1890, Mormon Church president Wilford Woodruff issued a
manifesto formally renouncing polygamy.
   In 1890, Congress established Yosemite National Park.
   In 1904, a New York City police officer ordered a woman named
Lillian Orr, who was riding in an automobile on Fifth Avenue, to
stop smoking a cigarette, in accordance with an unwritten rule
against women smoking in public.
   In 1919, President Wilson became seriously ill and collapsed
after a speech in Pueblo, Colo., during a national speaking tour in
support of the Treaty of Versailles.
   In 1957, with 300 Army troops standing guard, nine black children
who had been forced to withdraw from Central High School in Little
Rock, Ark., because of unruly crowds were escorted to their classes.
   In 1962, Sonny Liston knocked out Floyd Patterson in round one to
win the world heavyweight title at Comiskey Park in Chicago.
   In 1964, the situation comedy ``Gomer Pyle, USMC'' made its debut
on CBS-TV.
   In 1973, the three-man crew of the U.S. space laboratory Skylab 2
made a safe splashdown in the Pacific after spending 59 days in
orbit.
   In 1978, 144 people were killed when a Pacific Southwest Airlines
Boeing 727 and a Cessna private plane collided in the air over San
Diego, Calif., and crashed.
   In 1981, Sandra Day O'Connor was sworn in as the first woman
justice on the U.S. Supreme Court.
   Ten years ago: Addressing the UN General Assembly, Soviet Foreign
Minister Andrei A. Gromyko said ``falsehoods'' were being aimed at
his country and Cuba _ an apparent reference to U.S. charges of
Soviet combat troops in Cuba. The military government of Argentina
expelled publisher Jacobo Timerman. The musical ``Evita,'' based on
the life of Eva Peron, opened on Broadway.
   Five years ago: One day after President Reagan addressed the UN
General Assembly, the official Soviet news agency Tass rejected the
American leader's assurances of a U.S. desire for arms cuts as
``absolutely groundless.''
   One year ago: Republican George Bush amd Democrat Michael Dukakis
clashed over deficits, drugs and the Pledge of Allegiance in their
first presidential debate. Former ``first brother'' Billy Carter
died in Plains, Ga., at age 51. Florence Griffith Joyner won the
women's 100-meter dash at the Seoul Olympics.
   Today's Birthdays: New York Yankee broadcaster Phil Rizzuto is
71. ABC news correspondent Barbara Walters is 58. Dancer-actress
Juliet Prowse is 53. Actor Robert Walden is 46. Actor-producer
Michael Douglas is 45. Actor Mark Hamill is 37. Actor Christopher
Reeve is 37. Actress Heather Locklear is 28.
   Thought for Today: ``The Constitution belongs to the people and
not the people to the Constitution.'' _ Theodore Roosevelt, 26th
president of the United States (1858-1919).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance for Use Monday, September 25</NOTE>
