<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday, Sept. 29</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Friday, September 29, the 272nd day of 1989. There are
93 days left in the year. The Jewish New Year, Rosh Hashanah, begins
at sunset.
   Today's highlight in history:
   Two hundred years ago, on September 29, 1789, the U.S. War
Department established a regular army with a strength of several
hundred men.
   On this date:
   In 1758, English Admiral Horatio Nelson was born in Burnham
Thorpe.
   In 1829, London's re-organized police force, which became known
as Scotland Yard, went on duty.
   In 1902, impressario David Belasco opened his first Broadway
theater.
   In 1918, allied forces scored a decisive breakthrough of the
Hindenburg Line in Germany in World War I.
   In 1943, General Dwight D. Eisenhower and Italian Marshal Pietro
Badoglio signed an armistice aboard the British ship Nelson off
Malta.
   In 1957, the New York Giants played their last game at the Polo
Grounds, losing to the Pittsburgh Pirates, 9-1.
   In 1963, the second session of the ecumenical council Vatican II
opened in Rome.
   In 1975, baseball manager Casey Stengel died at a hospital in
Glendale, Calif., at the age of 85.
   In 1977, Muhammad Ali won a unanimous, 15-round decision over
Earnie Shavers at Madison Square Garden in New York to retain his
world heavyweight boxing championship.
   In 1978, Pope John Paul I was found dead in his Vatican apartment
by his personal secretary. He had served just over a month as
supreme pontiff of the Roman Catholic Church.
   In 1982, seven people in the Chicago area died after unwittingly
taking Extra-Strength Tylenol capsules that had been laced with
cyanide. To date, the crime remains unsolved.
   In 1987, Henry Ford the Second, longtime chairman of Ford Motor
Company, died in Detroit at age 70.
   Ten years ago: Pope John Paul II became the first pope to visit
Ireland as he arrived for a three-day tour and blessed more than a
million followers in a Dublin park.
   Five years ago: Officials in Ireland announced that two of its
navy cutters had intercepted the Marita Anne, a 56-foot trawler
carrying seven tons of U.S.-purchased weapons from the United States
for delivery to the Irish Republican Army.
   One year ago: The space shuttle Discovery blasted off from Cape
Canaveral, Fla., marking America's return to manned space flight
since the Challenger disaster. Florence Griffith Joyner and Jackie
Joyner-Kersee won their second gold medals of the Seoul Olympics, in
the 200-meter and the long jump, respectively.
   Today's Birthdays: Former singing cowboy and baseball magnate
Gene Autry is 82. Actress Greer Garson is 81. Movie director
Michelangelo Antonioni is 77. Movie director Stanley Kramer is 76.
Football coach Bum Phillips is 66. Former Sen. John Tower is 64.
Actress Anita Ekberg is 58. Singer Jerry Lee Lewis is 54. Actor
Larry Linville is 50. Actress Madeline Kahn is 47. Solidarity
founder and Nobel laureate Lech Walesa is 46. ``Today'' Show host
Bryant Gumbel is 41.
   Thought for Today: ``If you want work well done, select a busy
man _ the other kind has not time.'' _ Elbert Hubbard, American
author and publisher (1856-1915).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance for Use Friday, September 29</NOTE>
