<HEAD>$adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Saturday, Sept. 30</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Saturday, September 30th, the 273rd day of 1989. There
are 92 days left in the year. This is the Jewish New Year, Rosh
Hashanah.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On September 30th, 1938, British, French, German and Italian
leaders ended the Munich Conference with a decision to appease Adolf
Hitler by allowing Nazi annexation of Czechoslovakia's Sudetenland.
   On this date:
   In 1630, the first execution in America took place as John
Billington was hanged in Plymouth, Massachusetts, for fatally
shooting John Newcomin.
   In 1777, the Congress of the United States _ forced to flee in
the face of advancing British forces _ moved to York, Pennsylvania.
   In 1791, Mozart's opera ``The Magic Flute'' premiered in Vienna.
   In 1846, Dr. William Morton of Charleston, Massachusetts, used an
experimental anesthetic _ ether _ for the first time on one of his
patients.
   In 1927, Babe Ruth hit his 60th homer of the season to break his
own major league record. The blow came off Washington's Tom Zachary
in Yankee Stadium.
   In 1939, the first college football game to be televised was
shown on New York City station W2XBS as Fordham University defeated
Waynesburg College, 34-7.
   In 1946, an international military tribunal in Nuremberg,
Germany, found 22 top Nazi leaders guilty of war crimes.
   In 1949, the Berlin Airlift, which had ferried more than 2.3
million tons of supplies to the western sector of the German city in
defiance of a Soviet blockade, came to an end.
   In 1954, the first atomic-powered vessel, the submarine
``Nautilus,'' was commissioned by the Navy at Groton, Connecticut.
   In 1955, actor James Dean, was killed in the collision of his
sports car with another automobile near Cholame, California. He was
24.
   In 1962, James Meredith succeeded on his fourth try in
registering for classes at the University of Mississippi.
   In 1980, Iran's spiritual leader, Ayatollah Khomeini rejected a
truce call from Iraqi President Saddam Hussein, saying war between
the two countries would continue ``to the end.''
   Ten years ago: Pope John Paul II, continuing the first-ever papal
tour to Ireland, journeyed to the town of Drogheda, where he lashed
out at the sectarian violence in Northern Ireland, and pleaded for
peace.
   Five years ago: Mike Witt of the California Angels threw major
league baseball's first nine-inning perfect game in three years as
his team defeated its host, the Texas Rangers, 1-0.
   One year ago: Mikhail S. Gorbachev retired President Andrei A.
Gromyko from the Politburo and fired other old-guard leaders in a
Kremlin shake-up that put some Gorbachev allies in key positions.
   Today's Birthdays: Former Georgia Governor Lester Maddox is 74.
Actress Deborah Kerr is 68. Actress Angie Dickinson is 57. Singer
Johnny Mathis is 54. Sen. James Sasser (D-Tenn.) is 53. Singer
Marilyn McCoo is 46. Former White House News Secretary Jody Powell
is 46. Actress Rula Lenska is 42.
   Thought for Today: ``What makes a leader _ intelligence,
integrity, imagination, skill: in brief, statecraft? Not at all. It
is the fact that the man has a following.'' _ Gerald W. Johnson,
American journalist (1890-1980).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance for Use Saturday, Sept. 30</NOTE>
