<FIRST>a i AM-Cambodia-War Adv21   09-18 0748</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia-War, Adv 21,0769</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv21</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday AMs, Sept. 21, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cambodians Fear More War After Vietnamese Withdrawal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note 7th graf, Vietnamese pullout set to be completed by Sept.
26.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At 6 a.m. one recent Thursday, Soun
Sundary, gentle and serene at 21, gave birth to her first child and
held her up to a Cambodia that has known only war for two decades.
   ``I don't know about the future, whether there will be peace or
not,'' she said as the sun shone into her hospital room after days
of monsoon rains.
   She and her husband, Soun Rithy, 25, have spent most of their
lives with their tragic nation in turmoil and mass deaths _ the
civil war of 1970-75, the fanatical communist Khmer Rouge rule of
1975-78 and the fighting since Vietnam invaded in late 1978.
   Seven members of their two families died in the murderous scourge
of the Khmer Rouge who defeated a pro-West government in 1975.
   The couple and their daughter are likely to see more killing in
the years ahead, even though the Vietnamese are pulling out.
   Rithy had come to Phnom Penh for the birth of his child but is
returning to southern Koh Kong province, where he has fought as a
government soldier for seven years against the Khmer Rouge and other
guerrillas.
   Peace talks in Paris have collapsed. Vietnam's pullout, due to be
completed Sept. 26, will leave the Vietnamese-installed Communist
government in Phnom Penh facing the guerrillas alone in what could
be the war's most chaotic and violent phase.
   ``We would like to have peace, really,'' Vice Premier Kong Sam-Ol
said in an interview. ``For almost 20 years, our people have known
more about killing and war than peace.''
   Most feared is the possibility that Vietnam's pullout will allow
the return of the Khmer Rouge, the black pajama-clad fighters who
killed hundreds of thousands of people in torture chambers and slave
labor camps after they took over in 1975.
   The government claims the army will have no problems handling the
guerrillas.
   Many others do not feel as confident.
   Some Phnom Penh residents have been stocking rice in case
supplies are cut off by escalating fighting, said Khieu Kanharith,
editor of the government-sponsored weekly Kampuchea.
   Some senior government officials have told Western aid workers
they are saving money in case they have to flee.
   ``They don't know what is going to happen after September if
there are problems with the Khmer Rouge,'' one aid worker said.
``They believe if there are problems, the first problems would be
for them.''
   At Kompong Chhnang, just north of Phnom Penh, Maj. Chhour
Chandoeun, the provincial military commander, said his nine
battalions are hard pressed in their fight against the 300 Khmer
Rouge guerrillas in the area.
   ``They don't stay in one place and we don't know all their hiding
places,'' he said.
   An aid official said the government's military draft appears to
be widening. A few months ago, some parents forbade their sons to
leave the house as overzealous recruiters yanked men off the
streets. Some youths flee to the border with Thailand, only to be
rounded up by the guerrillas for service.
   A 10 p.m.-5 a.m. curfew was lifted in April, but the climate of
war still pervades this riverside capital.
   In July, authorities closed dance halls that had been packed
nightly since they were permitted to open last year. Mayor Thong
Khong blamed drunken quarrels and said only the rich could visit
them anyway.
   ``At that time, there was increased fighting at the border and it
was difficult to justify the sacrifice at the border and the good
life in Phnom Penh,'' one foreign-aid official said.
   For many years, popular support for the Vietnamese-backed
government had stemmed mostly from its being the only alternative to
the Khmer Rouge. With Vietnam's pullout, Phnom Penh extended
economic reforms to include a freeing up of private trade in an
effort to raise primitive living conditions.
   Ironically, it created a new security problem by worsening
corruption among officials, and corruption was a factor that helped
the Khmer Rouge topple Lon Nol's pro-West government in 1975.
   The reforms reduced somewhat the gulf between the people and
their leaders. But in addition to the fear of more war remains the
widespread fear of the authorities and ``the police,'' who are
thought to be everywhere.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thurs AMs, Sept. 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
