<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1413EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--SpecialBaseball Adv01   09-18 1063</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Special Baseball, Adv 01,1090</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 1</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&amp;w photos.
ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)    </HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   It took a lot of hustle by a group of Connecticut
parents, but the national Little League organization finally
sanctioned a baseball program for handicapped youngsters. Similar
leagues have now been formed in towns in Texas, Kentucky and
Massachusetts.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARK SEAVY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There were no hits, no runs and no errors.
But what made a recent baseball game perfect was that there were no
losers.
   That's just the way they like it in the Norwich Little League's
Special Needs Program, which was launched last year for disabled
youngsters between the ages of 6 and 15.
   ``Although it may not be as competitive as some of the other
leagues, that is not the issue,'' says Julie Sage of Norwich, whose
7-year-old son plays in the league. ``We never dreamed our kids
would have been able to play in anything like this.''
   During one recent game, Alfred ``A.J.'' Jonasch III, 15, who has
Down's syndrome, pounded his glove and pawed the infield dirt with
his cleats as he shouted at his teammates to ``get down on the
ball.''
   At the plate, 7-year-old Sam Sage, who has spinabifida, took a
left-handed cut at the ball, knocked it off the tee a short distance
from the pitcher's mound and then spun his wheelchair toward first
base.
   ``I like to bat, bat, bat,'' Sage said later.
   The two are among the 25 boys and girls who play in the league
every Sunday morning on fields shared with the girls' softball
leagues. Like Alfred and Sam, most of the players have Down's
syndrome or spinabifida, a malformation of the bones in the spine.
   Under league rules, batters hit the ball off a 3-foot tee and run
base paths that are a few feet shorter than the Little League
distance of 60 feet. They also use a ball that is softer than the
typical Little League hardball.
   In addition, scores aren't kept and outs aren't recorded. Each
team bats its entire lineup and then takes the field. Each game is
played for about an hour with no set number of innings required.
   Allowing the handicapped youngsters a chance to toe the rubber
and dig in at the plate was what Norwich Little League president
James B. Rusiecki envisioned when he first began putting the league
together in 1986.
   ``They have just as much enthusiasm and heart as any of the kids
playing ball,'' says Rusiecki, a supervisor at a Norwich naval
products company. ``Why should a child have to stay home because he
or she may not be as good as anyone else?''
   Rusiecki's proposal, born from the desire of some parents to give
their handicapped children a chance to play ball, did not become a
reality without a fight.
   The board of directors of Little League Baseball Inc., the
national organization, rejected the proposal for a special-needs
program in February 1987 and refused to sanction it, citing
insurance problems and the possible need for professional educators.
   It was only after a similar league in Brockton, Mass., threatened
legal action that Little League officials relented and granted
Norwich a charter as a pilot program in February 1988.
   The national organization, based in Williamsport, Pa., earlier
this year launched a Challenger Division for handicapped youngsters
between the ages of 6 and 18. The new division's structure was based
on the findings of a Challenger Division Task Force headed by U.S.
Sen. Robert Dole, R-Kan., which conducted a two-year study.
   Steve D. Keener, a spokesman for the national organization, said
leagues also are operating in Bristol, Conn., Spring, Texas,
Louisville, Ky., and Brockton, Mass.
   ``We just wanted to give handicapped youngsters the same
experience of playing Little League baseball,'' Keener says.
   A number of parents pushed for the creation of a league. Like the
parents of other Little Leaguers, they give up their Sunday mornings
to watch their sons and daughters play ball. Some serve as player
assistants, instructing youngsters on bases and in the field.
   ``I think it's a good idea for the handicapped to get an
opportunity to play,'' says Kenneth Patrick as he stood behind first
base, giving a mixture of encouragement and instruction to his
7-year-old daughter, Rose, one of his three mentally retarded
daughters that play in the league. ``I'm all for it.''
   The support the league has gained both from parents and the local
businesses that sponsor teams and donate equipment has led some
league officials to seek expansion next year.
   Gary Mathieu, an orderly at Seaside Regional Center in Waterford,
who helped put the teams together last year, said the league hopes
to expand to four, 5-player teams next year and create a division
for 16 to 18 year olds.
   The goal, Mathieu said, is to make the program more competitive
and more in line with the traditional game of hits, runs and errors.
Smaller teams also allow for more individualized attention, he says.
   ``Each child would have a coach and they could become more
active,'' he says. ``We would like to teach the difference between a
fair ball and a foul ball and keep scores of the games. Right now
they are both winners and there are no losers.''
   Barbara M. Sullivan, a Norwich physical therapist who helped
start the league and serves as its technical adviser, says the
program should expand to create integrated teams, those mixing
handicapped and non-handicapped players. She tried to start an
integrated team for 4 to 6 year olds in the Norwich T-Ball League in
1982, but was turned down.
   ``This is just a foot in the door,'' says Sullivan, who operates
the Norwich Rehabilitation Center. ``We would not like to have a
separate league, but eventually integrate some players into the
regular team system.''
   But many of the youngsters are not worried about the score or
even winning or losing. They frequently exchange greetings when they
reach base and seem just as interested in socializing during the
one-hour games as playing.
   ``I like playing, but I also like being with the kids,'' says
12-year-old Lucy Waters of Montville, shyly pulling her Red Sox cap
down over her eyes.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890918-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1415EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APN--TVWeek Adv01   09-18 0943</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--TV Week, Adv 01,0965</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 1</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w photo.)
   </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elizabeth Taylor sees no parallel between her
own life and that of the woman she portrays in a new television
version of the Tennessee Williams play ``Sweet Bird of Youth.''
   In the movie, to be shown on NBC on Sunday, Taylor plays Princess
Alexandra Del Lago, a faded movie star seeking solace in booze,
drugs and affairs with young men.
   During a rare interview at her Bel-Air home, Taylor is asked if
she ever considered that she might be compared to Alexandra.
   ``That never occurred to me,'' she says, lounging on a couch in a
purple gown, with her bare feet tucked beneath her. ``We're both
actresses. She believes her career is over. I've never felt that.
She's a desperate lady. My desperation, if I've ever had it, had
nothing to do with my career.''
   After a long pause, she looks up from a cup of tea and adds,
``Other people may draw comparisons because we're both actresses.''
   Her black hair is done in a hairdo with lots of spikes. Her
complexion is darker than it appears on screen and she apparently
has gained a few pounds since her famous weight loss. But her violet
eyes are luminous, probing, mesmerizing.
   Typically, she refuses to discuss her private life, her many
marriages and divorces, her life-threatening illnesses, and her
problems with drugs and alcohol.
   Currently unmarried, Taylor has been romantically linked in
recent months to millionaire publisher Malcolm Forbes. They have
been frequently seen together and last month she was hostess of
sorts at his $2 million party in Morocco.
   Taylor says it took her 30 years to grow into the role Tennessee
Williams always wanted her to play in ``Sweet Bird.'' She was only
27 when the playwright created Alexandra.
   ``He wanted me to do this, but I wasn't right for it until now,''
says Taylor, who has had starring roles in four Williams plays.
   ``I love doing Tennessee Williams,'' she says. ``I love his way
with words and language, the way he has characters feed off each
other. And eat off each other. His dark side is dramatic and there
is a wonderful black humor in everything he writes.
   ``Now, the age is right for me. Everything was just right. If I
had been thinner I would have had to put on weight. My acting style
is instinctive and I try to become the person I'm playing.
   ``I found this part terrifying because of her sadness and despair
and lack of control. Once I got started, however, I found it was
easy and no longer frightening. I loved doing this character.''
   Taylor's long association with Williams began in 1958 when she
played Maggie the Cat in the movie version of ``Cat on a Hot Tin
Roof'' with Paul Newman and Burl Ives. She was Katharine Hepburn's
mad niece in ``Suddenly, Last Summer,'' which also starred
Montgomery Clift. She and her then-husband, Richard Burton, made
``Boom'' in 1968, the film version of ``The Milk Train Doesn't Stop
Here Anymore.''
   ``Sweet Bird of Youth'' made its Broadway debut in 1959 with
Geraldine Page as Alexandra. Page also starred in the 1962 movie
with Paul Newman as Chance, her latest and most dangerous conquest.
Ed Begley won an Oscar for his role as Boss Tom Finley.
   Mark Harmon is Chance in the two-hour NBC version. Boss Finley is
played by Rip Torn, who was Tom Finley Jr. on the stage and in the
movie and was married to Page. Michael Wilding, Taylor's son, has a
small role as a producer who tries to lure Alexandra back to
Hollywood.
   Taylor was doing ``Boom'' on location in Sardinia when Williams
first suggested she do the role of Alexandra. She decided she wasn't
right yet, but in 1981 she considered doing it on the stage.
Instead, she did Lillian Hellman's ``The Little Foxes'' on Broadway.
``Sweet Bird of Youth'' was later re-staged in New York and London.
   Taylor says she saw Alexandra as a very selfish and vain creature.
   ``Her saving grace is her sense of humor, which she does have,''
Taylor says. ``But in her selfishness, which she does pull out of at
the end because she really does care for Chance, she was quite
single-minded in the beginning. She was consumed with self-pity.
   ``She takes this young lover and doesn't know who he is at first.
Then she develops a real sense of compassion for him and realizes
the terrible danger he's in. She really tries to help him, but he's
bent on his own self-destruction.''
   In recent years, Taylor has appeared on television more than the
movie screen. She scoffs at the idea that she might do a series,
however.
   ``It's simply too much work,'' she says. ``That's why I like
television movies, because they're short, then they're over with. My
preference is to do only one thing a year.''
   Her last feature film, ``Toscanini,'' was released in Europe, but
according to some reports may never open in this country. She has
appeared regularly in TV movies, as well as the miniseries ``North
and South,'' and made guest appearances on the ABC series ``Hotel''
and the ABC soap opera ``General Hospital.''
   Taylor spends much of her time promoting her perfume, ``Elizabeth
Taylor's Passion.'' She says she chose its fragrance of Oriental
floral herself with the help of a French chemist. She is also
bringing out a man's cologne with a ``woodsy, citrusy'' fragrance.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890918-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1420EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek Adv01   09-18 1167</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Theater Week, Adv 01,1193</SECOND>
<HEAD>adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct 1</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w photo.
ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)    </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The story of Michael Bennett is the story of the
American musical theater during the last 25 years.
   As a dancer, choreographer and director, Bennett had an impact on
Broadway that still reverberates more than two years after his death
from AIDS at the age of 44.
   From his first appearance on Broadway in 1961 in the chorus of
``Subways Are for Sleeping'' to 1986 when he withdrew as director
from the London production of ``Chess,'' Bennett defined what it was
like to make musicals move.
   Now his career has been dissected by Ken Mandelbaum in ```A
Chorus Line' and the Musicals of Michael Bennett'' (St. Martin's
Press), a detailed and fascinating new book about the man's career
and the musicals he appeared in and helped to create.
   Mandelbaum, a former Brooklyn high school teacher, columnist for
``Theater Week'' magazine and musical theater buff extraordinaire,
looks at all of Bennett's shows, from the more conventional efforts
like ``Promises, Promises,'' ``Coco'' and ``Seesaw'' to his work on
two Sondheim masterpieces, ``Company'' and ``Follies.''
   But the book's centerpiece is an exhaustive examination of ``A
Chorus Line,'' the story of dancers auditioning for the chorus of a
Broadway show. The musical is currently in its 15th year at New
York's Shubert Theater and will reach performance number 6,000
before the end of the year.
   ``I always wondered why there wasn't a book on `A Chorus Line' _
either a big coffee-table script with lots of pictures or a book
about the making of the show because it was such a unique process,''
Mandelbaum was saying the other day. ``It revolutionized the way
musicals were made.''
   The show was born of highly personal and painful revelations. It
was based on some 24 hours of tape recordings made by Broadway
dancers talking about their lives, loves, hates, successes, failures
and what it was like to dance in the chorus of a Broadway show.
   Mandelbaum painstakingly traces the musical's evolution. It began
with those first sessions, initially proposed by dancers Tony
Stevens and Michon Peacock and then embraced by Bennett. It looks at
the development of the book by Nicholas Dante and James Kirkwood and
the music and lyrics by Marvin Hamlisch and Ed Kleban. More
important, the author shows how the musical was shaped and honed by
Bennett in a series of workshops.
   Bennett didn't invent the idea of workshops. Many plays,
particularly off-Broadway, had been developed by that method. But
starting with ``A Chorus Line,'' he used it to create musicals.
   Mandelbaum's book is deliberately non-personal. There are
private, even touching moments in it, but the focus of the book is
the work, not the man.
   ``His life was his art,'' Mandelbaum says. ``I wanted to do a
study of a career.''
   The author began the book in September 1987, two months after
Bennett's death. He did a month or two of research, mostly at the
performing arts library at Lincoln Center, and then took five or six
months to conduct interviews, more than 70 in all, with people who
had worked with Bennett.
   Some of them, like Katharine Hepburn, who starred in ``Coco,''
declined to be interviewed. So did many original cast members of ``A
Chorus Line.''
   ``With four or five exceptions, they were the most difficult to
get to,'' Mandelbaum says. ``Some of them never really got over `A
Chorus Line.' It put them in a position that they really weren't
accustomed to and maybe they shouldn't have been in. Michael made
them look like these fascinating people. After that, there was
really no follow-up. So it was hard for them to talk about it.
   ``And because the book used their lives, to a degree, from the
tapes, they feel exploited by the show. Even though, as you know,
Michael gave them all royalties. More than one of them told me, `We
were exploited by that show and I don't want to be exploited
anymore.'''
   Stardom has eluded all of the original cast members of ``A Chorus
Line,'' although many continue to work in musical theater.
   ``None of them has had a role that showed them off the way that
show did,'' Mandelbaum says. ``I think what happened to those people
is a perfect example of how hard it is nowadays to find steady work
on Broadway.
   ``That's one reason why `Chorus Line' is so interesting. It's a
show about Broadway and dancers and performers. And what happened to
them is the whole story of Broadway in that period.''
   Mandelbaum never met Bennett.
   ``I came to think that was an advantage,'' he says now. ``I could
listen to what everyone was telling me about him without any ax to
grind or personal feelings to color it. So when people told me the
way he affected them _ both good and bad _ I could just sort of take
it in.
   ``But by the time I was finished with the book, I did feel I
really knew him.''
   One of the most intriguing aspects of Mandelbaum's book is his
chapter on ``Scandal,'' the Bennett musical that might-have-been.
The show, which had a book by television writer Treva Silverman and
music and lyrics by Jimmy Webb, tells of one woman's sexual
liberation. It never got beyond several workshop productions and was
canceled abruptly in 1985, most think, because Bennett learned he
was dying of AIDS.
   ``I truly believe that `Scandal' would have been fabulous,''
Mandelbaum says. ``The staging would have been so unusual. It had
long 20-minute sequences, a lot like `Lady in the Dark,' which were
the woman's fantasies.
   ``The book of the musical is very funny. And everyone insisted
the choreography was the greatest of Michael's career, unbelievably
beautiful, aesthetic-looking and pure. His stuff was so moral and
pristine that it made the sex and the wild and lewd comedy in the
show work. Everyone connected with it insisted that the show would
not have offended anyone. It would have made them think about right
and wrong.''
   Whatever the promise of ``Scandal,'' it was never realized, and
Bennett never staged another musical.
   But the saga of Michael Bennett is not likely to end _ at least
not in print. More Bennett books are in the making. Already out is
``The Untold Story Behind the Making of `A Chorus Line,''' (Bantam
Books) by Denny Martin Flinn, a dancer who appeared in a national
tour of the musical.
   Kevin Kelly, theater critic for The Boston Globe, has ``The
Michael Bennett Story'' arriving from Doubleday early next year.
Next March will mark the appearance of ``On the Line'' by Robert
Viagas (William Morrow). Subtitled ``The Creation of `A Chorus
Line','' it will be the memoirs of 19 original cast members of the
long-running show.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
