<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1425EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Jordan'sFuture Adv24-2Takes   09-18 0861</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Jordan's Future, Adv 24-2 Takes,0882</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 24, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>King Hussein's Jordan Tip-Toes Toward Wider Democracy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: accompanying items are BC-Jordan History, b0656, and BC-Jordan-Royals,
b0657.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Hussein is pushing Jordan toward its
first nationwide elections in 22 years, an event that could
transform a country crucial to the Middle East's balance of power.
   More than 1,000 candidates are testing their chances for the the
80 Parliament seats at stake Nov. 8 as a push toward greater
democracy and looser government control sweeps across the kingdom.
Martial law has been in place since the 1967 war with Israel.
   ``People are hungry for elections, for participation, after a
long absence,'' said Taher Masri, who resigned as deputy prime
minister in August in order to seek a seat from Amman. Active
Cabinet ministers are not allowed to run.
   The new Parliament will replace one originally elected in April
1967, two months before the Six Day War with Israel, and then became
largely ineffective. The body was suspended by Hussein in times of
difficulty and then lost about half its membership when the king
renounced Jordan's claim to the West Bank last year. No West Bankers
will be allowed to run for the new Parliament and candidates who do
run cannot do so under the banners of political parties, which have
been banned since an attempted coup in 1957.
   The election, however, accompanies a basic change in the nature
of the Jordan itself.
   Hussein's renunciation to claims to the West Bank, seized by
Israel in 1967, ended Jordan's main rivalry with the Palestine
Liberation Organization and helped accelerate a thrust toward
settlement of the 40-year-old Arab-Israeli conflict.
   Hussein's Hashemite kingdom of about 3 million people _ roughly
half of them Palestinians _ has now turned inward in a struggle to
reform an economy saddled with $8.3 billion in debts, a battle
dramatized by widespread rioting in April against economic hardship
and government repressiveness.
   ``This is a turning point in our life,'' candidate Masri said.
``The past era is gone and gone probably forever.''
   Liberals like Masri say the elections should lay the groundwork
for a stable, constitutional monarchy with a working Parliament to
thresh out grievances.
   The outgoing 60-member Parliament was suspended in 1974, then
revived in 1984, with a handful of local elections to replace
members who had died.
   Hussein scrapped the Parliament altogether last year as part of
his renunciation of claims to the West Bank. The economic riots
prodded the government to advance the date for the elections.
   Most previous Parliaments were little more than
government-dominated talking shops. But Masri and other officials
resigned from powerful posts to run in the elections, indicating
their faith that the new body will have a significant role.
   Skeptics fear, however, the voting could once again unleash
radical emotions among frustrated Palestinian refugees and
unemployed youngsters like those who threatened to rip the kingdom
apart in the late 1950s and again in 1970.
   Jordan's ability to cope with change is vital to any Arab peace
with Israel, whose longest border is with Jordan. Many in the
kingdom still have family and economic ties with the occupied West
Bank and with the Gaza Strip, which was administered by Egypt until
Israel seized it in the 1967 war.
   Jordan is also a vital buffer between four strategic countries:
Israel, Saudi Arabia, Syria and Iraq. It separates the powderkeg of
the Arab-Israeli conflict from the world's main sources of oil.
   The Palestinian guerrillas who tried to topple Hussein in 1970
are today more allies than rivals and are taking a hands-off
approach to the elections.
   While roughly half of Jordanians are from Palestinian families,
many over the past 40 years have come to identify with Jordan, the
only Arab country to give them passports.
   The royal family's descent from Islam's prophet, Mohammed, has
always helped blunt radical Islamic dissent.
   Hussein has patched up his frayed relations with the conservative
Moslem Brotherhood, the country's largest independent political
force.
   But some officials, who use a widespread intelligence and police
network to stifle radical dissenters, remain concerned about
potential Islamic extremism.
   The government does not feel secure enough to lift the ban on
political parties or martial law. Even government critics are wary
of too much change too fast.
   Laith Shubeilat, an independent Islamic activist who heads the
engineers association, argued that no one is ``ready to make a
dramatic change. The change should be slow.''
   Jordan was remarkably stable for most of the 1980s, thanks to
prosperity fed by income sent home by 350,000 Jordanian workers in
the Persian Gulf and grants from oil-producing Arab nations there.
   Falling oil prices squeezed that flow of money in recent years,
and Jordan borrowed to keep up spending on arms and luxury goods.
The resulting debt crashed down on the country last year. Prices for
imports soared as the dinar currency's value fell. Local wages were
stagnant.
   Anger at rising prices and perceived government arrogance boiled
over in April when riots erupted in the south, the rural heartland
of Hussein's support.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890918-0199 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1445EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Jordan'sFuture Adv24-1stAdd   09-18 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Jordan's Future, Adv 24-1st Add,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 24, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AMMAN: Hussein's support.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Hussein fired Prime Minister Zaid Rifai's government and promised
democratic reforms.
   He staved off economic collapse by cajoling more than $350
million in grants from alarmed Persian Gulf states, and his
ministers reached a series of debt-rescheduling agreements with
international lenders.
   The dinar, which plunged to $1 in July from a high of about $3
early last year, moved back up to about $1.50.
   But economists say Jordan faces years of austerity and high
unemployment.
   That is a dangerous prospect for an ambitious young generation
whose European-standard educational level is one of Jordan's
greatest assets.
   Hundreds of graduates, many of them jobless, line up daily
outside the U.S. Embassy to apply for visas.
   In Maan, where the economic riots broke out, people interviewed
recently said the edge had gone off their wrath, although anger at
the police remains.
   ``The people are satisfied now,'' said 26-year-old Aqab Khatib,
son of a prominent clan leader.
   The criticism that stormed around Prime Minister Rifai
occasionally crept upward to touch Hussein, Crown Prince Hassan and
Queen Noor, who were accused of condoning government abuses and of
wasting money.
   Despite frequent medical checkups, the 53-year-old monarch still
appears vigorous. In early September, he set a course record in an
automobile hillclimb and is seen repeatedly on television touring
towns and military bases.
   Hussein has ridden out the Middle East's turbulence and escaped
several assassination attempts in 35 years on the throne.
   But his health and survival remain constant subjects of
speculation in a country so closely identified with its ruler.
   Political analyst Rami Khoury, former editor of the Jordan Times,
said the country ``is on the verge of a new stage of political
participation'' no matter who reigns.
   Hussein's Oxford-educated brother Hassan, heir to the throne,
lacks the king's popularity, but he has championed the sort of
openness that reformers have demanded.
   The only major power base that might challenge the monarchy, the
army, remains fiercely loyal by all accounts.
   The king has more time to cement that loyalty following his
renunciation of claims to the West Bank and his retreat from 20
years as a starring player in frustrated Arab-Israeli peace efforts.
   The 21-month-old anti-Israeli uprising in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip shattered the last vestiges of loyalties to Jordan among the
950,000 West Bank Palestinians.
   Hussein cast their fate to the PLO, prodding that organization to
declare a state roughly encompassing the West Bank and the Gaza
Strip and to meet U.S. conditions for talks, ending a 13-year
boycott.
   Yet Jordan remains crucial to any settlement and the king holds
the power to sway events.
   Americans and Israelis want Jordan as a watchdog over the 1.7
million Palestinians on the West Bank and in the Gaza Strip to help
prevent an independent Palestinian state.
   The PLO proposes an eventual confederation of equals between
Jordan and that state. Israeli hardliners led by former Defense
Minister Ariel Sharon want to make Jordan itself a Palestinian
state, an idea bitterly opposed by most Jordanians and Palestinians.
   Hussein's nightmare is the call by some Israeli radicals to push
West Bank Palestinians into his kingdom, swamping it with refugees
for a third time to threaten the Hashemite throne.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 24</NOTE>
</DOC>
