<FIRST>s i BC-Jordan-History Adv24   09-18 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Jordan-History, Adv 24,0601</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 24, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Key Dates in History of Jordan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Jordan's Future, b0654-b0655</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some important dates in the history of Jordan:
   1916-18 _ Emir Hussein Bin Ali of Mecca and his sons revolt
against Turkish rule during World War I with the aid of Britain,
which promises them a vast postwar Arab kingdom.
   1920 _ Britain reneges on promises and cuts up the area with the
French in a postwar mandate. The French expel Emir Hussein's son
Feisal as king of Syria (British later make him king of Iraq).
Feisal's brother Abdullah arrives in what later becomes Jordan.
   1921 _ Britain separates the new emirate of Transjordan from the
Ottoman territories of Syria, Hejaz and Palestine and persuades a
reluctant Abdullah to become emir of the British protectorate on a
six-month trial basis.
   1937 _ Abdullah is the only major Arab leader to endorse a call
for partitioning Palestine into Jewish and Arab sectors, the Arab
sector to be ruled by Transjordan.
   1946 _ Transjordan gains independence from Britain, with Abdullah
as king.
   1948 _ Abdullah's British-led Arab Legion joins the war against
newly established Israel and holds onto the West Bank and East
Jerusalem. With the new territories, the kingdom changes its name to
Jordan in 1950. Palestinian refugees flood country.
   1951 _ Abdullah is assassinated by disgruntled Palestinian
nationalists and his son Talal takes the throne.
   1952 _ Talal abdicates because of mental illness and the throne
passes to Abdullah's grandson, the 17-year-old Hussein, who takes up
power in 1953 after reaching his 18th birthday by the Islamic
calendar.
   1956 _ Hussein expels British military officers, holds free
elections. Leftist sentiment sweeps the Arab world as Israel,
Britain and France attack Egypt in the Suez War.
   1957 _ Hussein squashes a leftist coup and bans political parties.
   1958 _ Hussein's cousin, King Faisal, is assassinated in a
leftist coup in Iraq. British troops help protect Jordan.
   1967 _ Hussein joins Egypt and Syria in the war against Israel
and loses the West Bank and East Jerusalem. More than 200,000
Palestinian refugees flood the kingdom. Hussein imposes martial law.
   1970 _ Hussein's army crushes Palestinian guerrillas who had
threatened his throne during fighting that became known as ``Black
September.'' The army also beats back a Syrian invasion.
   1973 _ Jordan sends a token force to help Syria in the fourth
Arab-Israeli war.
   1974 _ The Arab League recognizes the Palestine Liberation
Organization as sole representative of the Palestinians. Hussein
responds by suspending Parliament, half of which represents West
Bank Palestinians.
   1978 _ Jordan, left out of U.S.-sponsored Egypt-Israel peace
talks, rejects the resulting Camp David peace accords and joins an
Arab boycott of Egypt, arguing against separate settlements.
   1983-85 _ Hussein unsuccessfully tries to bring the United States
and PLO together for peace effort with Israel.
   1986-87 _ Jordan launches a West Bank development plan tacitly
supported by Israel that challenges the PLO role on the West Bank.
It collapses when pro-PLO rioting breaks out in Jordan in November
1987.
   1988 _ Hussein renounces sovereignty over the West Bank in favor
of the PLO and encourages the organization to accept U.S. conditions
for talks. He insists he will never negotiate on behalf of
Palestinians. He suspends Parliament.
   1989 _ Four days of riots over economic problems sweep Jordan.
Hussein changes the government and calls elections for a new
Parliament.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 24</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890918-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1447EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Jordan-Royals Adv24   09-18 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Jordan-Royals, Adv 24,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 24, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Thumbnail Sketches of Key Members of Jordan's Royal Family</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Jordan's Future, b0654-b0655</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are brief sketches of key figures in
Jordan's royal family:
   KING HUSSEIN _ The grandson of Jordan's founder, King Abdullah,
the 53-year-old monarch has ruled for 36 of Jordan's 41 years of
independence. His family draws its legitimacy from its history as
guardians of Mecca, Islam's holiest city, and its descent from the
Prophet Mohammed.
   QUEEN NOOR _ The American-born daughter of former Pan Am airlines
Chairman Najeeb Halaby, an Arab-American, she met Hussein while
doing contract work for Royal Jordanian Airways and married him in
1979. Hussein's fourth wife, she has given him four children: Prince
Hamzeh, 9; Prince Hashim, 8; Princess Iman, 6; and Princess Raiyah,
3. The Princeton-educated queen, 38, sponsors women's societies,
social work and arts. She also acts as a goodwill ambassador.
   CROWN PRINCE HASSAN _ The younger of Hussein's two brothers,
Hassan, 42, was named crown prince in 1965 while earning a degree in
Oriental studies at Oxford in England. Noted as the palace
intellectual, he oversees economic development and sponsors seminars
on a wide range of topics. He is married to the Pakistani-born
Princess Tharwat. They have four children, although the royal line
is due to return to Hussein's offspring.
   QUEEN ZEIN _ The queen mother, she was the wife of the late King
Talal, Hussein's father, who abdicated due to mental illness in
1952. She was an important adviser in the early days of Hussein's
reign, but now in her 70s, plays a low-key role.
   PRINCE ALI _ Hussein's eldest child by an Arab mother, the late
Queen Alia, Ali, 13, is designated to become king after Hassan. The
remainder of the line of succession is open to constitutional
interpretation of the question of the children having non-Arab
mothers, the American-born Queen Noor and the British-born Princess
Muna, Hussein's previous wife.
   PRINCE ABDULLAH _ Hussein's eldest child, he was named crown
prince at birth in 1962, but the title was later given to Hassan due
to political turmoil at the time and because Abdullah's mother,
British-born Princess Muna, Hussein's second wife, was not Arab. The
prince, 27, has inherited Hussein's interest in rally-car racing and
flying. He attended prep schools in the United States, studied at
Britain's Sandhurst military academy and is an army lieutenant. He
sometimes acts as regent when both Hussein and Hassan are abroad.
   PRINCE FAISAL _ Hussein's second son by Muna, Faisal, 25, is an
air force pilot who won honors at a military training course in
Britain. He studied electrical engineering at Brown University in
Providence, R.I., and has played an increasingly visible role,
sometimes acting as regent.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 24</NOTE>
</DOC>
