<DOCNO> AP890918-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 2252EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   09-18 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   Madrigals by Sigismondo d'India, Claudio Monteverdi; Chiaroscuro
and London Baroque, directed by Nigel Rogers (EMI)
   
   Italian madrigals as an art form display perhaps the most perfect
marriage of words and music. They are poems in song, in which
musical notes paint pictures of language.
   How particularly infuriating, then, that this otherwise excellent
recording contains only a German translation of the Italian text.
What about us English-speakers, not to mention French?
   Yet even those monolingual among us can generally recognize words
such as ``crudel,'' ``amore'' and ``morte.'' We don't even need to
know their meaning with the dramatic, vivid interpretation by
Chiaroscuro, the vocal ensemble consisting of tenor and director
Nigel Rogers, two sopranos, bass, a counter-tenor and second tenor.
   Their performance strikes a nice balance between the
over-homogenized quality of some ensembles and the over-wrought,
extra-dramatized readings of others.
   This disc shows us music by one of the best-known Italian
madrigalists, Monteverdi, and the obscure d'India, and presents them
in two guises. On the first half, we hear the more familiar,
ensemble-sung madrigal; the second half contains music that points
to opera _ works in which singers take on roles, sometimes limited
to two or three voices.
   The high point of this disc is Monteverdi's ``Hor che'l ciel e la
terra,'' a stunning setting of a Petrarch sonnet. In the space of 14
lines, the music moves from a slow, eerie opening to a series of
loudly declaimed words to a florid, rapid section and finally to the
long, beautiful cadence on the last word, ``lunge.'' Emotions vary
from word to word. It's as if the range of a three-hour opera is
compressed into nine minutes. The performance is masterful.
   For those familiar with this repertoire, the presence of the
rarely heard d'India _ who called himself the ``Noble Palermitano''
_ should prove welcome. His musical language is simpler and less
ornate, his lines more extended.
   _ By Daniel Wakin, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``World in Motion'' (Elektra) _ Jackson Browne
   
   The album opens with a funky beat and Jackson Browne singing,
``Sun going down on the USA.'' Party time, right? Let's dance! After
all, the name of the song is ``World in Motion.''
   But wait. ``Now we awake with a world at stake,'' Browne sings.
So this is not good-time music; it's an entreaty to BMW owners.
   Browne's fountain of sorrow has become a mountain of fret. It
includes the homeless, hunger and hatred, gangs and greed, war and
weapons.
   Browne obviously reads the paper, but the record exposes a
certain naivete, such as when he rails against the need for nuclear
weapons on ``How Long.'' On the title cut, he volunteers to help the
world realize its potential.
   Still, heart and sincerity count for something; ``World in
Motion'' has plenty of both. And musically, the record is terrific.
``Anything Can Happen,'' for example, is one of Browne's loveliest
melodies. ``Chasing You Into the Light'' is a catchy rocker.
   The final cut, ``Lights and Virtue,'' includes a sizzling guitar
duel between Browne and Kevin Dukes, as well as the album's most
assured lyric. ``Here's to truths yet to be known ... the search for
things of your own,'' Browne sings.
   On ``World in Motion,'' such abstract sentiments have the truest
ring.
   _ By Steven Wine, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
