<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Willis Adv29-01   09-18 0897</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Willis, Adv 29-01,0928</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 29-Oct. 1, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: Thoughts of Immortality, Wisecracks and Lazy Charm</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smirks, wisecracks, lazy charm. Bruce Willis
calls them his tools, what carried him through four seasons of
``Moonlighting'' and last year's hit action film ``Die Hard.''
   But the 34-year-old actor is tired of just playing for laughs.
Now, thinking about how future audiences will remember him, Willis
balances his admiration for the Three Stooges with a desire to
portray enduring dramatic characters.
   So he welcomed the chance to start from scratch with Warner
Bros.' ``In Country,'' playing the troubled Vietnam War veteran,
Emmett.
   ``I was pretty scared, and I didn't really know if I could do
it,'' Willis said in a recent interview.
   ``Look, if I had done 4{ years of a guy who was angst-ridden and
was carrying around a lot of weight, I would have waltzed through
this thing. But on each step I had to make sure I was taking the
right step.''
   The boyish grin and urbane looks that Willis had as David Addison
in ``Moonlighting'' has disappeared for ``In Country.'' Instead,
there's a ``Fu Manchu'' mustache, long, slicked-back hair and a
dull, pained expression in his eyes. Fans may be shocked, but Willis
sees it as part of his job.
   ``That's what actors are supposed to be doing. If you're not
taking risks, you might as well work in TV. TV doesn't require you
to take any risk, that's why I went after this film,'' he said.
   ``I had just done 4{ years of playing the same guy, the same
character. I wasn't taking any risk at all. I wanted to do something
I wasn't sure I could do.''
   Television is a bad memory for Willis, who insists only his
contract kept him from leaving ``Moonlighting'' after the second
season. He worried that the public would know him only for one role,
that his abilities would be eaten up from the demands of producing
new material each week.
   ``Glenn (Gordon Caron, executive producer) said after the first
year we'd come to a point where there's nothing left to say. He knew
even then. It was bound to happen. It's a very cyclical thing,''
Willis said.
   ``You're just pouring yourself into this thing. I was concerned I
was going to use all my stuff on this show, that we were going to
exhaust ourselves.''
   Emmett was like an old friend for Willis, who met several Vietnam
vets while bartending in his native New Jersey. Like Sam (Emily
Lloyd), Emmett's teen-age niece in ``In Country'' who begs her uncle
to talk about the war, Willis wanted to learn what happened in
Vietnam.
   ``I've been researching this character for a long time,'' he
said. ``I have always been fascinated with the war itself, the
effect it had on American guys. I know what makes most of us what we
are, but I saw there was something different, that they saw
something there that freaked them out.
   ``I found things I had no idea I was ever going to find. I found
out things about myself, things about the Vietnam War. That's one of
the really unique things about acting, if you make yourself work
hard enough in this direction, you're going to find things you never
heard of.''
   Up to now, his style has been patterned on the breezy, detached
leading men of 1930s and '40s romantic comedies, actors such as
William Powell, Clark Gable and, especially, Cary Grant.
   ``He's the king,'' Willis said. ``His comic timing was superb,
even in films that didn't do so well, like `Arsenic and Old Lace.' I
could never figure how he did it.''
   Willis admired Grant's resourcefulness, the way he gently
manipulated the other characters in such classics as ``The
Philadelphia Story'' and ``The Awful Truth.'' He tried to use the
same techniques in ``Moonlighting,'' playing off the straight-laced
Cybill Shepherd.
   ``I always thought if you could make somebody laugh, you could
get them off balance, and if you could get them off balance, you
could get what you want from them,'' he said.
   While ``Moonlighting'' drew on the snappy dialogue of Grant's
movies, ``In Country'' was based on the spare language of Bobbie Ann
Mason's best-selling novel. Willis credited director Norman Jewison
(``Moonstruck,'' ``In the Heat of the Night'') with fine-tuning his
character.
   ``You can't play stoicism,'' Willis said, ``You can't play
somebody that sits there like a mope. You have to have something
coming out. So much of what my character had to communicate in this
film was done non-verbally.''
   Personally and professionally, he'll be busy for the coming year.
Willis is married to actress Demi Moore, who gave birth to daughter
Rumer Glenn during the filming of ``In Country.''
   A sequel to ``Die Hard'' is planned, and his second album, ``If
It Don't Kill You, It Makes You Stronger,'' comes out this fall.
   Willis also ponders life.
   ``I think about dying,'' he said.
   ``What scares me most is dying before you get anything done. I'm
starting out with things that have some kind of longevity, that will
hopefully be around. It's something that outlasts you. It does give
you a little bit of immortality.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Sept. 29-Oct. 1</NOTE>
