<DOCNO> AP890918-0207 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 2304EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Dunne Adv29-01   09-18 0929</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Dunne, Adv 29-01,0958</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 29-Oct 1, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: A Dramatic Restructuring of Facts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For some writers, ``facts'' can be more deceptive
than fiction. Just ask John Gregory Dunne, author of the
best-selling novels ``True Confessions'' and ``The Red, White and
Blue.''
   His new book, ``Harp,'' is a non-fictional account of travels,
family history and health problems. But Dunne admits that some
dramatic restructuring has been performed, events rearranged for the
sake of a writer's most sacred truth, a better story.
   That's why Dunne insists ``Harp'' was never really meant to be
written. It's also why he includes disclaimers throughout, invoking
an author's privilege to reinvent history.
   ``I was going to publish a book of essays with a longish
introduction, 5,000 words,'' said Dunne, whose wife, Joan Didion, is
author of ``Play It as It Lays'' and ``A Book of Common Prayer.''
   ``Last spring, I began writing this introduction and I got to
6,000 words rather quickly and kept on going. It got bigger and
bigger and longer and if I had conceived of it as a book I never
would have written it.
   ``When I got to about 100 pages, which is approximately 20-25,000
words, my wife said, `This is a book.'''
   Reluctantly, he agreed and eventually put enough material into
his computer to fill 234 pages. That may seem pretty modest for
readers, but as Dunne wrote at the book's conclusion and repeated in
a recent interview, a writer's life is his capital and 50,000 words
is a substantial expenditure.
   He also noted that material can come from anywhere. Dunne
introduces one chapter with an unusual personal ad that appeared in
the Los Angeles Times: ``TO MY Comrades in the Resistance concerning
Cheka Occupation Via Mexico. Cheka has learned of our existence.''
   Casual readers would chuckle slightly, if they could be bothered
to look at all. But items like these are buried treasure for Dunne.
   ``What does that mean, who would put that in? You really indulge
in something like that,'' he said.
   ```Dutch Shea' began with a piece in The New York Times. I got
sent several copies from various writers who said `This is your
material.' Joyce Carol Oates is an inveterate reader of the little
tiny filler items, there's a lot of material there.''
   Opinionated, confessional and investigative, Dunne's writing
incorporates the three ``p's'' that he said once provided escapes
from the Irish ghetto: politics, priesthood and the police.
   A fourth ``p'' should be kept in mind: performer. That's how he
sees himself and other writers. Reading a work by Dunne is like
having a man approach you at the bar, slam his drink on the counter
and tell his life story.
   ``I'm interested in getting the character's voice,'' the author
said. ``I was having breakfast with Joan one morning, and I came up
with the first line of a monologue. I went upstairs and I wrote it
before lunch, 13 pages for just one monologue.''
   In ``Harp,'' he challenges readers with detailed accounts of
prostitutes, family deaths and his own recent heart troubles.
   Dunne, 57, noted that other authors of his generation _ Philip
Roth, Reynolda Price _ had also recently written about their private
lives and offered his own theory why.
   ``I say we have all had life-threatening experiences. Philip just
had bypass surgery. Reynolds Price had cancer. It makes one somewhat
meditative,'' he said. Didion's multiple sclerosis is in remission.
   ``My wife insists that it's a product of good times and we never
had a war,'' Dunne said. ``Philip and I were both in the peacetime
army, and because we didn't have a war to always fall back in, there
comes a time I should write something like this.''
   Dunne was born in Hartford, Conn., the fifth of six children.
Like authors John Updike and W. Somerset Maugham, he was a stutterer
and turned to the written word as a way of mastering language.
   ``If you feel that you can't be a lawyer or a brain surgeon, I
think you begin to think about what you can do. It's interesting the
number of devices people use to get by stammering. You never stammer
if you're singing, for instance.''
   He graduated from Princeton University in 1954 and worked five
years as a staff writer for Time magazine. Dunne married Didion in
1964 and was overshadowed by her until the publication of ``True
Confessions'' 13 years later.
   A tough, bleak account of a woman's brutal murder and its
connection to two brothers, a policeman and a priest, ``True
Confessions'' sold more than 1 million copies and was eventually
made into a film starring Robert Duvall and Robert De Niro with a
screenplay by Dunne and Didion.
   Writing has now become a full-time job, Dunne said, even when
reading others. Admiration for an author's work gives way to
curiosity about the methods used to produce it. He cited Updike's
``Rabbit Is Rich,'' whose title character runs an auto dealership.
   ```Rabbit Is Rich' is an astonishing book,'' Dunne said. ``I
wonder how he found out so much about that Toyota agency. It was
sublime. You very seldom get to see in American fiction how people
work. You make them a lawyer or a writer.
   ``Writers read differently than other people, they read at rather
than read. They're interested in how it got there and how certain
effects are done.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Sept. 29-Oct. 1</NOTE>
