<FIRST>r f PM-Bankers-Credit     09-18 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bankers-Credit,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey: Debt Ratings of Latin America and Africa Continue To Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A broad range of nations gained in
creditworthiness in the past year, according to a survey of
international bankers, but the debt reputation of Latin American and
African nations continued to decline.
   The 30 nations with improved credit reputations among the bankers
over the past year included both industrial countries and
oil-producing nations, according to Institutional Investor magazine,
which conducted the survey for release today.
   Among the 15 biggest losers in credit reputation were six nations
in Latin America and six in Africa, the magazine said in a news
release. Results of the survey are contained in the magazine's
September issue.
   The winners included such smaller nations as Barbados, Oman,
Qatar and Cyprus, while the losers included China, Brazil and
Nigeria.
   The survey results showed a growing gap between the credit
ratings of richer and poor nations, the magazine said. While Asian
countries as a whole continue to move closer to becoming wealthy
nations, Latin America sinks toward Africa's numbers and Africa
continues a slide of its own, it said.
   ``Growing despondency about Third World debt among the bankers
who participate in this survey has tarnished their views of Latin
American and African countries _ and unleased what bankers
inevitably call a flight to quality, which translates into higher
ratings for many industrial nations,'' the magazine said.
   The United States remained in fourth place in creditworthiness,
behind Japan, Switzerland and West Germany.
   Uganda, Nicaragua and North Korea continued to languish at the
bottom of the list, ranked 110th, 111th and 112th, respectively.
   Every six months the magazine surveys 75 to 100 bankers to rate
the creditworthiness of 112 nations on a scale of 0 to 100.
   In the 10 years the magazine has conducted the survey the ratings
of Iraq, Argentina, Mexico, Brazil, Nigeria, Liberia and a number of
other Latin American and African nations have plunged dramatically.
   Among the winners over the decade, the biggest improvement came
from Turkey, which climbed from 89th to 44th place. Also showing
significant improvement in creditworthiness over the period were
Taiwan, Portugal, Cyprus and Spain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
