<HEAD>Lloyds Bank Sell U.S. Business to Japanese Bank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lloyds Bank PLC Monday said it has agreed to sell
its U.S. commercial banking business to Daiwa Bank Ltd. of Japan for
$200 million.
   Lloyds said the sale involves 15 offices. The U.S. business had
after-tax profit of $11 million in 1988. It had $1.5 billion in
assets at the end of last year.
   ``The sale is consistent with our policy of concentrating our
resources on mainstream activities which can make a significant
contribution to our total business results,'' said Lloyds' chief
executive, Brian Pitman.
   Pitman said the U.S. business has ``little linkage'' with Lloyds'
other activities.
   Lloyds said it will continue its corporate banking and treasury
operations based in New York, and its Miami, Florida-based private
banking business.
</TEXT>
