<FIRST>r f BC-BAT     09-18 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-BAT,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hoylake Says It Controls 2.3 Percent of BAT Shares</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hostile bidder Hoylake Investments Ltd. said Monday
it controls 2.3 percent of its target, the British conglomerate BAT
Industries PLC.
   Hoylake, an investor group led by Anglo-French financier Sir
James Goldsmith, also announced that it would keep its all-paper $21
billion offer open until 1400 GMT on Sept. 29.
   Last week, Hoylake was given more time for its bid when the
British Panel on Takeovers and Mergers said Hoylake could let its
bid for BAT lapse until it had cleared all regulatory hurdles with
U.S. insurance commissioners. Hoylake can then relaunch its offer
within 21 days, the panel ruled.
   Normally a bidder which has failed to secure a majority stake in
its target within the required 90 days would have to wait a year
before bidding again.
   BAT stock was trading lower, at the equivalent of $12.62 a share,
off 16 cents, at midday on the London Stock Exchange.
   Hoylake's offer values BAT at $13.70 a share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
