<SECOND>PM-Meridian-First Pennsylvania, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0021,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>CoreStates, First Pennsylvania Announce Merger Agreement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede READING</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with CoreStates, First Pennsylvania reaching
agreement. ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CoreStates Financial Corp. and First
Pennsylvania Corp. today announced a $730 million merger agreement
that would create a leading mid-Atlantic banking organization with
nearly $23 billion in assets.
   Announcement of the tax-free $18.75-a-share deal, approved this
morning by First Pennsylvania's board, followed a weekend during
which the battle for control of First Pennsylvania intensified.
   On Saturday, Meridian Bancorp Inc., responding to CoreStates'
offer, said it intended to increase its earlier $704 million bid to
buy First Pennsylvania.
   But today CoreStates and First Pennsylvania said in a joint
statement that their merger was approved after discussion with
Meridian.
   Meanwhile, First Pennsylvania and Marine Midland Banks Inc.,
which had agreed earlier to acquire First Pennsylvania, will
terminate their agreement, according to terms of the merger plan
with CoreStates.
   Marine Midland, a unit of Hongkong &amp; Shanghai Banking Corp. of
Hong Kong, was to have acquired First Pennsylvania next spring.
   CoreStates chairman Terrence A. Larsen said the merger would
create an unspecified number of jobs and result in no layoffs. The
deal, subject to approval by shareholders and regulators, is
targeted for completion by the end of 1990.
   ``In large part our branch systems are complementary,'' said
Larsen. ``The combination will give us the strongest possible base
for providing both retail and commercial customers in all parts of
the region with conveniently located services.''
   Under the agreement, First Pennsylvania will become an operating
subsidiary of CoreStates, retaining its name as have CoreStates'
three existing full-service banks _ Philadelphia National Bank,
Hamilton and New Jersey National.
   George A. Butler, chairman of First Pennsylvania, will become
president of CoreStates. Butler previously had been considering
retiring in early 1991 but, at Larsen's request, he has agreed to
postpone his departure until the end of that year.
   Larsen will remain chairman and chief executive officer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
