<FIRST>r f BC-KelloggPresident     09-18 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Kellogg President,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Horst W. Schroeder Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATTLE CREEK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kellogg Co. President and Chief
Operating Officer Horst W. Schroeder has resigned, citing personal
reasons, the company announced Monday.
   Kellogg Chairman and Chief Executive Officer William E. LaMothe
said he would assume responsibilities of the president's office.
   Schroeder, 48, had been with the world's largest cereal company
for 19 years and had been president and chief operating officer
since December 1988.
   LaMothe said in a news release that Schroeder resigned from the
company and as a board member for personal reasons.
   Kellogg officials refused to elaborate on the reasons for the
resignation or comment on a possible permanent successor to
Schroeder.
   Schroeder, a native of Schwerin, Germany, joined Kellogg in 1970
as financial controller of Kellogg (Deutchland) GmbH.
   In 1976 he was promoted to managing director for Germany, Austria
and Switzerland and in 1978 was given responsibility for the
Mediterranean area.
   He was promoted to president and chief executive officer of
Kellogg Salada Canada Inc. in January 1981 and appointed executive
vice president of Kellogg Co. in January 1984.
   He was named president and chief operating officer of Kellogg Co.
in December 1988 and elected to the board of directors in April 1989.
   Kellogg's latest fiscal-year earnings were $480.4 million on
revenue of $4.35 billion. General Mills Co. is the world's
second-largest cereal producer.
</TEXT>
