<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1246EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-FirstBank     09-18 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-First Bank,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Bank Mulls Workforce Cut as Part of Restructuring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First Bank System is considering cutting its
work force by 15 percent to 20 percent over the next year under a
restructuring that could cost up to $40 million and reduce assets by
$2 billion, the company announced Monday.
   Chairman D.H. Ankeny Jr. said the possible restructuring is still
being studied by management and has not been presented to the board
of directors.
   ``We must seriously consider eliminating or downsizing some of
our businesses that have risk characteristics that exceed their
reward potential or that no longer provide the return our
shareholders expect,'' Ankeny said.
   He said the restructuring could cost $25 million to $40 million,
which could be booked as a loss in the third or fourth quarter.
   The company said it is likely to increase its focus on its
businesses in the Upper Midwest and Northwest United States and
place greater emphasis on its consumer and small business services.
   The bank sold all of its non-trade-related loans to developing
countries in the third quarter to remove about $200 million of
non-performing loans from its books. But the bank said Monday that
its portfolio of non-performing domestic loans is growing.
   First Bank said it expects to write off about $45 million in
domestic loans in the third quarter, giving the institution a total
of about $330 million in non-performing loans compared with $294
million a year ago and $247 million at the end of the second quarter
of 1989.
   First Bank's announcement coincided with a statement Monday from
rival Norwest Corp. that it was expanding by acquiring First
Interstate Corp. of Wisconsin, the fifth largest bank holding
company in Wisconsin.
   At the end of 1988, First Bank had $14.8 billion in assets.
</TEXT>
