<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1254EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-GeneralMills     09-18 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-General Mills,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Operating Earnings Increase 18 Percent at General Mills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First-quarter earnings at General Mills Inc.
were only about half the year-ago level, but the food and restaurant
giant Monday posted an 18 percent gain in operating profit and 12
percent sales growth.
   For the 13 weeks ended Aug. 27, General Mills earned $114.9
million, or $1.39 a share. During the same period last year, the
company booked a profit of $218.8 million, or $2.66 a share, but the
results were skewed by a gain of $198.3 million from the sale of
specialty retailing businesses.
   That gain was partially offset by a $70 million charge for an
accounting change related to post-retirement health benefits.
   On an operating basis, the cereal maker and owner of Red Lobster
and Olive Garden restaurants made $107.2 million after tax in the
first quarter of fiscal 1990 compared with $90.5 million for the
same period a year before. Sales were up 12 percent to $1.5 billion
from $1.3 billion.
   Chairman Bruce Atwater attributed the operating gains partly to
General Mills' growing market share in breakfast cereals, where
rival Kellogg Co. of Battle Creek, Mich., has long been the dominant
force.
   Big G ready-to-eat cereals achieved a 27 percent market share
during the first quarter, up from the record 24.6 percent share of
the market recorded at the end of fiscal 1989.
   Much of the gain reflects the growth of Cheerios, which has
benefited from a health craze over oat bran and the introduction of
two new Cheerios flavors, Atwater said.
   Also in the foods division, strong sales gains were achieved by
Hamburger Helper, Bisquick, and Yoplait Light.
   Restaurants, which accounted for $46.5 million of the first
quarter operating profit, reported first-quarter gains in sales and
operating profit of 18 percent and 21 percent, respectively.
   Atwater said the emerging Olive Garden chain of Italian-style
restaurants reported a 50 percent sales gain and even faster growth
in earnings.
   The company plans to invest $600 million to open 250 new Red
Lobster and Olive Garden restaurants by the end of 1992, which
Atwater said will enable General Mills to increase restaurant sales
to about $2.6 billion, a gain of $1 billion over three years.
   General Mills also plans to spend $100 million this year to build
a cereal plant in Covington, Ga., as part of a $400 million,
three-year investment program that will increase the company's
cereal capacity by over 20 percent in the next 18 months, Atwater
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
