<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     09-18 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0313</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were mixed today in an atmosphere of
caution after the market's recent declines.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down about 77 points
over the past two weeks, rose 5.32 to 2,679.90 by 2 p.m. today on
Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 6 to 5 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 619 up, 752 down and
513 unchanged.
   Analysts said traders were reluctant to make any big commitments
either way while they kept a watchful eye on the market for
high-yield ``junk'' bonds.
   The market for those securities, commonly used to finance
takeovers and buyouts, has been rocked lately by problems at Campeau
Corp., which used debt to finance a coast-to-coast U.S. retailing
empire.
   If the junk bond market suffers a lasting loss of investor
confidence, brokers say, stocks might undergo a painful reappraisal
by traders no longer interested in chasing after takeover news and
rumors.
   Analysts also cited widespread talk that stocks were due for a
``correction,'' or short-term pullback, after their sharp rise over
the first eight months of the year.
   Gainers among the blue chips included American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph, up | at 41[; McDonald's, up { at 30\; General Electric,
up [ at 57], and Procter &amp; Gamble, up 2[ at 121[.
   Stratus Computer fell 6~ to 26| as the most active issue in the
over-the-counter market. The company said its sales and earnings for
the third quarter would fall short of expectations.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.18 to 191.77. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .82 at 378.82.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 88.92 million shares with two
hours to go.
