<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     09-18 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower in Europe, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell against major currencies in
slow European trading Monday. Gold rose about $5 an ounce.
   Foreign exchange dealers said they were reluctant to trade
because the direction of the dollar was uncertain after sharp
fluctuations Friday, when a narrower-than-expected U.S. trade
deficit for July was announced.
   Currency markets will be reluctant to make definite moves before
they see what happens at the weekend meeting in Washington of the
Group of Seven industrialized nations and central bankers, dealers
said.
   The group is made up of the United States, Japan, West Germany,
France, Britain, Italy and Canada.
   Dealers said they expected the markets to be quiet this week with
the dollar ranging between 1.9500 West German marks and 1.9800 West
German marks.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.5695 late Monday, over 3
cents more expensive for buyers than Friday's late $1.5390.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe compared to Friday's
late rates: 1.9525 West German marks, down from 2.0005; 1.6850 Swiss
francs, down from 1.7260; 6.5890 French francs, down from 6.7430;
2.2180 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2490; 1,417.40 Italian lire, down
from 1,433.50; 1.1834 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1880.
   Earlier in Tokyo the dollar closed at 146.43 Japanese yen, up
0.58 yen. Later in London, the dollar was quoted at 145.85 yen.
   Gold prices strengthened as the dollar declined but volume was
light.
   Gold closed in London at a bid $361.65 a troy ounce, up from
$356.25 late Friday. The closing price in Zurich was $361.00 bid, up
from $356.00.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $360.25, up from $360.00.
   Silver traded late in London at $5.08 bid a troy ounce, up from
$5.03.
</TEXT>
