<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1426EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Ferranti     09-18 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ferranti,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ferranti Says U.S. Subsidiary May Have Fraudulently Misreported Contracts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ferranti PLC, a British defense equipment and
electronics manufacturer, on Monday confirmed that its U.S.
subsidiary may have fraudulently misreported contracts to its parent
company.
   In a letter to employees, Ferranti Chairman Sir Derek Alun-Jones
said an investigation of contract irregularities at International
Signal &amp; Control, a Lancaster, Penn.-based defense equipment
company, so far suggested that Ferranti was ``at least misled and
possibly made the victim of serious fraud.''
   A copy of the letter was obtained by the AP-Dow Jones News
Service.
   The Sunday Times reported that the company might have to write
off the equivalent of $234 million or more against non-existent
contracts for which the company had previously believed it had been
paid.
   The newspaper also reported that International Signal &amp; Control
was being investigated for allegedly selling arms illegally in the
Middle East and South Africa. Ferranti officials declined to comment
on that report.
   Alun-Jones' letter said the problems under investigation ``affect
only a few transactions and are in no way connected with other
important contracts with specified customers in the Middle East or
elsewhere.''
   Britain's defense secretary, Tom King, said Monday, ``I am very
concerned and we hope these matters can be resolved at the earliest
possible date because they are an important defense contractor.''
   Ferranti executives left for the United States on Friday for
meetings, a Ferranti spokesman said Sunday.
   The company, based in Cheadle, England, announced Friday it
called in the accountants Coopers &amp; Lybrand to investigate
irregularities in its accounts.
   Trading in the company's shares was suspended last week and the
annual general meeting was postponed due to problems with the
accounts.
   The difficulties have prompted speculation that Ferranti would
become the target of a takeover.
   Ferranti merged with International Signal &amp; Control two years ago
in a $647 million deal.
   According to a report in The Sunday Times, the U.S. Justice
Department has been conducting a secret, two-year investigation into
International Signal &amp; Control over alleged illegal exports of arms
to customers in the Middle East and South Africa.
   Ferranti was warned of the questionable arms deals shortly after
the merger, unidentified British Ministry of Defense sources told
the Sunday Times.
   Among other things, Ferranti supplies fighter-jet radar systems
to British and foreign air forces. It also is involved in the
development of a new generation of mobile telephones.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
