<DOCNO> AP890918-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1530EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EPAList 18Takes   09-18 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EPA List, 18 Takes,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: This introductory take is in BODY; following 17 takes of tabular
matter are in AGATE. Also moved on general news wires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the Environmental Protection Agency's
fuel economy ratings for 1990 model year cars, vans and light trucks.
   The first column gives the manufacturer and the model. A ``D''
after the name indicates the vehicle has a diesel engine. A ``G''
after the name indicates the car was subject to the gas-guzzler tax.
   The second column shows miles per gallon in city driving.
   The third column shows miles per gallon in highway driving.
   The fourth column shows the overall combined miles per gallon.
   The fifth column gives the engine displacement in cubic inches
and the number of cylinders.
   The last column indicates the type of transmission and the number
of gears. For example, ``A4'' means a four-speed automatic and
``M5'' means a five-speed manual. Transmissions may carry identical
designations yet differ in some respect not shown here.
   Apparently identical listings may show different or identical
mileage ratings. This occurs because of something not shown on this
table, such as different types of transmissions or other equipment.
   For several years EPA has reduced the results of its mileage
tests by constant percentages in an attempt to more closely
correspond to results achieved on the road. The city mileage tests
are discounted by 10 percent and the highway tests are discounted by
22 percent. The combined mileage shown in this table is calculated
from the discounted city and highway ratings on the assumption that
55 percent of the miles driven are in the city.
   Turbochargers are not shown, unless indicated in the name of the
model.
   The size classifications are EPA's own, based on interior volume,
and do not confirm with size classifications in common use in the
auto industry.
   Some manufacturers may not have completed tests in time and their
cars are not listed.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
