<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Fall on Harvest Pressure, Slack Demand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices fell sharply
Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade, dragged down by harvest
pressure and a report the Soviet Union will import no more grain
this year.
   ``We were on the defensive all day,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a
trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Mild, dry weather in the Midwest over the weekend gave the corn
harvest a boost and provided ideal conditions for the maturing
soybean crop.
   Forecasts call for little change in the Midwestern weather for
most of this week.
   A news report out of Moscow that the Soviets have completed their
grain buying for 1989 put pressure on the wheat market. A similar
report surfaced last week.
   ``They might just be talking their position, trying to force
prices lower, but some people believed them,'' Lespinasse said.
   At the close, wheat futures were 1{ cents to 6} cents lower with
the contract for delivery in September at $3.82 a bushel; corn was }
cent to 2{ cents lower with September at $2.34\ a bushel; oats were
1} cents to 2{ cents lower with September at $1.35\ a bushel;
soybeans were 4 cents to 11 cents lower with September at $5.72{ a
bushel.
</TEXT>
