<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1658EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Mazda     09-18 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mazda,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>First U.S.-Made Mazda 626 Comes Off Assembly Line</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FLAT ROCK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mazda Motor Corp. on Monday began
manufacturing its 626 sedan at its plant south of Detroit, but the
factory's main product will continue to be the Ford Probe.
   Mazda officials said about 60 percent of the plant's
240,000-vehicle annual capacity will be Probes. About 25 percent
will be 626 four-door sedans and the rest MX-6 coupes.
   At times during the past year, Probes have taken up to 80 percent
of the plant's production.
   ``The long-term plan was a 60-40 split, with 60 percent Ford,''
said Mazda spokesman Jim Gill. ``We knew all along that in that 40
percent would be the sedan, we just didn't tell anybody.''
   Within the next two years, all 626 sedans sold in the United
States will be made at the Flat Rock plant. That will make room in
the company's voluntary import quota for the Miata, Mazda's
strong-selling two-seat roadster.
   The Flat Rock plant began making the MX-6 in September 1987 and
production of the Probe began the following January. The plant
employs about 3,500 people. It is the sole source for the Probe and
nearly all MX-6 coupes sold in the United States are made there.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
