<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1658EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-BanksMerge Bjt   09-18 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Banks Merge, Bjt,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>CoreStates, First Pennsylvania Agree to $714 Million Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CoreStates Financial Corp. and First
Pennsylvania Corp. agreed Monday to a $730 million merger that rival
Meridian Bancorp Inc. said was less than its own bid for First
Pennsylvania.
   The tax-free $18.75-a-share stock deal also ended an earlier
agreement for First Pennsylvania to be acquired next spring by
Marine Midland Banks Inc., the New York-based unit of Hongkong &amp;
Shanghai Banking Corp. of Hong Kong.
   The merger, subject to shareholder and regulatory approval, would
create a Philadelphia-based banking organization with nearly $23
billion in assets and leading positions in the mid-Atlantic region
in consumer, trust and credit card markets and in processing
financial transactions.
   The stock-for-stock deal includes all of First Pennsylvania's
nearly 39 million oustanding common shares and equivalents such as
convertible stock.
   First Pennsylvania spokesman Leslie R. Butler said Reading-based
Meridian had offered 0.93 shares of its stock for each of First
Pennsylvania's outstanding shares.
   Based on Meridian's closing price Friday of $22.375, that would
have amounted to about $20.875 a share, or about $813 million. The
actual value would have depended on the price of Meridian stock when
the deal was completed in six months, Butler said.
   Meridian spokeswoman Doris Piasecki would not confirm the terms
of the failed offer.
   ``We negotiated the transaction throughout the weekend,'' she
said. ``We were confident our higher bid would be a good bid.''
   CoreStates chairman Terrence A. Larsen said in a statement the
merger would create an unspecified number of jobs and result in no
layoffs. The deal is targeted for completion by the end of 1990.
   CoreStates said both dilution of per-share earnings in 1990 would
be limited to 6.8 percent, with a modest improvement in 1991 and a
strong rise by 1992.
   Under the plan, First Pennsylvania Bank N.A. would become an
operating subsidiary of CoreStates, retaining its name, as have
CoreStates' three existing full service banks _ Philadelphia
National, Hamilton and New Jersey National.
   Philadelphia National and First Pennsylvania banks would be
realigned to serve specific market segments in the Philadelphia
area. First Pennsylvania would serve primarily the retail and
small-business market, while Philadelphia National would focus on
wholesale commercial markets.
   Joel W. Silverstein, an analyst with The Advest Group in New
York, predicted investors would view the merger favorably.
   ``It will enhance their (the banks') market position in retail
banking and middle market commercial lending,'' he said.
   Trust operations of the merged companies would exceed $100
billion in administered assets and $70 million aggregate fees per
year, ranking CoreStates among the top 20 in the nation, Larsen said.
   CoreStates, based in Philadelphia since the founding of
Philadelphia National Bank in 1803, had total assets of $16.4
billion as of June 30. Its banking subsidiaries do commercial and
retail business through 201 domestic and foreign branches and 14
foreign representative offices.
   First Pennsylvania, the oldest commercial bank in the United
States, traces its roots to the National Bank of North America,
founded in 1782. The holding company's total assets June 30 were
$6.6 billion.
   If the merger is approved, First Pennsylvania Chairman George A.
Butler would become president of CoreStates, while Larsen would
remain chairman and chief executive officer.
   George Butler, who earlier had discussed retiring in early 1991,
agreed to postpone his retirement and remain as president until the
end of that year.
   Robert B. Palmer, vice chairman of CoreStates and president and
CEO of Philadelphia National Bank, would become president and CEO of
First Pennsylvania Bank. Frank E. Reed, president and chief
operating officer of First Pennsylvania Corp. and Bank, would be
president and CEO of Philadelphia National Bank.
   CoreStates' projections of savings and 1990 earnings dilution
were based on normal employee attrition rates in both companies and
on projected non-personnel savings, Larsen said.
   The projections included a ``very conservative'' estimate of
increases in revenues, but 80 percent of the dilution would be paid
through projected savings.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
