<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1731EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     09-18 0686</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0708</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocoa Futures Collapse On Failure Of Price-Support Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cocoa futures prices fell to new life-of-contract lows Monday on
New York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange following the
international cocoa cartel's failure to salvage a derailed
price-support scheme.
   On other markets, grain and soybean futures fell sharply;
livestock and meat futures were mixed; precious metals were lower;
and energy futures were mixed.
   Cocoa futures settled $54 to $67 lower with the contract for
delivery in December at $1,035 per metric ton. All contracts
established new lifetime lows.
   The price drop followed the conclusion Saturday of a fruitless
six-day meeting in London of the International Cocoa Organization,
whose approximately 40 nation-members were seeking to resolve
problems that have severely weakened the cartel's ability to support
cocoa prices.
   The ICCO, charged with stabilizing world cocoa prices by
maintaining a variable ``buffer stock'' of the commodity, has been
virtually powerless since February 1988, when the stockpile reached
its permitted 250,000-metric-ton limit.
   The organization also has been weakened by the refusal of some
the major cocoa producers to pay levies on their cocoa exports to
finance ICCO operations.
   The overall debt to the organization by its 12 producer members
now stands at $120 million. Cocoa producers say they cannot afford
the levies, due partly to the historically low price that cocoa
commands in a world market burdened by five straight years of
expanding supplies.
   Negotiators for the producer nations appeared to nearing a
unified position at the London meeting on Friday, prompting hope for
a solution to the ICCO's problems, and the meeting was extended
through Saturday. But discord ultimately prevailed, said Arthur
Stevenson, a cocoa market analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc. in New York.
   ``Some of the participants at the end didn't even bother to vote
_ they just walked out,'' he said. ``This means the International
Cocoa Organization cannot be viewed as even a psychological
price-support instrument because it is just not getting support from
its key members.''
   Further selling was prompted by indications that a proposed sale
of 500,000 metric tons of cocoa from the Ivory Coast, the world's
largest producer, to the trade house Philipp Brothers Inc. had
fallen through.
   Grain and soybean futures fell sharply on the Chicago Board of
Trade due to harvest pressure and a report the Soviet Union will
import no more grain in 1989.
   Wheat futures settled 1{ cents to 6{ cents lower with September
at $3.82\ a bushel; corn was } cent to 2\ cents lower with September
at $2.34\ a bushel; oats were 1} cents to 2\ cents lower with
September at $1.35\ a bushel; soybeans were 5 cents to 11\ cents
lower with September at $5.72\ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange ahead of a monthly Agriculture Department report
that showed 4 percent fewer cattle on feedlots as of Sept. 1 than on
the same date a year ago.
   The number was slightly lower than expected. But the USDA also
reported lighter-than-expected marketings of cattle off of feedlots
last month and analysts said they expected cattle prices to open
slightly lower Tuesday in reaction to that report.
   Live cattle futures settled .10 cent to .43 cent lower with
October at 72.02 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent lower to
.15 cent higher with September at 83.52 cents a pound; hogs were .02
cent to .68 cent higher with October at 41.65 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .03 cent to .20 cent lower with February at 48.20
cents a pound.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold settled $2.40 to $2.50
lower with October at $362.80 a troy ounce; silver was 2 cents to
2.2 cents lower with September at $5.063 a troy ounce.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, West Texas Intermediate
crude oil settled 5 cents to 8 cents lower with October at $19.88 a
barrel; heating oil was .23 cent lower to .01 cent higher with
October at 55.72 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was unchanged to
.52 cent higher with October at 58.13 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
