<FIRST>r f AM-Mexico-Telephones     09-18 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Telephones,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Vows State Regulation And Domestic Ownership In Phone Company</HEAD>
<HEAD>By TALLI NAUMAN</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Carlos Salinas de Gortari told
telephone company workers Monday that Mexican investors will get
majority control when the government sells most of its shares in the
phone company.
   The government currently owns a 56 percent stake in Telefonos de
Mexico, known as Telmex, and will continue to regulate the industry
after the sale, Salinas said.
   Salinas told about 500 union phone workers at their annual
meeting that he has ordered the Communications and Transportation
Department to release details of phone company privatization plans
within a week.
   In June, Telmex announced two alternatives for privatization in
which the government would retain 25 percent of the company.
   A rough draft of the government's proposal for the company calls
for 75 percent private ownership in order to double the system's
capacity within five years, the independent El Financiero business
newspaper reported Monday.
   Salinas said expansion and strengthening of research and
techonology are his administration's goals for the company, which
the government has controlled for 16 years.
</TEXT>
