<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1748EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     09-18 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Prices Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices ended mixed Monday in
fairly quiet trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   The October contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, fell 8 cents to $19.88 a barrel after
peaking at $20.07 during the session. The contract had risen 24
cents on Friday.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, the October
contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline picked up 0.52 cent to
close at 58.13 cents a gallon. Home heating oil for October delivery
declined 0.23 cent to 55.72 cents a gallon.
   Oil analysts said trading was featureless as participants began
to anticipate the coming meeting of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries on Saturday.
   ``The market is being cautious,'' said Larry Lawrence, manager of
options and technical analysis for Elders Futures Inc.
   OPEC's eight-member strategy and price-monitoring committee is
scheduled to meet in Geneva to discuss current market conditions as
well as future strategy.
   OPEC officials said after the group's meeting in June that the
September gathering might turn into a full meeting of all 13
ministers and could result in a further increase in the cartel's
production ceiling from 19.5 million barrels.
   But more recent speculation is that the committee will focus on
long-term price and production strategy and wait until later in the
year to change output levels.
   Oil prices have weakened since last spring as OPEC continues to
exceed its output ceiling, but prices have remained firmer than many
analysts predicted due to strong demand and perceptions that OPEC
was trying to rein in production.
   Nevertheless, many analysts believe the current market is
overbought and that prices could weaken more significantly if OPEC
fails to show at this weekend's meeting that it plans to act
decisively to contain overproduction.
</TEXT>
