<FIRST>r f AM-Cattle-Feedlots     09-18 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cattle-Feedlots,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inventories Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Table in BODY. Also on general news wires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cattle being fed for the slaughter market as of
Sept. 1 in the seven major beef states totaled 6.43 million head,
down 4 percent from a year ago and 6 percent below the level of two
years ago, the Agriculture Department said Monday.
   Marketings of fed cattle in August totaled 1.68 million head,
down 5 percent from a year ago and 2 percent below two years ago.
   Moreover, the placement of new cattle and calves in fattening
pens last month was reported at 1.62 million head, down 3 percent
from a year ago and 16 percent fewer than two years ago.
   The department's Economic Research Service says improved forage
conditions this summer have given producers the option of keeping
cattle on pastures instead of sending so many to feedlots.
   As of Sept. 1, feedlot inventories were smaller than a year
earlier in Arizona, California, Colorado, Kansas and Texas. Only
Iowa and Nebraska feedlots showed increases.
   State feedlot cattle inventories are listed here for the seven
states, which account for about three-fourths of the nation's beef.
The first number is the number of head, in thousands, as of Sept. 1,
and the second number is the percentage of a year earlier.
