<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     09-18 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down Again; Gold Also Falls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar dropped again Monday in the aftermath
of the panicky decline at the end of last week, hurt by traders'
fear of central-bank selling and the uncertain effect of an
impending meeting of finance ministers.
   Gold prices also fell following gains overseas. Republic National
Bank quoted gold at $360.70 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, vs.
$362.50 late Friday.
   Money traders said the foreign exchange market was quieter Monday
than last Friday, when wild rumors and price swings jolted traders
and wrenched down the dollar's value unexpectedly.
   Traders said that rout convinced other dollar holders to sell
their holdings Monday or at least avoid the market until the
currency's long-term outlook becomes clearer.
   ``The dollar bulls are hanging on the sidelines,'' said Michael
Guarino, vice president and chief dealer at the New York branch of
Algemene Bank Nederland NV, the largest Dutch bank.``The dollar
bears are taking over. They have the central banks in their favor.
That's going to add fuel to the fire.''
   The central banks of the United States and its principal trading
allies repeatedly have swooped into the foreign exchange markets
recently to sell large amounts of dollars in order to keep the
dollar from rising in value.
   A more expensive dollar partly reflects confidence in the U.S.
economy and the relatively high interest rates offered in this
country, which attract foreign investors. But as the dollar's value
rises, it hurts American manufacturers by making their products more
expensive overseas.
   Some traders said a meeting this weekend of finance ministers
from the so-called Group of Seven nations likely would reinforce the
group's resolve to keep the dollar at present levels or depress it
further. Others said it was impossible to speculate intelligently on
what the G-7 nations might do.
   ``At this point I dare say I wouldn't put my neck on the line. My
frame of mind is one minute to one hour,'' said Scott Horwitz,
senior foreign exchange trader at the Bank of Boston's New York
branch. ``I think we'll see the dollar trade in a range until we get
new direction from that meeting.''
   The G-7 members meeting in Washington include envoys from
Britain, Canada, France, Japan, Italy, the United States and West
Germany.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 146.43 Japanese yen, up 0.58 yen.
Later in London the dollar was quoted at 145.85 yen. By the time
trading concluded in New York the dollar fetched 145.93 yen, down
from 146.35 late Friday.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.5695 late Monday, more
expensive than the $1.5390 rate late Friday. Later in New York the
pound fetched $1.5710, more expensive than its $1.5660 rate late
Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York vs. late rates Friday: 1.9523
West German marks, down from 1.9660; 1.6840 Swiss francs, down from
1.6945; 1.1833 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1847; 6.5830 French
francs, down from 6.6295; and 1,404.50 Italian lire, down from
1,410.50.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared to Friday's rates: 1.9525
West German marks, down from 2.0005; 1.6850 Swiss francs, down from
1.7260; 6.5890 French francs, down from 6.7430; 2.2180 Dutch
guilders, down from 2.2490; 1,417.40 Italian lire, down from
1,433.50; and 1.1834 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1880.
   On the New York Commodity Exchange, gold bullion for current
delivery settled at $361.70 a troy ounce, down $2.20 from Friday.
   Earlier, gold closed in London at $361.65 an ounce, vs. $356.25
late Friday. The Zurich price was $361 vs. $356 and the Hong Kong
price was $360.25 vs. $360.
   Silver prices were mixed. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery fell to $5.063 a troy ounce from $5.084 Friday.
Silver rose in London to $5.08 an ounce from $5.03.
 
</TEXT>
