<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 2032EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-AutoAds     09-18 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Ads,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Introduces 1990 Ads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co., the leading light-truck seller for
three consecutive years, is steering clear of comparing its models
with the competitor's trucks in its new advertising, company
officials said Monday.
   Ford and Chevrolet trucks have been battling for sales supremacy
for years and Chevrolet ran a series of ads last year comparing its
trucks with Ford's in tugs of war, load hauling and switching to
four-wheel-drive in something Chevrolet tagged the ``Ditch of Doom.''
   John Vanderzee, advertising manager for the Ford division, said
Monday the company won't trade pot shots using Chevys in its 1990
commercials.
   In one ad for 1990, a heavy chain is locked to the bumper of a
hefty Ford four-wheel drive pickup, the truck begins to pull and an
announcer talks about engine size, power and competition.
   The truck at the other end of the chain, pulling equally hard,
also is a Ford rather than a competitor, and the announcer voices
the theme ``The toughest competition we have is ourselves.''
   ``One of the fundamental principles of advertising is when you
are the marketing leader you never mention the competition,''
Vanderzee said.
   Ford research indicates potential buyers want facts, not staged
competitions, he said.
   ``The consumers really believe these so-called stunts are not
what they want,'' Vanderzee said. ``We would like to think the
competition is going to get off their kick of taking us on.''
   Chevrolet, however, is continuing its comparison ads for 1990.
   Chevrolet sold more than 1.3 million light trucks compared with
Ford's total of more than 1.2 million in 1985 but Ford has led in
succeeding years.
   In 1986, Ford sold nearly 1.4 million trucks while Chevrolet sold
more than 1.2 million; in 1987, Ford sold more than 1.4 million
versus fewer than 1.2 million for Chevrolet, and in 1988, Ford sold
more than 1.5 million trucks to more than 1.3 million for Chevrolet,
according to Ford's figures.
   Although Ford's truck ads are keeping the gloves on, the
company's car ads aren't. There are pointed comparisons to features
and prices of competitors' models in television advertisements for
Escort, Festiva and Tempo cars.
   Two new vehicle introductions will boost Ford's advertising
budget for 1990, Vanderzee said, though he wouldn't give an overall
figure or a percentage increase.
   Ford's Explorer, a replacement for the Bronco II utility truck,
and a new Escort model both are scheduled for spring introduction.
   The new car and truck advertisements will debut Oct. 5 on
television, in magazines and newspapers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
