<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 2235EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Gulfstream-Soviets     09-18 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Gulfstream-Soviets,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gulfstream Officials Discuss Supersonic Jet with Soviets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet aerospace designers met Monday with
Gulfstream Aerospace Corp. officials to discuss a joint venture to
develop a supersonic corporate jet that would hold 10 to 12
passengers.
   Gulfstream and officials of Sukhoi Design Bureau said they hope
to develop a prototype of the jet within three years and begin
commercial manufacture in five years. Eventually, they said, they
may develop a ``stretch'' version that would seat up to 52
passengers.
   Under the joint venture, the Soviets would pick up all costs for
the project. Gulfstream, a unit of Chrysler Corp., would provide the
technology, developed in the design of its Gulfstream IV business
jet. Production and assembly would be completed in the Soviet Union.
   The venture was first announced at the Paris Air Show in June.
   V.M. Chepkin, general designer for the Soviet engine manufacturer
A.N. Lulka Design Bureau, made available slides of Soviet engine
designs that were top secret 18 months ago.
   Gulfstream Chairman Allen E. Paulson said part of the Soviet
interest in the $50 million project may stem from a need for foreign
currency.
   ``They need hard dollars desperately and don't mind spending
rubles to get them,'' Paulson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
